\n|footnotes              =\n}}\n\n'''Teston''' is a suburban neighbourhood and former [[hamlet (place)|hamlet]] located at the intersection of [[York Regional Road 49|Teston Road]] and Jane Street, in the City of [[Vaughan, Ontario|Vaughan]], [[Ontario]], at the northern edge of the city's developed area. The Teston United Church and some homes of early settlers are still standing to this day, but the rapid development of Vaughan has impacted the area in recent years.\n\nIn early 2005, the Teston United Church was unsuccessfully relocated, meaning that lifting and flotation to an alternate site could not be accomplished. Parts of the church were distributed before it was completely demolished.<ref>Peter Kuitenbrouwer, ''National Post'', [http://www.peacevillage.ca/_mgxroot/page_10755.html Giving Peace a chance in Muslim suburbia] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100609183943/http://www.peacevillage.ca/_mgxroot/page_10755.html |date=2010-06-09 }}, Oct. 6, 2007.</ref> The only visible remnants of the hamlet today run from Kleinberg to Keele Street, and continue east of Maple, eventually becoming Elgin Mills Road at Bathurst Street.\n\nIn 2010, a major archeological discovery was made on the south side of the road, as road crews discovered an aboriginal burial ground just east of Jane Street.<ref>Cf. Gail Swainson, ''Toronto Star'', [https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/article/854119--first-nations-want-say-in-the-preservation-of-important-archaeological-sites-in-ontario  First Nations want say in the preservation of important archaeological sites in Ontario], Aug. 29, 2010; [https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/article/856282--thousands-of-native-remains-being-held-in-u-of-t-storage U of T basements hold thousands of remains], Sept. 3, 2010; [https://www.thestar.com/news/gta/article/859013--first-nation-battles-for-history-in-court First Nation battles for history in court], Sept. 10, 2010.</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Vaughan}}\n{{coord|43|52|10|N|79|32|26|W|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:Neighbourhoods in Vaughan]]\n{{GoldenHorseshoe-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Rich Farmbrough", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Unabbreviate months", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Teston,_Ontario"}
{"title_page": "Paella", "text_new": "{{distinguish|paelya}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}{{Infobox food\n| name             = Paella\n| image            = File:01 Paella Valenciana original.jpg\n| caption          = ''Paella valenciana''\n| country          = [[Spain]]\n| region           = [[Valencian Community|Valencia]]\n| creator          =\n| course           = [[Main course]]\n| served           = warm\n| main_ingredient  = [[White rice|Short grain rice]], [[chicken]], [[rabbit]], [[vegetables]], [[saffron]]\n| calories         = \n| other            = \n|Related=[[Spanish cuisine]]}}\n\n'''Paella''' ({{IPAc-en|p|a\u026a|\u02c8|\u025b|l|\u0259}} {{respell|py|EL|\u0259}},{{refn|{{OxfordDictionaries.com|accessdate=22 January 2016|paella}}}} {{IPA-va|pa\u02c8e\u028ea|lang}}, {{IPA-es|pa\u02c8e\u028ea|lang}}) is a Spanish rice dish originally from [[Valencian Community|Valencia]].\n\nPaella is one of the best-known dishes in the [[Spanish cuisine]]. For this reason, it may be seen internationally as Spain's [[national dish]], but Spaniards almost unanimously consider it to be a dish from the [[Valencian community|Valencian region]]; those who live there, in turn, regard ''paella'' as one of their identifying symbols.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://en.comunitatvalenciana.com/taxonomy/term/25458|title=Paella, on the way to becoming a World Heritage Site|publisher=[[Generalitat Valenciana]]|access-date=19 February 2020|quote=''For the Region of Valencia, paella is much more than a recipe, it is a ritual and an icon of our culture.''}}</ref><ref> {{cite news|newspaper=Diario16|url=http://mediterraneo.diario16.com/la-paella-valenciana-quiere-patrimonio-la-humanidad|last=Panadero |first=Amparo |date=11 March 2019|title=La paella valenciana quiere ser Patrimonio de la Humanidad|access-date=19 February 2020|language=Spanish|quote=''En el caso de la paella valenciana, se trata de una tradici\u00f3n culinaria y social que constituye un icono de hospitalidad y un s\u00edmbolo de uni\u00f3n e identidad valencianas ...''}}</ref>\n\n''Paella'' takes its name from the wide, shallow traditional pan used to cook the dish on an open fire.  ''Paella'' means \"frying pan\" in [[Valencian]], Valencia's regional language.\n\nAs a dish, it may have ancient roots, but in its modern form it is traced back to the mid-19th century, in the rural area around the [[Albufera]] lagoon adjacent to the city of [[Valencia]], on the east coast of Spain.<ref name=\"Info about Paella on About.com\">{{cite web|url=http://spanishfood.about.com/od/maincourses/a/paella.htm |title=Info about Paella on About.com |publisher=Spanishfood.about.com |date=15 December 2009 |accessdate=19 February 2010}}</ref>\n\n'''''Paella valenciana''''' is the traditional paella of the [[Valencia Region|Valencia region]], believed to be the original recipe,<ref name=\"Saveur\">[http://www.saveur.com/article/Kitchen/The-Art-of-Paella Saveur, \"The Art of Paella\"] (accessed 21 July 2015)</ref> and consists of round grain rice<ref name=\"paellarecipes\">[https://paellarecipes.top/paella-rice/ Paella Rice] (accessed 12 April 2020)</ref>, ''bajoqueta'' and ''tavella'' (varieties of ''[[green bean]]s''), rabbit, chicken, sometimes duck, ''garrof\u00f3'' (a variety of [[Lima bean|lima or butter bean]]),<ref>[[Phaseolus lunatus]] L. var. macrocarpus Benth.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.la-bible-de-la-paella.fr/the-authentic-paella/official-ingredients-of-the-authentic-paella/the-garrofon/|access-date=5 September 2018|title=La Bible de la Paella: The Garrofon}}</ref> and optionally [[Snail#As food|snails]].  [[Artichoke]] hearts and stems may be used as seasonal ingredients.  Olive oil is used as a base, and [[saffron]] and (sometimes) whole [[Rosmarinus officinalis|rosemary]] branches are used as seasoning.\n\n'''''Paella de marisco''''' (seafood ''paella'') replaces meat with [[seafood]] and omits beans and green vegetables, while '''''paella mixta'''''  (mixed ''paella'') combines meat from [[livestock]], [[seafood]], [[vegetables]], and sometimes [[beans]], with the traditional rice.\n\nOther popular local variations of ''paella'' are cooked all through the Mediterranean area, the rest of Spain and internationally.\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Possible origins ===\n[[File:Bomba-Rice.jpg|right|thumb|Raw bomba rice]]\n[[Moors]] in [[Al-Andalus|Muslim Spain]] began rice cultivation around the 10th century.<ref>{{cite book|ref=Watson|author=Watson, Andrew |year=1983|title=Agricultural innovation in the early Islamic world|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=0-521-06883-5}}</ref> Consequently, eastern [[Iberian Peninsula|Iberian Pen\u00ednsula]] locals often made [[casserole]]s of rice, fish, and spices for family gatherings and [[religious feast]]s, thus establishing the custom of eating rice in Spain. This led to rice becoming a staple by the 15th century. Afterwards, it became customary for cooks to combine rice with vegetables, beans, and dry [[cod]], providing an acceptable meal for [[Lent]]. Along Spain's eastern coast, rice was predominantly eaten with fish.<ref name=\"foodtimeline.org\">{{cite web|author=Lynne Olver |url=http://www.foodtimeline.org/foodfaq6.html#paella |title=The Food Timeline presents a history of paella |publisher=Foodtimeline.org |date=16 September 2009 |accessdate=19 February 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"Jaine1989\">{{cite book|author=Tom Jaine|title=The Cooking Pot: Proceedings|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=U-SSnkfrLCkC&pg=PA104|year=1989|publisher=Oxford Symposium|isbn=978-0-907325-42-0|page=104}}</ref>\n\nSpanish [[food historian]] Lourdes March notes that the dish \"symbolizes the union and heritage of two important cultures, the [[Roman Empire|Roman]], which gives us the utensil and the [[Arab world|Arab]] which brought us the basic food of humanity for centuries.\"<ref>{{citation| first =Lourdes| last =March| chapter =Paella| pages =[https://archive.org/details/oxfordcompaniont00davi_0/page/566 566\u2013567]| title =The Oxford Companion to Food| series =| volume =| editor-first =Alan| editor-last =Davidson| location =Oxford| publisher =Oxford University Press| year =1999| isbn =0-19-211579-0| ref =none| url =https://archive.org/details/oxfordcompaniont00davi_0/page/566}}</ref>\n[[File:Paellera.jpg|thumb|The traditional pan known as ''paella'' or ''paellera,'' along with a traditional wooden spoon used to eat from it''.'']]\n\n===Naming, etymology and ''paellera''===\n''Paella'' is a Valencian word that means frying pan.<ref name=\"MerriamWebster2020\">{{cite web|url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/paella|title=Merriam Webster's definition and etymology of the word paella|date=|accessdate=8 June 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"AVL2020\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.avl.gva.es/lexicval/?paraula=paella|title=Diccionari normatiu valenci\u00e0|website=www.avl.gva.es|access-date=2019-11-02}}</ref><ref name=\"RAE2020\">{{cite web|url=https://dle.rae.es/?w=paella|title=Diccionario de la Real Academia Espa\u00f1ola's (DRAE) definition and etymology of Paella|date=|accessdate=11 October 2012}}</ref> The dish gets its name from it.<ref name=\"AVL2020\" /><ref name=\"RAE2020\" /> Valencian speakers use the word ''paella'' for all pans, including the traditional shallow pan used for cooking the [[homonym]] dish.<ref name=\"RAE2020\" /> The pan is made out of polished or coated steel with two side handles.''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lapaella.net/recipiente/|title=El recipiente|date=|publisher=Lapaella.net|access-date=19 February 2010}}</ref>''\n\nIn many regions of [[Spain]] and other [[Spanish-speaking countries]], the term ''paellera'' may be used for the traditional pan, while ''paella'' is reserved for the rice dish prepared in it. Both ''paella'' and ''paellera'' are correct terms for the pan.<ref>[http://buscon.rae.es/draeI/SrvltConsulta?TIPO_BUS=3&LEMA=paellera The Royal Spanish Academy's definition of '&#x27;paellera'&#x27;]. Buscon.rae.es. Retrieved on 5 October 2016.</ref>\n\nThe word ''paella'' may derive from the [[Old French]] word ''paelle''<ref name=\"MerriamWebster2020\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lexico.com/en/definition/paella|title=Paella {{!}} Definition of Paella by Lexico|website=Lexico Dictionaries {{!}} English|language=en|access-date=2019-11-02}}</ref> for [[frying pan]], which in turn comes from the [[Latin]] word ''patella'' for pan.\n\nThe word ''paella'' is also related to ''[[paila]]'' used in many [[Latin America]]n countries. ''Paila'' in [[Spanish dialects and varieties|Latin American Spanish]] refers to a variety of cookware resembling metal and [[clay]] pans, which are also used for both cooking and serving.\n\nThe Latin root ''patella'' from which ''paella'' derives is also akin to the [[French language|modern French]] ''po\u00eale'',<ref>[http://www.littre.org/definition/po%C3%AAle.3 Origin of '&#x27;po\u00eale'&#39]. Littre.org. Retrieved on 5 October 2016.</ref> the Italian ''padella,''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.etimo.it/?term=padella|title=Etimologia : padella;|work=etimo.it}}</ref> and the [[Old Spanish language|Old Spanish]] ''padilla''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spanishdict.com/translate/padilla#|title=Meaning of the Spanish word '&#39;padilla'&#39;|date=|publisher=Spanishdict.com|accessdate=19 February 2010}}</ref>\n\nSome claim that the word ''paella'' comes from the [[Arabic]] {{Lang|ar|\u0628\u064e\u0642\u064e\u0627\u064a\u064e\u0627}}, pronounced ''baqaayya'', meaning \"leftovers\".<ref>{{Citation|title=\u062d\u0643\u0627\u064a\u0629 \u0637\u0628\u0642 - \u0628\u0627\u0625\u064a\u064a\u0644\u0627 / \u0625\u0633\u0628\u0627\u0646\u064a\u0627|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QSDSjOeDqVY|language=en|access-date=2019-10-30}}</ref> This claim is based on the 8th-century custom in which [[Moorish]] kings' servants would take home the rice, chicken, and vegetables their employers left at the end of the meal.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.de/books?id=DX1NBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA192|title=Vibrant Andalusia: The Spice of Life in Southern Spain|last=Ruiz|first=Ana|date=2007|publisher=Algora Publishing|isbn=9780875865409|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.de/books?id=hHNS0NAK33AC&pg=PT51|title=Andalus: Unlocking The Secrets Of Moorish Spain|last=Webster|first=Jason|date=2010-08-03|publisher=Transworld|isbn=9781407094816|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.de/books?id=YD0hBQAAQBAJ&pg=PT62|title=Arab Women in the Middle Ages: Private Lives and Public Roles|last=Guthrie|first=Shirley|date=2013-08-01|publisher=Saqi|isbn=9780863567643|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.de/books?id=mB6aKnaqChMC&pg=PA26|title=Late Dinner: Discovering the Food of Spain|last=Richardson|first=Paul|date=2007-08-21|publisher=Simon and Schuster|isbn=9781416545392|language=en}}</ref> It has been said, however, that a problem with this etymology is that the word ''paella'' is not attested until six centuries after Moorish Valencia was conquered by [[Jaume I]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://www.raco.cat/index.php/RevistaEtnologia/article/download/81655/106249|title=Els espais socials de la paella: antropologia d\u2019un plat camale\u00f2nic|last=Duhart|first=Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric|last2=Medina|first2=F. Xavier|publisher=Revista d'etnologia de Catalunya|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=89}}</ref>\n\n===''Paella Valenciana''===\nOriginally, paella made in Valencia was a lunchtime meal for farmers and farm laborers.  Workers would gather what was available to them around the rice fields.  This often included tomatoes, onions, and snails.  Rabbit or duck was a common addition, or chicken less often.<ref>{{cite web |title=History and Origins of Paella |url=https://www.thepaellacompany.co.uk/history.html |website=The Paella Company |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn special occasions, 18th century Valencians used ''calderos'' to cook rice in the open air of their orchards near lake [[Albufera]]. [[Arvicola sapidus|Water vole]] meat was one of the main ingredients of early paellas,<ref>Manuel V\u00e1zquez Montalb\u00e1n, ''La cocina de los mediterr\u00e1neos'', Ediciones B \u2013 Mexico</ref> along with [[eel]] and [[White beans|butter beans]]. Novelist [[Vicente Blasco Ib\u00e1\u00f1ez]] described the Valencia custom of eating [[European water vole|water voles]] in ''Ca\u00f1as y Barro'' (1902), a realistic novel about life among the fishermen and peasants near lake Albufera.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucm.es/info/especulo/numero31/viblasco.html |title=C\u00e9sar Bes\u00f3 Portal\u00e9s, '&#39;Vicente Blasco Ib\u00e1\u00f1ez y el Naturalismo'&#39;, I.E.S. Clara Campoamor, Alaqu\u00e1s (Valencia) |publisher=Ucm.es |date= |accessdate=19 February 2010}}</ref>\n\nLiving standards rose with the sociological changes of the late 19th century in Spain, giving rise to gatherings and outings in the countryside. This led to a change in paella's ingredients, as well, using instead rabbit, chicken, duck and sometimes snails. This dish became so popular that in 1840, a local Spanish newspaper first used the word ''paella'' to refer to the recipe rather than the pan.<ref name=\"foodtimeline.org\" />\n\nThe most widely used, complete ingredient list of this era was: short-grain white rice, chicken, rabbit, snails (optional), duck (optional), [[White beans|butter beans]], [[White beans|great northern beans]], [[runner beans]], [[artichoke]] (a substitute for runner beans in the winter), [[tomato]]es, fresh rosemary, sweet [[paprika]], [[saffron]], [[garlic]] (optional), salt, olive oil, and water.<ref name=\"foodtimeline.org\" /> Poorer Valencians, however, sometimes used nothing more than snails for meat. Valencians insist that only these ingredients should go into making modern ''paella valenciana''.\n\n=== Seafood and mixed ''paella''===\nOn the [[Mediterranean Sea|Mediterranean]] coast, Valencians used seafood instead of meat and beans to make paella. Valencians regard this recipe as authentic, as well. In this recipe, the seafood is served in the shell. A variant of this is ''paella del senyoret'' which uses seafood without shells. Later, however, Spaniards living outside of Valencia combined seafood with meat from land animals and mixed ''paella'' was born.<ref name=\"arrozsos.com\">{{cite web |author=Tu nombre |url=http://www.arrozsos.com/articulos/ver/historia_de_la_paella |title=Arroz SOS presents a history of paella |publisher=Arrozsos.com |accessdate=19 February 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100125102334/http://www.arrozsos.com/Articulos/ver/historia_de_la_paella |archivedate=25 January 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> This ''paella'' is sometimes called ''preparaci\u00f3n barroca'' (baroque preparation) due to the variety of ingredients and its final presentation.<ref>{{cite web|title=Nuestras Paellas|url=http://www.pacharan.com.uy/platos/paellas/|website=Pachar\u00e1n|accessdate=2 September 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151116111929/http://www.pacharan.com.uy/platos/paellas/|archivedate=16 November 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nDuring the 20th century, paella's popularity spread past Spain's borders. As other cultures set out to make paella, the dish invariably acquired regional influences. Consequently, ''paella'' recipes went from being relatively simple to including a wide variety of seafood, meat, sausage (including [[chorizo]]),<ref>[http://www.oprah.com/food/Paella Mario Batali's version of mixed paella with chorizo] Oprah.com: Retrieved 30 June 2011</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Recipe courtesy Tyler Florence |url=http://www.foodnetwork.com/recipes/tyler-florence/paella-with-seafood-chicken-and-chorizo-recipe/index.html |title=Foodnetwork's paella recipe with seafood, chicken and chorizo |publisher=Foodnetwork.com |date= |accessdate=19 February 2010}}</ref> vegetables and many different seasonings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spain-recipes.com/paellarecipes.html |title=An assortment of paella recipes |publisher=Spain-recipes.com |date= |accessdate=19 February 2010}}</ref> However, the most globally popular recipe is seafood paella.\n\nThroughout non-Valencia Spain, mixed ''paella'' is relatively easy to find. Some restaurants both in Spain and abroad that serve this mixed version refer to it as ''Paella valenciana''. However, Valencians insist that only the original two Valencia recipes are authentic, and generally view all others as inferior, not genuine or even grotesque.<ref name=\"arrozsos.com\" />[[File:Paella hirviendo.jpg|thumb|Traditional preparation of paella]]\n\n== Basic cooking methods ==\nAccording to tradition in [[Valencia]], ''paella'' is cooked over an open fire, fueled by orange and pine branches along with pine cones.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/go/london/restaurants/quique-dacosta-arros-qd-restaurant-london-a4160206.html|title=Arros QD's Quique Dacosta on why paella will be the dish of the summer|date=2019-06-05|website=Evening Standard|language=en|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref> This produces an aromatic smoke which infuses the ''paella''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/food-and-drink/features/michelin-starred-chef-quique-dacosta-make-ultimate-paella/|title=Michelin-starred chef Quique Dacosta on how to make the ultimate paella|last=Curtis|first=Nick|date=2019-06-02|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2019-12-18|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>  Also, dining guests traditionally eat directly out of the pan instead of serving in plates.<ref name=\"Info about Paella on About.com\" /><ref name=\"foodtimeline.org\" /><ref name=\"arrozsos.com\" /><ref name=\"paellarecipes.top\">{{cite web|url=https://paellarecipes.top/paella-valenciana-recipe/ |title=Authentic Paella Valenciana as it is made in Valencia |publisher=paellarecipes.top |date= |accessdate=23 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nSome recipes call for ''paella'' to be covered and left to settle for five to ten minutes after cooking.\n\nAfter cooking ''paella'', there may be a layer of roasted rice at the bottom of the pan, called ''socarrat'' in [[Valencian|Valenci\u00e0]]. The layer develops on its own if the ''paella'' is cooked over a burner or open fire. This is traditionally considered positive (for as long as it is not scorched) and [[Valencia]] natives enjoy eating it.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/dbf555ec-b7da-11e9-96bd-8e884d3ea203|title=My kitchen essential: I\u2019d be lost without . . . my paella pan|last=Dacosta|first=Quique|date=2019-08-06|website=www.ft.com|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref>\n\n===''Paella valenciana''===\n{{cookbook|Paella Valenciana}}\n[[File:01 Paella Valenciana original.jpg|thumb|''Paella valenciana'']]\n\nThis recipe is standardized<ref name=\"paellarecipes.top\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://galbis.com/w/principal-paella-galbis-uk.htm |title=Restaurante Galbis \u2013 Restaurante,restaurantes L'alcudia \u2013 Valencia |work=waybackmachine.org |url-status=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090420125108/http://galbis.com/w/principal-paella-galbis-uk.htm |archivedate=20 April 2009 }}</ref><ref>Marqu\u00e8s, Vicent (2004): ''Els millors arrossos valencians''. Aldaia: Edicions Alfani.</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jasonwebstersblog.com/2010/12/how-to-make-real-paella.html |title=Author Jason Webster's method for making Valencian paella |publisher=jasonwebstersblog.com |accessdate=28 December 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110713090839/http://www.jasonwebstersblog.com/2010/12/how-to-make-real-paella.html |archivedate=13 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> because [[Valencia]] originals consider it traditional and very much part of their culture. Rice in ''paella valenciana'' is never [[braised]] in oil, as [[pilaf]], though the ''paella'' made further southwest of Valencia often is.\n\n*Heat oil in a ''paella''.\n*[[Saut\u00e9]] meat after seasoning with salt.\n*Add green vegetables and saut\u00e9 until soft.\n*Add garlic (optional), grated tomatoes, beans and saut\u00e9.\n*Add paprika and saut\u00e9.\n*Add water, saffron (or food coloring), snails (optional) and rosemary.\n*Boil to make [[broth]] and allow it to reduce by half.\n*Remove the rosemary once flavour has infused or it starts to fall apart.\n*Add rice and simmer until rice is cooked.\n\nSome people enjoy garnishing their served plate with freshly squeezed lemon.\n\n===''Paella de marisco'' (Seafood ''paella'') ===\n{{Cookbook|Paella de Marisco}}\n[[File:Paella de marisco 01.jpg|thumb|Seafood paella]]\n\nRecipes for this dish vary somewhat, even in Valencia. The recipe below is based on the two cited here.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ApmHP6uTg3Y&t=16s|title=Chef Juanry Segui's recipe for seafood paella |publisher=YouTube |date= |accessdate=27 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1ciBy9uX5Ts|title=Recipe for seafood paella |publisher=YouTube |date= |accessdate=27 February 2017}}</ref>\n*Make a seafood broth from shrimp heads, onions, garlic and bay leaves.\n*Heat oil in a ''paella''.\n*Add mussels. Cook until they open and then remove.\n*Saut\u00e9 [[Norway lobster]] and whole, deep-water rose shrimp. Then remove both the lobster and shrimp.\n*Add chopped [[cuttlefish]] and saut\u00e9.\n*Add shrimp tails and saut\u00e9.\n*Add garlic and saut\u00e9.\n*Add grated tomato and saut\u00e9.\n*Add rice and braise in [[sofrito]].\n*Add paprika and saut\u00e9.\n*Add seafood broth and then saffron (or food coloring).\n*Add salt to taste.\n*Add the deep-water rose shrimp, mussels and Norway lobster that were set aside.\n*Simmer until rice is cooked.\n\n===''Paella mixta'' (Mixed ''paella'')  ===\n{{cookbook|Paella Roja}}\n[[File:Red paella with mussels.jpg|thumb|Mixed paella]]\n\nThere are countless mixed ''paella'' recipes. The following method is common to most of these. Seasoning depends greatly on individual preferences and regional influences. However, salt, saffron, and garlic are almost always included.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spain-recipes.com/mixed-paella.html |title=Mixed paella recipe |publisher=Spain-recipes.com |date= |accessdate=19 February 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QuCmO3Zlbng |title=A Spanish grandmother near Madrid cooks her mixed paella recipe on video |publisher=Youtube.com |date= |accessdate=19 February 2010}}</ref><ref>[http://www.hayrecetas.com/paella-mixta/6431 Mixed paella recipe on the '&#39;Hay Recetas'&#39; website]. Hayrecetas.com. Retrieved on 5 October 2016.</ref>\n*Make a broth from seafood, chicken, onions, garlic, bell peppers, and bay leaf.\n*Heat oil in a ''paella''.\n*Sear red bell pepper strips and set aside.\n*Sear [[crustacean]]s and set aside.\n*Season meat lightly with salt and saut\u00e9 meat until golden brown.\n*Add onions, garlic and bell peppers. Saut\u00e9 until vegetables are tender.\n*Add grated tomatoes and saut\u00e9.\n*Add dry seasonings except for salt.\n*Add rice.\n*Braise rice until covered with sofrito.\n*Add broth.\n*Add salt to taste.\n*Add saffron (or food coloring) and mix well.\n*Simmer until rice is almost cooked.\n*Replace crustaceans.\n*Continue simmering until rice and crustaceans are finished cooking.\n*Garnish with seared red bell pepper strips.\n\n== Variants ==\n=== Philippines ===\n{{Main|Arroz a la valenciana}}\n''Arroz a la valenciana'' (Spanish) or ''Arroz \u00e0 valenciana'' ([[Portuguese language|Portuguese]]) is considered as a part of [[Cuisine of the Philippines|Philippine cuisine]]. It is considered as the Philippine version of [[paella]].<ref>https://www.saveur.com/philippine-seafood-paella-recipe/</ref>\n\nThe Philippine version uses [[glutinous rice]], otherwise the ingredients are the same. In the Philippines, ''arroz a la valenciana'' refers to chicken, and ''[[longganisa]]'' (''chorizo'') versions.<ref name=\"ppmrvalenciana\">{{cite web |title=Arroz Valenciana Recipe |url=https://www.pinoyrecipe.net/arroz-valenciana-recipe/ |website=Pinoy Recipe At Iba Pa|accessdate=13 August 2011}}</ref>\n\n== In popular culture ==\n[[File:Un granito por Haiti.jpg|thumb|Giant ''paella'' being served]]\n\n=== Competitions and records ===\n\nIt has become a custom at mass gatherings in the [[Valencian Community|Valencia region]] (festivals, political campaigns, protests, etc.) to prepare enormous paellas, sometimes to win a place in the ''[[Guinness World Records]]'' book. Chefs use gargantuan ''paelleras'' for these events.\n\n[[Valencia]] restaurateur Juan Galbis claims to have made the world's largest ''paella'' with help from a team of workers on 2 October 2001. This ''paella'' fed about 110,000 people according to Galbis' former website.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.paellagigante.com/|title=Paellas gigantes \u2013 Catering y paellas para eventos \u2013 Comidas gigantes|work=Paellas Gigantes}}</ref> Galbis says this ''paella'' was even larger than his earlier world-record ''paella'' made on 8 March 1992 which fed about 100,000 people. Galbis' record-breaking 1992 ''paella'' is listed in ''Guinness World Records''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/news/2007/10/071030.aspx |title=Galbis's 1992 record listed on the Guinness website |publisher=Guinnessworldrecords.com |date= |accessdate=19 February 2010}}</ref>\n\n=== Controversial representations ===\nSome non-Spanish [[chef]]s include chorizo in their paellas along with other ingredients which Valencia people believe do not belong in ''paella'' of any type. The alternative name proposed for these dishes, although pejorative, is {{lang|es|arroz con cosas}} ('rice with things'). Famous cases are [[Jamie Oliver]]'s ''paella'' recipe (which included [[chorizo]])<ref>Oliver, Jamie. (16 September 2015) [http://www.jamieoliver.com/recipes/rice-recipes/chicken-chorizo-paella/ Chicken & chorizo paella | Rice Recipes]. Jamie Oliver. Retrieved on 2016-10-05.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-37555389|title=Jamie Oliver's paella recipe is panned online|website=[[BBC News]]|publisher=[[BBC]]|date=30 October 2014|access-date=5 January 2016}}</ref> and [[Gordon Ramsay]]'s.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Vega|first1=Ana|title=Chefs que destrozan la comida espa\u00f1ola|url=http://elcomidista.elpais.com/elcomidista/2016/02/26/articulo/1456475765_337785.html|accessdate=5 October 2016|work=[[El Pa\u00eds]]|issue=El Comidista|date=2 March 2016|language=es}}</ref> The author Josep Pla once noted:\n\n{{Quote|text=The abuses committed in the name of Paella Valenciana, are excessive \u2013 an absolute scandal. |author=Josep Pla |source=Catalan Cuisine, Revised Edition: Vivid Flavors From Spain's Mediterranean Coast }}\n\nHowever, in an article for [[El Pa\u00eds]], Spanish food writer Ana Vega 'Biscayenne', citing historical references, showed that traditional Valencian paella did indeed include chorizo, exclaiming, \"Ah Jamie, we'll have to invite you to the [[Falles]]\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Vega|first1=Ana|title=La paella s\u00ed llevaba chorizo|url=https://elcomidista.elpais.com/elcomidista/2016/10/13/articulo/1476372723_268242.html|access-date=13 June 2018|work=[[El Pa\u00eds]]|issue=El Comidista|date=14 October 2016|language=es}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Noto Emoji Pie 1f958.svg|thumb|''Paella'' UNICODE emoji]]\n\n===Emoji===\nIn 2015, an [[emoji]] for ''paella'' was proposed to [[Unicode]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.unicode.org/L2/L2015/15055-paella-emoji.pdf|title=ISO/IEC JTC 1/SC 2/WG 2 PROPOSAL SUMMARY FORM TO ACCOMPANY SUBMISSIONS FOR ADDITIONS TO THE REPERTOIRE OF ISO/IEC 10646 1|last=Gonzalez Capella|first=Antonio|date=1 February 2015|work=[[Unicode]]|accessdate=10 March 2017}}</ref> The [[emoji]] was approved for Unicode 9.0 as {{code|U+1F958 \"SHALLOW PAN OF FOOD\"}} in June 2016. Although it is generally rendered as paella, [[Samsung]] has rendered the symbol as a Korean [[hot pot]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://emojipedia.org/shallow-pan-of-food/|title=Paella Emoji|publisher=[[Emojipedia]]|accessdate=10 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Related dishes ==\n{{cookbook|Arroz Negro}}\n[[File:arroz-negro.png|thumb|''[[Arr\u00f2s negre]]'' (also called ''arroz negro'' and ''paella negra'')]]\n\nTraditional [[Valencian cuisine|Valencia cuisine]] offers recipes similar to ''paella valenciana'' and ''paella de marisco'' such as ''[[arr\u00f2s negre]]'', ''arr\u00f2s al forn'', ''arr\u00f2s a banda'' and ''arr\u00f2s amb fesols i naps'', since rice is the base of lots of local cuisine''.''\n\n[[Fideu\u00e0]] is a [[pasta]] noodle dish variation cooked in a similar fashion in a ''paella''. It may be served with [[aioli|allioli]] sauce.\n\n===''Paella'' descendants===\n*[[Arroz a la valenciana]] \u2013 Latin American and Filipino adaptation of meat ''paella'', uses [[annatto]] instead of [[saffron]]\n*[[Arroz con gandules]] \u2013 Puerto Rican adaptation, also uses annatto\n*[[Arroz con pollo]] \u2013 Latin American adaptation with chicken, also uses annatto\n*[[Bringhe]] \u2013 Filipino adaptation of ''paella'' with [[glutinous rice]] and [[coconut milk]], uses [[turmeric]]\n*[[Jambalaya]] \u2013 Louisiana dish influenced by ''paella'' and the French ''jambalaia'' from [[Provence]]\n*[[Locrio]] \u2013 Dominican descendant of paella.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dominicancooking.com/509-locrio-de-pollo-rice-and-chicken.html|title=Locrio de Pollo|author=Aunt Clara's Kitchen|accessdate=2014-03-18}}</ref>\n*[[Paelya]] \u2013 Filipino adaptation of ''paella'' that distinctively use glutinous rice, also uses annatto, [[turmeric]], or [[safflower]]. Also spelled \"''paella''\", but pronounced differently.<ref name=\"ppmrvalenciana2\">{{cite web |title=Arroz Valenciana |url=http://www.panlasangpinoymeatrecipes.com/arroz-a-la-valenciana.htm |website=Panlasang Pinoy Meaty Recipes |accessdate=14 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Other dishes===\n*[[Arr\u00f2s negre]] \u2013 sometimes called \"''paella negra''\", a similar Catalonia and Valencia dish using squid ink\n*[[Biryani]] \u2013 a similar dish from the Indian subcontinent\n*[[Bisi Bele Bath]] \u2013 a similar dish from India\n*[[Jollof rice]] \u2013 a similar dish from West Africa\n*[[Kabsa]] \u2013 a similar dish from the Middle East\n*[[Pilaf]] \u2013 a similar dish from Central Asia\n*[[Risotto]] \u2013 similar northern Italian dish\n*[[Thieboudienne]] \u2013 a similar dish from Mauritania and Senegal\n\n== See also ==\n{{portal|Spain|Food}}\n* [[Arroz a la valenciana]]\n* [[List of rice dishes]]\n* [[Mediterranean cuisine]]\n* [[Spanish cuisine]]\n* [[Risotto]]\n* [[Pilaf]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite book |last = March |first = Lourdes  |year = 1985 |title = El Libro De La Paella Y De Los Arroces |publisher = Alianza| location = Madrid |isbn = 8420601012 }}\n*{{cite book |last = R\u00edos |first = Alicia and Lourdes March |year = 1992 |title = The Heritage of Spanish Cooking |publisher = Random House |location = New York |isbn = 0-679-41628-5 |url = https://archive.org/details/heritageofspanis0000rios }}\n\n{{Commons category|Paella}}\n{{Culture of Valencian Community}}\n{{Rice dishes}}\n\n[[Category:Valencian cuisine]]\n[[Category:Spanish cuisine]]\n[[Category:Spanish rice dishes]]\n[[Category:Seafood dishes]]\n[[Category:National dishes]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|paelya}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2016}}{{Infobox food\n| name             = Paella\n| image            = File:01 Paella Valenciana original.jpg\n| caption          = ''Paella valenciana''\n| country          = [[Spain]]\n| region           = [[Valencian Community|Valencia]]\n| creator          =\n| course           = [[Main course]]\n| served           = warm\n| main_ingredient  = [[White rice|Short grain rice]], [[chicken]], [[rabbit]], [[vegetables]], [[saffron]]\n| calories         = \n| other            = \n|Related=[[Spanish cuisine]]}}\n\n'''Paella''' ({{IPAc-en|p|a\u026a|\u02c8|\u025b|l|\u0259}} {{respell|py|EL|\u0259}},{{refn|{{OxfordDictionaries.com|accessdate=22 January 2016|paella}}}} {{IPA-va|pa\u02c8e\u028ea|lang}}, {{IPA-es|pa\u02c8e\u028ea|lang}}) is a Spanish rice dish originally from [[Valencian Community|Valencia]].\n\nPaella is one of the best-known dishes in the [[Spanish cuisine]]. For this reason, it may be seen internationally as Spain's [[national dish]], but Spaniards almost unanimously consider it to be a dish from the [[Valencian community|Valencian region]]; those who live there, in turn, regard ''paella'' as one of their identifying symbols.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://en.comunitatvalenciana.com/taxonomy/term/25458|title=Paella, on the way to becoming a World Heritage Site|publisher=[[Generalitat Valenciana]]|access-date=19 February 2020|quote=''For the Region of Valencia, paella is much more than a recipe, it is a ritual and an icon of our culture.''}}</ref><ref> {{cite news|newspaper=Diario16|url=http://mediterraneo.diario16.com/la-paella-valenciana-quiere-patrimonio-la-humanidad|last=Panadero |first=Amparo |date=11 March 2019|title=La paella valenciana quiere ser Patrimonio de la Humanidad|access-date=19 February 2020|language=Spanish|quote=''En el caso de la paella valenciana, se trata de una tradici\u00f3n culinaria y social que constituye un icono de hospitalidad y un s\u00edmbolo de uni\u00f3n e identidad valencianas ...''}}</ref>\n\n''Paella'' takes its name from the wide, shallow traditional pan used to cook the dish on an open fire.  ''Paella'' means \"frying pan\" in [[Valencian]], Valencia's regional language.\n\nAs a dish, it may have ancient roots, but in its modern form it is traced back to the mid-19th century, in the rural area around the [[Albufera]] lagoon adjacent to the city of [[Valencia]], on the east coast of Spain.<ref name=\"Info about Paella on About.com\">{{cite web|url=http://spanishfood.about.com/od/maincourses/a/paella.htm |title=Info about Paella on About.com |publisher=Spanishfood.about.com |date=15 December 2009 |accessdate=19 February 2010}}</ref>\n\n'''''Paella valenciana''''' is the traditional paella of the [[Valencia Region|Valencia region]], believed to be the original recipe,<ref name=\"Saveur\">[http://www.saveur.com/article/Kitchen/The-Art-of-Paella Saveur, \"The Art of Paella\"] (accessed 21 July 2015)</ref> and consists of round grain rice<ref name=\"paellarecipes\">[https://paellarecipes.top/paella-rice/ Paella Rice] (accessed 12 April 2020)</ref>, ''bajoqueta'' and ''tavella'' (varieties of ''[[green bean]]s''), rabbit, chicken, sometimes duck, ''garrof\u00f3'' (a variety of [[Lima bean|lima or butter bean]]),<ref>[[Phaseolus lunatus]] L. var. macrocarpus Benth.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.la-bible-de-la-paella.fr/the-authentic-paella/official-ingredients-of-the-authentic-paella/the-garrofon/|access-date=5 September 2018|title=La Bible de la Paella: The Garrofon}}</ref> and optionally [[Snail#As food|snails]].  [[Artichoke]] hearts and stems may be used as seasonal ingredients.  Olive oil is used as a base, and [[saffron]] and (sometimes) whole [[Rosmarinus officinalis|rosemary]] branches are used as seasoning.\n\n'''''Paella de marisco''''' (seafood ''paella'') replaces meat with [[seafood]] and omits beans and green vegetables, while '''''paella mixta'''''  (mixed ''paella'') combines meat from [[livestock]], [[seafood]], [[vegetables]], and sometimes [[beans]], with the traditional rice.\n\nOther popular local variations of ''paella'' are cooked all through the Mediterranean area, the rest of Spain and internationally.\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Possible origins ===\n[[File:Bomba-Rice.jpg|right|thumb|Raw bomba rice]]\n[[Moors]] in [[Al-Andalus|Muslim Spain]] began rice cultivation around the 10th century.<ref>{{cite book|ref=Watson|author=Watson, Andrew |year=1983|title=Agricultural innovation in the early Islamic world|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=0-521-06883-5}}</ref> Consequently, eastern [[Iberian Peninsula|Iberian Pen\u00ednsula]] locals often made [[casserole]]s of rice, fish, and spices for family gatherings and [[religious feast]]s, thus establishing the custom of eating rice in Spain. This led to rice becoming a staple by the 15th century. Afterwards, it became customary for cooks to combine rice with vegetables, beans, and dry [[cod]], providing an acceptable meal for [[Lent]]. Along Spain's eastern coast, rice was predominantly eaten with fish.<ref name=\"foodtimeline.org\">{{cite web|author=Lynne Olver |url=http://www.foodtimeline.org/foodfaq6.html#paella |title=The Food Timeline presents a history of paella |publisher=Foodtimeline.org |date=16 September 2009 |accessdate=19 February 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"Jaine1989\">{{cite book|author=Tom Jaine|title=The Cooking Pot: Proceedings|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=U-SSnkfrLCkC&pg=PA104|year=1989|publisher=Oxford Symposium|isbn=978-0-907325-42-0|page=104}}</ref>\n\nSpanish [[food historian]] Lourdes March notes that the dish \"symbolizes the union and heritage of two important cultures, the [[Roman Empire|Roman]], which gives us the utensil and the [[Arab world|Arab]] which brought us the basic food of humanity for centuries.\"<ref>{{citation| first =Lourdes| last =March| chapter =Paella| pages =[https://archive.org/details/oxfordcompaniont00davi_0/page/566 566\u2013567]| title =The Oxford Companion to Food| series =| volume =| editor-first =Alan| editor-last =Davidson| location =Oxford| publisher =Oxford University Press| year =1999| isbn =0-19-211579-0| ref =none| url =https://archive.org/details/oxfordcompaniont00davi_0/page/566}}</ref>\n[[File:Paellera.jpg|thumb|The traditional pan known as ''paella'' or ''paellera,'' along with a traditional wooden spoon used to eat from it''.'']]\n\n===Naming, etymology and ''paellera''===\n''Paella'' is a Valencian word that means frying pan.<ref name=\"MerriamWebster2020\">{{cite web|url=http://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/paella|title=Merriam Webster's definition and etymology of the word paella|date=|accessdate=8 June 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"AVL2020\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.avl.gva.es/lexicval/?paraula=paella|title=Diccionari normatiu valenci\u00e0|website=www.avl.gva.es|access-date=2019-11-02}}</ref><ref name=\"RAE2020\">{{cite web|url=https://dle.rae.es/?w=paella|title=Diccionario de la Real Academia Espa\u00f1ola's (DRAE) definition and etymology of Paella|date=|accessdate=11 October 2012}}</ref> The dish gets its name from it.<ref name=\"AVL2020\" /><ref name=\"RAE2020\" /> Valencian speakers use the word ''paella'' for all pans, including the traditional shallow pan used for cooking the [[homonym]] dish.<ref name=\"RAE2020\" /> The pan is made out of polished or coated steel with two side handles.''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lapaella.net/recipiente/|title=El recipiente|date=|publisher=Lapaella.net|access-date=19 February 2010}}</ref>''\n\nIn many regions of [[Spain]] and other [[Spanish-speaking countries]], the term ''paellera'' may be used for the traditional pan, while ''paella'' is reserved for the rice dish prepared in it. Both ''paella'' and ''paellera'' are correct terms for the pan.<ref>[http://buscon.rae.es/draeI/SrvltConsulta?TIPO_BUS=3&LEMA=paellera The Royal Spanish Academy's definition of '&#x27;paellera'&#x27;]. Buscon.rae.es. Retrieved on 5 October 2016.</ref>\n\nThe word ''paella'' may derive from the [[Old French]] word ''paelle''<ref name=\"MerriamWebster2020\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lexico.com/en/definition/paella|title=Paella {{!}} Definition of Paella by Lexico|website=Lexico Dictionaries {{!}} English|language=en|access-date=2019-11-02}}</ref> for [[frying pan]], which in turn comes from the [[Latin]] word ''patella'' for pan.\n\nThe word ''paella'' is also related to ''[[paila]]'' used in many [[Latin America]]n countries. ''Paila'' in [[Spanish dialects and varieties|Latin American Spanish]] refers to a variety of cookware resembling metal and [[clay]] pans, which are also used for both cooking and serving.\n\nThe Latin root ''patella'' from which ''paella'' derives is also akin to the [[French language|modern French]] ''po\u00eale'',<ref>[http://www.littre.org/definition/po%C3%AAle.3 Origin of '&#x27;po\u00eale'&#39]. Littre.org. Retrieved on 5 October 2016.</ref> the Italian ''padella,''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.etimo.it/?term=padella|title=Etimologia : padella;|work=etimo.it}}</ref> and the [[Old Spanish language|Old Spanish]] ''padilla''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spanishdict.com/translate/padilla#|title=Meaning of the Spanish word '&#39;padilla'&#39;|date=|publisher=Spanishdict.com|accessdate=19 February 2010}}</ref>\n\nSome claim that the word ''paella'' comes from the [[Arabic]] {{Lang|ar|\u0628\u064e\u0642\u064e\u0627\u064a\u064e\u0627}}, pronounced ''baqaayya'', meaning \"leftovers\".<ref>{{Citation|title=\u062d\u0643\u0627\u064a\u0629 \u0637\u0628\u0642 - \u0628\u0627\u0625\u064a\u064a\u0644\u0627 / \u0625\u0633\u0628\u0627\u0646\u064a\u0627|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QSDSjOeDqVY|language=en|access-date=2019-10-30}}</ref> This claim is based on the 8th-century custom in which [[Moorish]] kings' servants would take home the rice, chicken, and vegetables their employers left at the end of the meal.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.de/books?id=DX1NBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA192|title=Vibrant Andalusia: The Spice of Life in Southern Spain|last=Ruiz|first=Ana|date=2007|publisher=Algora Publishing|isbn=9780875865409|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.de/books?id=hHNS0NAK33AC&pg=PT51|title=Andalus: Unlocking The Secrets Of Moorish Spain|last=Webster|first=Jason|date=2010-08-03|publisher=Transworld|isbn=9781407094816|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.de/books?id=YD0hBQAAQBAJ&pg=PT62|title=Arab Women in the Middle Ages: Private Lives and Public Roles|last=Guthrie|first=Shirley|date=2013-08-01|publisher=Saqi|isbn=9780863567643|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.de/books?id=mB6aKnaqChMC&pg=PA26|title=Late Dinner: Discovering the Food of Spain|last=Richardson|first=Paul|date=2007-08-21|publisher=Simon and Schuster|isbn=9781416545392|language=en}}</ref> It has been said, however, that a problem with this etymology is that the word ''paella'' is not attested until six centuries after Moorish Valencia was conquered by [[Jaume I]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://www.raco.cat/index.php/RevistaEtnologia/article/download/81655/106249|title=Els espais socials de la paella: antropologia d\u2019un plat camale\u00f2nic|last=Duhart|first=Fr\u00e9d\u00e9ric|last2=Medina|first2=F. Xavier|publisher=Revista d'etnologia de Catalunya|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=89}}</ref>\n\n===''Paella Valenciana''===\nOriginally, paella made in Valencia was a lunchtime meal for farmers and farm laborers.  Workers would gather what was available to them around the rice fields.  This often included tomatoes, onions, and snails.  Rabbit or duck was a common addition, or chicken less often.<ref>{{cite web |title=History and Origins of Paella |url=https://www.thepaellacompany.co.uk/history.html |website=The Paella Company |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn special occasions, 18th century Valencians used ''calderos'' to cook rice in the open air of their orchards near lake [[Albufera]]. [[Arvicola sapidus|Water vole]] meat was one of the main ingredients of early paellas,<ref>Manuel V\u00e1zquez Montalb\u00e1n, ''La cocina de los mediterr\u00e1neos'', Ediciones B \u2013 Mexico</ref> along with [[eel]] and [[White beans|butter beans]]. Novelist [[Vicente Blasco Ib\u00e1\u00f1ez]] described the Valencia custom of eating [[European water vole|water voles]] in ''Ca\u00f1as y Barro'' (1902), a realistic novel about life among the fishermen and peasants near lake Albufera.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucm.es/info/especulo/numero31/viblasco.html |title=C\u00e9sar Bes\u00f3 Portal\u00e9s, '&#39;Vicente Blasco Ib\u00e1\u00f1ez y el Naturalismo'&#39;, I.E.S. Clara Campoamor, Alaqu\u00e1s (Valencia) |publisher=Ucm.es |date= |accessdate=19 February 2010}}</ref>\n\nLiving standards rose with the sociological changes of the late 19th century in Spain, giving rise to gatherings and outings in the countryside. This led to a change in paella's ingredients, as well, using instead rabbit, chicken, duck and sometimes snails. This dish became so popular that in 1840, a local Spanish newspaper first used the word ''paella'' to refer to the recipe rather than the pan.<ref name=\"foodtimeline.org\" />\n\nThe most widely used, complete ingredient list of this era was: short-grain white rice, chicken, rabbit, snails (optional), duck (optional), [[White beans|butter beans]], [[White beans|great northern beans]], [[runner beans]], [[artichoke]] (a substitute for runner beans in the winter), [[tomato]]es, fresh rosemary, sweet [[paprika]], [[saffron]], [[garlic]] (optional), salt, olive oil, and water.<ref name=\"foodtimeline.org\" /> Poorer Valencians, however, sometimes used nothing more than snails for meat. Valencians insist that only these ingredients should go into making modern ''paella valenciana''.\n\n=== Seafood and mixed ''paella''===\nOn the [[Mediterranean Sea|Mediterranean]] coast, Valencians used seafood instead of meat and beans to make paella. Valencians regard this recipe as authentic, as well. In this recipe, the seafood is served in the shell. A variant of this is ''paella del senyoret'' which uses seafood without shells. Later, however, Spaniards living outside of Valencia combined seafood with meat from land animals and mixed ''paella'' was born.<ref name=\"arrozsos.com\">{{cite web |author=Tu nombre |url=http://www.arrozsos.com/articulos/ver/historia_de_la_paella |title=Arroz SOS presents a history of paella |publisher=Arrozsos.com |accessdate=19 February 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100125102334/http://www.arrozsos.com/Articulos/ver/historia_de_la_paella |archivedate=25 January 2010 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> This ''paella'' is sometimes called ''preparaci\u00f3n barroca'' (baroque preparation) due to the variety of ingredients and its final presentation.<ref>{{cite web|title=Nuestras Paellas|url=http://www.pacharan.com.uy/platos/paellas/|website=Pachar\u00e1n|accessdate=2 September 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151116111929/http://www.pacharan.com.uy/platos/paellas/|archivedate=16 November 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nDuring the 20th century, paella's popularity spread past Spain's borders. As other cultures set out to make paella, the dish invariably acquired regional influences. Consequently, ''paella'' recipes went from being relatively simple to including a wide variety of seafood, meat, sausage (including [[chorizo]]),<ref>[http://www.oprah.com/food/Paella Mario Batali's version of mixed paella with chorizo] Oprah.com: Retrieved 30 June 2011</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Recipe courtesy Tyler Florence |url=http://www.foodnetwork.com/recipes/tyler-florence/paella-with-seafood-chicken-and-chorizo-recipe/index.html |title=Foodnetwork's paella recipe with seafood, chicken and chorizo |publisher=Foodnetwork.com |date= |accessdate=19 February 2010}}</ref> vegetables and many different seasonings.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spain-recipes.com/paellarecipes.html |title=An assortment of paella recipes |publisher=Spain-recipes.com |date= |accessdate=19 February 2010}}</ref> However, the most globally popular recipe is seafood paella.\n\nThroughout non-Valencia Spain, mixed ''paella'' is relatively easy to find. Some restaurants both in Spain and abroad that serve this mixed version refer to it as ''Paella valenciana''. However, Valencians insist that only the original two Valencia recipes are authentic, and generally view all others as inferior, not genuine or even grotesque.<ref name=\"arrozsos.com\" />[[File:Paella hirviendo.jpg|thumb|Traditional preparation of paella]]\n\n== Basic cooking methods ==\nAccording to tradition in [[Valencia]], ''paella'' is cooked over an open fire, fueled by orange and pine branches along with pine cones.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/go/london/restaurants/quique-dacosta-arros-qd-restaurant-london-a4160206.html|title=Arros QD's Quique Dacosta on why paella will be the dish of the summer|date=2019-06-05|website=Evening Standard|language=en|access-date=2019-12-18}}</ref> This produces an aromatic smoke which infuses the ''paella''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/food-and-drink/features/michelin-starred-chef-quique-dacosta-make-ultimate-paella/|title=Michelin-starred chef Quique Dacosta on how to make the ultimate paella|last=Curtis|first=Nick|date=2019-06-02|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2019-12-18|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>  Also, dining guests traditionally eat directly out of the pan instead of serving in plates.<ref name=\"Info about Paella on About.com\" /><ref name=\"foodtimeline.org\" /><ref name=\"arrozsos.com\" /><ref name=\"paellarecipes.top\">{{cite web|url=https://paellarecipes.top/paella-valenciana-recipe/ |title=Authentic Paella Valenciana as it is made in Valencia |publisher=paellarecipes.top |date= |accessdate=23 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nSome recipes call for ''paella'' to be covered and left to settle for five to ten minutes after cooking.\n\nAfter cooking ''paella'', there may be a layer of roasted rice at the bottom of the pan, called ''socarrat'' in [[Valencian|Valenci\u00e0]]. The layer develops on its own if the ''paella'' is cooked over a burner or open fire. This is traditionally considered positive (for as long as it is not scorched) and [[Valencia]] natives enjoy eating it.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/dbf555ec-b7da-11e9-96bd-8e884d3ea203|title=My kitchen essential: I\u2019d be lost without . . . my paella pan|last=Dacosta|first=Quique|date=2019-08-06|website=www.ft.com|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref>\n\n===''Paella valenciana''===\n{{cookbook|Paella Valenciana}}\n[[File:01 Paella Valenciana original.jpg|thumb|''Paella valenciana'']]\n\nThis recipe is standardized<ref name=\"paellarecipes.top\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://galbis.com/w/principal-paella-galbis-uk.htm |title=Restaurante Galbis \u2013 Restaurante,restaurantes L'alcudia \u2013 Valencia |work=waybackmachine.org |url-status=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090420125108/http://galbis.com/w/principal-paella-galbis-uk.htm |archivedate=20 April 2009 }}</ref><ref>Marqu\u00e8s, Vicent (2004): ''Els millors arrossos valencians''. Aldaia: Edicions Alfani.</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.jasonwebstersblog.com/2010/12/how-to-make-real-paella.html |title=Author Jason Webster's method for making Valencian paella |publisher=jasonwebstersblog.com |accessdate=28 December 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110713090839/http://www.jasonwebstersblog.com/2010/12/how-to-make-real-paella.html |archivedate=13 July 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> because [[Valencia]] originals consider it traditional and very much part of their culture. Rice in ''paella valenciana'' is never [[braised]] in oil, as [[pilaf]], though the ''paella'' made further southwest of Valencia often is.\n\n*Heat oil in a ''paella''.\n*[[Saut\u00e9]] meat after seasoning with salt.\n*Add green vegetables and saut\u00e9 until soft.\n*Add garlic (optional), grated tomatoes, beans and saut\u00e9.\n*Add paprika and saut\u00e9.\n*Add water, saffron (or food coloring), snails (optional) and rosemary.\n*Boil to make [[broth]] and allow it to reduce by half.\n*Remove the rosemary once flavour has infused or it starts to fall apart.\n*Add rice and simmer until rice is cooked.\n\nSome people enjoy garnishing their served plate with freshly squeezed lemon.\n\n===''Paella de marisco'' (Seafood ''paella'') ===\n{{Cookbook|Paella de Marisco}}\n[[File:Paella de marisco 01.jpg|thumb|Seafood paella]]\n\nRecipes for this dish vary somewhat, even in Valencia. The recipe below is based on the two cited here.<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ApmHP6uTg3Y&t=16s|title=Chef Juanry Segui's recipe for seafood paella |publisher=YouTube |date= |accessdate=27 February 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1ciBy9uX5Ts|title=Recipe for seafood paella |publisher=YouTube |date= |accessdate=27 February 2017}}</ref>\n*Make a seafood broth from shrimp heads, onions, garlic and bay leaves.\n*Heat oil in a ''paella''.\n*Add mussels. Cook until they open and then remove.\n*Saut\u00e9 [[Norway lobster]] and whole, deep-water rose shrimp. Then remove both the lobster and shrimp.\n*Add chopped [[cuttlefish]] and saut\u00e9.\n*Add shrimp tails and saut\u00e9.\n*Add garlic and saut\u00e9.\n*Add grated tomato and saut\u00e9.\n*Add rice and braise in [[sofrito]].\n*Add paprika and saut\u00e9.\n*Add seafood broth and then saffron (or food coloring).\n*Add salt to taste.\n*Add the deep-water rose shrimp, mussels and Norway lobster that were set aside.\n*Simmer until rice is cooked.\n\n===''Paella mixta'' (Mixed ''paella'')  ===\n{{cookbook|Paella Roja}}\n[[File:Red paella with mussels.jpg|thumb|Mixed paella]]\n\nThere are countless mixed ''paella'' recipes. The following method is common to most of these. Seasoning depends greatly on individual preferences and regional influences. However, salt, saffron, and garlic are almost always included.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.spain-recipes.com/mixed-paella.html |title=Mixed paella recipe |publisher=Spain-recipes.com |date= |accessdate=19 February 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QuCmO3Zlbng |title=A Spanish grandmother near Madrid cooks her mixed paella recipe on video |publisher=Youtube.com |date= |accessdate=19 February 2010}}</ref><ref>[http://www.hayrecetas.com/paella-mixta/6431 Mixed paella recipe on the '&#39;Hay Recetas'&#39; website]. Hayrecetas.com. Retrieved on 5 October 2016.</ref>\n*Make a broth from seafood, chicken, onions, garlic, bell peppers, and bay leaf.\n*Heat oil in a ''paella''.\n*Sear red bell pepper strips and set aside.\n*Sear [[crustacean]]s and set aside.\n*Season meat lightly with salt and saut\u00e9 meat until golden brown.\n*Add onions, garlic and bell peppers. Saut\u00e9 until vegetables are tender.\n*Add grated tomatoes and saut\u00e9.\n*Add dry seasonings except for salt.\n*Add rice.\n*Braise rice until covered with sofrito.\n*Add broth.\n*Add salt to taste.\n*Add saffron (or food coloring) and mix well.\n*Simmer until rice is almost cooked.\n*Replace crustaceans.\n*Continue simmering until rice and crustaceans are finished cooking.\n*Garnish with seared red bell pepper strips.\n\n== Variants ==\n=== Philippines ===\n{{Main|Arroz a la valenciana}}\n''Arroz a la valenciana'' (Spanish) or ''Arroz \u00e0 valenciana'' ([[Portuguese language|Portuguese]]) is considered as a part of [[Cuisine of the Philippines|Philippine cuisine]]. It is considered as the Philippine version of [[paella]].<ref>https://www.saveur.com/philippine-seafood-paella-recipe/</ref>\n\nThe Philippine version uses [[glutinous rice]], otherwise the ingredients are the same. In the Philippines, ''arroz a la valenciana'' refers to chicken, and ''[[longganisa]]'' (''chorizo'') versions.<ref name=\"ppmrvalenciana\">{{cite web |title=Arroz Valenciana Recipe |url=https://www.pinoyrecipe.net/arroz-valenciana-recipe/ |website=Pinoy Recipe At Iba Pa|accessdate=13 August 2011}}</ref>\n\n== In popular culture ==\n[[File:Un granito por Haiti.jpg|thumb|Giant ''paella'' being served]]\n\n=== Competitions and records ===\n\nIt has become a custom at mass gatherings in the [[Valencian Community|Valencia region]] (festivals, political campaigns, protests, etc.) to prepare enormous paellas, sometimes to win a place in the ''[[Guinness World Records]]'' book. Chefs use gargantuan ''paelleras'' for these events.\n\n[[Valencia]] restaurateur Juan Galbis claims to have made the world's largest ''paella'' with help from a team of workers on 2 October 2001. This ''paella'' fed about 110,000 people according to Galbis' former website.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.paellagigante.com/|title=Paellas gigantes \u2013 Catering y paellas para eventos \u2013 Comidas gigantes|work=Paellas Gigantes}}</ref> Galbis says this ''paella'' was even larger than his earlier world-record ''paella'' made on 8 March 1992 which fed about 100,000 people. Galbis' record-breaking 1992 ''paella'' is listed in ''Guinness World Records''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/news/2007/10/071030.aspx |title=Galbis's 1992 record listed on the Guinness website |publisher=Guinnessworldrecords.com |date= |accessdate=19 February 2010}}</ref>\n\n=== Controversial representations ===\nSome non-Spanish [[chef]]s include chorizo in their paellas along with other ingredients which Valencia people believe do not belong in ''paella'' of any type. The alternative name proposed for these dishes, although pejorative, is {{lang|es|arroz con cosas}} ('rice with things'). Famous cases are [[Jamie Oliver]]'s ''paella'' recipe (which included [[chorizo]])<ref>Oliver, Jamie. (16 September 2015) [http://www.jamieoliver.com/recipes/rice-recipes/chicken-chorizo-paella/ Chicken & chorizo paella | Rice Recipes]. Jamie Oliver. Retrieved on 2016-10-05.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-37555389|title=Jamie Oliver's paella recipe is panned online|website=[[BBC News]]|publisher=[[BBC]]|date=30 October 2014|access-date=5 January 2016}}</ref> and [[Gordon Ramsay]]'s.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Vega|first1=Ana|title=Chefs que destrozan la comida espa\u00f1ola|url=http://elcomidista.elpais.com/elcomidista/2016/02/26/articulo/1456475765_337785.html|accessdate=5 October 2016|work=[[El Pa\u00eds]]|issue=El Comidista|date=2 March 2016|language=es}}</ref> The author Josep Pla once noted:\n\n{{Quote|text=The abuses committed in the name of Paella Valenciana, are excessive \u2013 an absolute scandal. |author=Josep Pla |source=Catalan Cuisine, Revised Edition: Vivid Flavors From Spain's Mediterranean Coast }}\n\nHowever, in an article for [[El Pa\u00eds]], Spanish food writer Ana Vega 'Biscayenne', citing historical references, showed that traditional Valencian paella did indeed include chorizo, exclaiming, \"Ah Jamie, we'll have to invite you to the [[Falles]]\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Vega|first1=Ana|title=La paella s\u00ed llevaba chorizo|url=https://elcomidista.elpais.com/elcomidista/2016/10/13/articulo/1476372723_268242.html|access-date=13 June 2018|work=[[El Pa\u00eds]]|issue=El Comidista|date=14 October 2016|language=es}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Noto Emoji Pie 1f958.svg|thumb|''Paella'' UNICODE emoji]]\n\n===Emoji===\nIn 2015, an [[emoji]] for ''paella'' was proposed to [[Unicode]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.unicode.org/L2/L2015/15055-paella-emoji.pdf|title=ISO/IEC JTC 1/SC 2/WG 2 PROPOSAL SUMMARY FORM TO ACCOMPANY SUBMISSIONS FOR ADDITIONS TO THE REPERTOIRE OF ISO/IEC 10646 1|last=Gonzalez Capella|first=Antonio|date=1 February 2015|work=[[Unicode]]|accessdate=10 March 2017}}</ref> The [[emoji]] was approved for Unicode 9.0 as {{code|U+1F958 \"SHALLOW PAN OF FOOD\"}} in June 2016. Although it is generally rendered as paella, [[Samsung]] has rendered the symbol as a Korean [[hot pot]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://emojipedia.org/shallow-pan-of-food/|title=Paella Emoji|publisher=[[Emojipedia]]|accessdate=10 March 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Related dishes ==\n{{cookbook|Arroz Negro}}\n[[File:arroz-negro.png|thumb|''[[Arr\u00f2s negre]]'' (also called ''arroz negro'' and ''paella negra'')]]\n\nTraditional [[Valencian cuisine|Valencia cuisine]] offers recipes similar to ''paella valenciana'' and ''paella de marisco'' such as ''[[arr\u00f2s negre]]'', ''arr\u00f2s al forn'', ''arr\u00f2s a banda'' and ''arr\u00f2s amb fesols i naps'', since rice is the base of lots of local cuisine''.''\n\n[[Fideu\u00e0]] is a [[pasta]] noodle dish variation cooked in a similar fashion in a ''paella''. It may be served with [[aioli|allioli]] sauce.\n\n===''Paella'' descendants===\n*[[Arroz a la valenciana]] \u2013 Latin American and Filipino adaptation of meat ''paella'', uses [[annatto]] instead of [[saffron]]\n*[[Arroz con gandules]] \u2013 Puerto Rican adaptation, also uses annatto\n*[[Arroz con pollo]] \u2013 Latin American adaptation with chicken, also uses annatto\n*[[Bringhe]] \u2013 Filipino adaptation of ''paella'' with [[glutinous rice]] and [[coconut milk]], uses [[turmeric]]\n*[[Jambalaya]] \u2013 Louisiana dish influenced by ''paella'' and the French ''jambalaia'' from [[Provence]]\n*[[Locrio]] \u2013 Dominican descendant of paella.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dominicancooking.com/509-locrio-de-pollo-rice-and-chicken.html|title=Locrio de Pollo|author=Aunt Clara's Kitchen|accessdate=2014-03-18}}</ref>\n*[[Paelya]] \u2013 Filipino adaptation of ''paella'' that distinctively use glutinous rice, also uses annatto, [[turmeric]], or [[safflower]]. Also spelled \"''paella''\", but pronounced differently.<ref name=\"ppmrvalenciana2\">{{cite web |title=Arroz Valenciana |url=http://www.panlasangpinoymeatrecipes.com/arroz-a-la-valenciana.htm |website=Panlasang Pinoy Meaty Recipes |accessdate=14 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Other dishes===\n*[[Arr\u00f2s negre]] \u2013 sometimes called \"''paella negra''\", a similar Catalonia and Valencia dish using squid ink\n*[[Biryani]] \u2013 similar dish from the Indian subcontinent\n*[[Bisi Bele Bath]] \u2013 similar dish from India\n*[[Jollof rice]] \u2013 similar dish from West Africa\n*[[Kabsa]] \u2013 similar dish from the Middle East\n*[[Pilaf]] \u2013 similar dish from Central Asia\n*[[Risotto]] \u2013 similar northern Italian dish\n*[[Thieboudienne]] \u2013 similar dish from Mauritania and Senegal\n\n== See also ==\n{{portal|Spain|Food}}\n* [[Arroz a la valenciana]]\n* [[List of rice dishes]]\n* [[Mediterranean cuisine]]\n* [[Spanish cuisine]]\n* [[Risotto]]\n* [[Pilaf]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{cite book |last = March |first = Lourdes  |year = 1985 |title = El Libro De La Paella Y De Los Arroces |publisher = Alianza| location = Madrid |isbn = 8420601012 }}\n*{{cite book |last = R\u00edos |first = Alicia and Lourdes March |year = 1992 |title = The Heritage of Spanish Cooking |publisher = Random House |location = New York |isbn = 0-679-41628-5 |url = https://archive.org/details/heritageofspanis0000rios }}\n\n{{Commons category|Paella}}\n{{Culture of Valencian Community}}\n{{Rice dishes}}\n\n[[Category:Valencian cuisine]]\n[[Category:Spanish cuisine]]\n[[Category:Spanish rice dishes]]\n[[Category:Seafood dishes]]\n[[Category:National dishes]]\n", "name_user": "Gdylezo", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixed some grammar mistakes", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paella"}
{"title_page": "Rodney Howard-Browne", "text_new": "{{short description|South African preacher}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name          = Rodney Howard-Browne\n|image         = \n|image_size    = \n|caption       = \n|birth_name    = Rodney Morgan Howard Browne<ref name=\"TORONTOBLESSING\">{{Cite web|url=http://jbeard.users.rapidnet.com/bdm/Psychology/holylaugh.htm|title=Holy Laughter - Rodney Howard-Browne and the Toronto Blessing|website=jbeard.users.rapidnet.com|accessdate=Mar 31, 2020}}</ref>\n|birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1961|6|12}}<ref name=\"TORONTOBLESSING\"></ref>\n|birth_place   = [[Port Elizabeth]], South Africa\n|nationality   = South African\n|spouse        = Adonica Howard-Browne (nee Weyers)\n|website       = [http://www.revival.com Revival Ministries International]\n|footnotes     = \n}}\n\n'''Rodney (Morgan) Howard-Browne''' (born June 12, 1961)<ref name=\"HCDC\">{{cite web |title=Hernando County Inmate Booking Information: Rodney Howard Browne |url=https://www.hernandosheriff.org/jail/Applications/JailSearch/JailSearchDetails.aspx?BookNo=HCSO20JBN002084 |website=Hernando County Detention Center |accessdate=April 11, 2020 |date=March 30, 2020}}</ref> is a South African-born American Christian [[Evangelism|evangelist]] and [[conspiracy theorist]].<ref name=\"Guard040420\">{{cite news |last1=Wilson |first1=Jason |title=The rightwing Christian preachers in deep denial over Covid-19's danger |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/apr/04/america-rightwing-christian-preachers-virus-hoax |accessdate=April 12, 2020 |publisher=[[The Guardian]] |date=April 4, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Forbes033120\">{{cite news |last1=Carlie Porterfield |first1=Carlie |title=Florida Megachurch Pastor Arrested For Defying Coronavirus Stay-At-Home Order And Holding Services |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/carlieporterfield/2020/03/31/florida-megachurch-pastor-arrested-for-defying-coronavirus-stay-at-home-order-and-holding-services/#7a5201e36ac6 |accessdate=April 12, 2020 |publisher=[[Forbes (magazine)|Forbes]] |date=March 31, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"NYT031720\">{{cite news |last1=Williamson |first1=Elizabeth |title=On the Political Right, Anger and Suspicion Over Virus Precautions |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/17/us/politics/coronavirus-republicans.html |accessdate=April 12, 2020 |publisher=[[New York Times]] |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"TBT033020\"/> He has resided in [[Tampa]], [[Florida]] since the mid-1990 and is pastor of The River church in Tampa Bay. The River is considered both [[Pentecostal]] and [[Charismatic]] with [[revival meetings]], led by Howard-Browne, known for those in the audience breaking into \"[[holy laughter]]\".<ref name=\"TBT\"/><ref name=\"M&G\"/><ref name=\"carnes\"/><ref name=ravitz/><ref name=\"VOA\"/>  Howard-Browne is the head of Revival Ministries International, a group he and his wife founded in 1997.\n\n==Biography==\nHoward-Browne and his three brothers (Mervyn, Bazil, and Gil) were raised in a [[Pentecostalism|Pentecostal]] family in the cities of [[Port Elizabeth]] and [[East London, Eastern Cape|East London]], South Africa. His father, Frank Mervyn Derric Howard-Browne (1924\u20132005),<ref name=\"TBT090205\">{{cite news |title=Frank Howard-Browne Obituary |url=https://www.legacy.com/obituaries/tampabaytimes/obituary.aspx?n=frank-howard-browne&pid=15005170 |accessdate=April 6, 2019 |publisher=[[Tampa Bay Times]] |date=September 2, 2005}}</ref> was a cleric.  Howard-Browne became a Christian at age five.<ref name=\"M&G\"/> In 1981, he met and married his wife Adonica (n\u00e9e Weyers).<ref name=ravitz>Ravitz, Jessica. [https://archive.sltrib.com/article.php?id=5294497&itype=NGPSID \"Up for Godly giddiness: Pastor spreads the joy of salvation 'anywhere the Lord opens a door.'\"] The Salt Lake Tribune, March 22, 2007</ref> In the 1980s, he volunteered to work for [[Youth for Christ]] before doing a teaching stint with Rhema Bible School in [[Johannesburg]].\n\nIn December 1989, the family emigrated from South Africa to the United States,<ref>[https://www.pbs.org/wnet/religionandethics/week251/profile.html \"Profile: Evangelist Rodney Howard-Browne.\"] Religion and Ethics NewsWeekly, PBS, August 20, 1999</ref><ref name=\"M&G\">{{cite news |url=https://mg.co.za/article/2012-03-16-gods-bartender-in-good-spirits|last1=Philp |first1=Rowan Philp |title=God's bartender in good spirits |accessdate=April 4, 2019 |publisher=[[Mail & Guardian]] |date=March 16, 2012}}</ref> settling in [[Louisville, Kentucky]], and in 1991, he began holding revival meetings.<ref name=\"TBT090205\"/><ref name=\"Time062401\"/><ref name=\"RMI1\">{{cite web |title=History of Campmeetings |url=https://www.revival.com/index.html |website=Revival Ministries International |accessdate=April 6, 2019 |quote=Through the summer of 1991, we held revival meetings in Louisville, Kentucky, and all over the surrounding\u2026}}</ref> The Rodney Howard-Browne Evangelistic Association was incorporated in November 1993<ref name=\"FDS\">{{cite web |title=Rodney Howard Brown Evangelistic Association, Inc.: Annual Report 1994 |url=http://search.sunbiz.org/Inquiry/CorporationSearch/ConvertTiffToPDF?storagePath=COR%5C0107%5C0105%5CAR000589.tif&documentNumber=F93000005142 |publisher=Florida Department of State, Division of Corporations |accessdate=January 4, 2020}}</ref> and the family moved to the [[Tampa Bay, Florida]] area in 1994. Rodney's eldest brother Gil<ref name=\"TBT090205\"/> went on to operate Times of Refreshing Ministries, an online evangelical ministry.<ref name=\"TORM\">{{cite web |title=Times of Refreshing Ministries:The Internet Ministry of Evangelists Gil & Loraine Howard-Browne \u2013 About Us |url=http://revivaltimes.com/about.html |accessdate=April 6, 2019}}</ref>. Likewise, his youngest brother Bazil established an eponymous evangelical ministry on 1 January 1994 with the professed aim of people achieving financial freedom through the special anointing of God <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bhbem.wordpress.com/2009/05/26/what-you-need-to-know-about-bazil-howard-browne/|title=What you need to know about Bazil Howard-Browne|date=May 26, 2009|accessdate=Mar 31, 2020}}</ref>. Prior to this he had worked alongside his brother Rodney for a year.\n\nIn 1996, Howard-Browne founded a church he named \"The River\" at Tampa Bay Church in [[Tampa, Florida]], serving as its pastor ever since.<ref name=\"TBT011005\">{{cite news |last1=Graham |first1=Kevin |title=Church's Hummer prize too worldly? |url=http://www.sptimes.com/2005/01/10/Hillsborough/Church_s_Hummer_prize.shtml |accessdate=April 5, 2019 |publisher=[[Tampa Bay Times]] |date=January 10, 2005 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180326000430/http://www.sptimes.com/2005/01/10/Hillsborough/Church_s_Hummer_prize.shtml |archivedate=March 26, 2018}}</ref> Howard-Browne and his wife also founded Revival Ministries International in 1997, as well as River Bible Institute and River School of Worship.<ref>Howard-Browne, Rodney [https://www.revival.com/about \"About us\"] Revival.com</ref>\n\nHoward-Browne\u2019s services are characterized by [[faith healing|laying on of hands]] with worshipers giggling in apparent [[spiritual drunkenness]], [[speaking in tongues]], emitting animal noises, breaking into uncontrollable [[holy laughter]], shaking, dancing in the aisles, or falling to the ground.<ref name=\"TBT\"/><ref name=\"M&G\"/><ref name=\"carnes\"/><ref name=ravitz/><ref name=\"VOA\">{{cite news |last1=Socolovsky |first1=Jerome |title=African-born Pastor Brings \u2018Holy Laughter\u2019 Revival to Washington |url=https://www.voanews.com/a/african-born-pastor-brings-holy-laughter-revival-to-washington/1954365.html|accessdate=April 5, 2019 |publisher=[[Voice of America]] |date=July 9, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"NunNews\">{{cite news |last1=Rohner |first1=Thomas |title=Conspiracy-theorizing megachurch preacher visits Nunavut|url=https://nunatsiaq.com/stories/article/conspiracy-theorizing-megachurch-preacher-visits-nunavut/ |accessdate=January 4, 2020 |publisher=[[Nunatsiaq News]] |date=September 5, 2019 |quote=Howard-Browne also spoke in tongues, which he claimed was once understood in the obscure native dialect of a Papua New Guinea pastor}}</ref> He refers to himself as \"God's bartender\" and the \"holy ghost bartender\".<ref name=\"carnes\">Carnes, Tony. [http://www.christianitytoday.com/ct/1999/august9/9t913a.html \"Howard-Browne Takes New York.\"] Christianity Today, August 9, 1999</ref><ref name=\"TBT\">{{cite news|url=http://tampabayonline.net/reports/minister/homealt.htm|title=The Holy Ghost Bartender|last=Bearden|first=Michelle|date=1999-06-28|newspaper=[[The Tampa Tribune]]|accessdate=2019-02-23|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120707031815/http://tampabayonline.net/reports/minister/homealt.htm|archivedate=2012-07-07|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nHoward-Browne is credited with introducing holy laughter to [[Carpenter's Home Church]] in [[Lakeland, Florida]] during a series of revival services with Karl Strader in 1993. The holy laughter revivals later spread to nearby churches in Melbourne, Titusville, Stuart and Vero Beach, Florida.<ref name=\"OS090196\">{{cite news |last1=Pinsky |first1=Mark I |title=When Holy Laughter Starts, Some Find It Hard To Stop |url=https://www.orlandosentinel.com/news/os-xpm-1996-09-01-9608310934-story.html |accessdate=April 6, 2019 |publisher=[[Orlando Sentinel]] |date=September 1, 1996}}</ref><ref name=\"Ledger051808\">{{cite news |last1=McMullen |first1=Cary |title=Florida Outpouring: Internet Draws Thousands to Lakeland Revival |url= https://www.theledger.com/article/LK/20080518/News/608117817/LL/ |accessdate=April 6, 2019 |publisher=[[The Ledger]] |date=May 18, 2008}}</ref> Howard-Browne is credited with bringing holy laughter to the charismatic Toronto Airport Vineyard Church (soon after expelled by its parent [[Association of Vineyard Churches|Vineyard Church]]) at a 1994 revival in [[Toronto, Canada]] with evangelist Randy Clark, known as the \u201c[[Toronto Blessing]],\" and then a year later, to [[Assemblies of God]] (AOG) Brownsville Church in [[Pensacola, Florida]] with evangelist [[Steve Hill (evangelist)|Steve Hill]].  The event became known in Christian circles as the [[Brownsville Revival]].<ref name=\"OS090196\"/><ref name=\"Ledger051808\"/><ref name=\"Time062401\">{{cite news |last1=Ostling |first1=Richard N |title=Laughing for the Lord |url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,164903,00.html |accessdate=April 6, 2019 |publisher=[[Time Magazine]] |date=June 24, 2001}}</ref> Howard-Browne also ministered under pastor Mike Rose at the Juneau Christian Center (formerly known as the Bethel Assembly of God) in [[Juneau, Alaska]], an AOG church that [[Sarah Palin]] later attended after becoming governor of Alaska.<ref name=\"HuffPo101208\">{{cite news |last1=Wilson |first1=Bruce |title=Palin and the Holy Laughter Anointing |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/palin-and-the-holy-laught_b_125582 |accessdate=April 6, 2019 |publisher=[[Huffington Post]] |date=October 12, 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"NPR090508\">{{cite news |last1=Bradley Hagerty |first1=Barbara |title=Examining Palin's Pentecostal Background |url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=94332540 |accessdate=April 6, 2019 |publisher=[[NPR]] |date=September 5, 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"Hapers083008\">{{cite news |last1=Silverstein |first1=Ken |title=Palin and Her Pastors: \"Those that die without Christ have a horrible, horrible surprise\" |url=https://harpers.org/blog/2008/08/palin-and-her-pastors-those-that-die-without-christ-have-a-horrible-horrible-surprise/ |accessdate=April 6, 2019 |publisher=[[Harper's Magazine]] |date=August 30, 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"Newsweek102708\">{{cite web |last1=Miller |first1=Lisa |title=What Are Sarah Palin\u2019s Religious Beliefs? |url=https://www.newsweek.com/what-are-sarah-palins-religious-beliefs-91785 |website=[[Newsweek]] |accessdate=April 6, 2019 |date=October 27, 2008}}</ref>\n\nHoward-Browne first came to national prominence in the US in 1999 when his Revival Ministries organization rented [[Madison Square Garden]] in New York City for six weeks. The event, called Good News New York, was described as \u201can effort to achieve a Billy Graham-style faith uprising\u201d, but was \u201cderided in local media as a giant flop\u201d. It was estimated to cost up to $10 million but only 3,000 people were counted in attendance at the 19,000-seat arena.<ref name=\"M&G\"/><ref name=\"carnes\"/><ref name=\"TBT\"/> Investigative journalists in his home town of Tampa reported at the time that since arriving from South Africa almost penniless in December 1989, his sudden wealth included a boat, a [[Harley Davidson]] motorcycle, a home in one of Tampa\u2019s exclusive gated communities and access to a private jet; however, they were unable to find evidence of financial wrongdoing.<ref name=\"M&G\"/><ref name=\"TBT\"/>\n\nHoward-Browne\u2019s daughter Kelly died due to cystic fibrosis on Christmas Day, 25 December 2002, at the age of 18. He then vowed that \u201csince the devil has taken their daughter with this dreaded disease, he would pay with one million souls over the next ten years\u201d.<ref name=\"Kambulow\"/><ref name=\"TBT122802\">{{cite news |title=Kelly Howard-Browne Obituary |url=https://www.legacy.com/obituaries/tampabaytimes/obituary.aspx?n=kelly-howard-browne&pid=680575 |accessdate=April 6, 2019 |publisher=[[Tampa Bay Times]] |date=December 28, 2002}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, it was reported that Howard-Browne\u2019s River Church had hosted political meetings for the Florida chapter of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] during the preceding two years, including a rally for then presidential candidate [[Newt Gingrich]], at which Howard-Browne called for a national \"rising\" of Christian Americans \"that will not sit idly by and allow the killing of unborn babies and allow Islam to take over this country\". At the same event, he described [[Mormonism]] as a \"cult\" that, in the 19th century, \"had death squads that would go around killing everybody that was not a Mormon\". He later recanted, saying Mormons were \"honourable people\".<ref name=\"M&G\"/>\n\nHoward-Browne published ''The Killing of Uncle Sam: The Demise of the United States of America'', which was scheduled to be released in May 2018, and announced that proceeds from sales of the book would go to the River School of Government, a degree granting program, operated by Howard-Browne and his wife under the auspices of Revival Ministries, that funds training for people seeking to run for political office.<ref name=\"DFP\">{{cite news |last1=McGregor |first1=Grady |title=Controversial pastor visits Dickinson: Rival pastor from Montana dragged from church after protesting |url=https://www.thedickinsonpress.com/news/4360976-controversial-pastor-visits-dickinson-rival-pastor-montana-dragged-church-after |accessdate=January 4, 2020 |publisher=[[Dickinson Press]] |date=November 17, 2017}}</ref>  \n\nHoward-Browne's evangelical movement has been rejected as cult-like by many mainstream Christian organisations, and it has been described as \"a combination of brimstone and fire about God\u2019s power, sprinkled with hipster references and a conviction that church\u2014like Disneyland\u2014should be 'the happiest place on earth'.\"<ref name=\"M&G\"/> The Christian Research Institute labelled his operation a \u201ccult\u201d and called the him \"a good stage hypnotist\" who has made millions from vulnerable believers.<ref name=\"M&G\"/> According to ''[[The Tampa Tribune]]'', critics have described him as \"a manipulator leading followers into a cult; a circus ring leader making a good living.\"<ref name=\"TBT\"/>\n\n==Statements and controversies==\n===Diploma mill doctorate===\nHoward-Browne claimed to have earned a \"doctorate of ministry degree\" in 1992  from \"The School of Bible Theology\", a [[non-accredited]] Pentecostal correspondence school in San Jacinto, California that has been described as a \"[[diploma mill]]\".<ref name=TBT/><ref name=\"AI1\">{{cite news|last1=Kowalski|first1=David|title=\"Name it and Frame it\" \u2014 Phony Doctorates in the Church|url=http://www.apologeticsindex.org/2794-name-it-and-frame-it-phony-doctorates-in-the-church|accessdate=May 3, 2018|publisher=Apologetics Index|date=2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dSur1KLjWIUC&source=gbs_navlinks_s|last1=Stokes |first1=Jerry |title=Joseph Smith and Word of Faith Movement |page=21 |accessdate=April 4, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Kambulow\">{{cite book |last1=Kambulow |first1=Walter |title=The Best of the Kambulows |date=June 1, 2003 |page=879 |url=https://books.google.com/books/about/THE_BEST_OF_THE_KAMBULOW.html?id=YS3cAgAAQBAJ |accessdate=April 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Multi-level marketing: Monavie and Jeunesse===\nHoward-Browne and his wife Adonica were top-ranking (\u201cBlack Diamond executive level\u201d) distributors for [[Monavie]], a [[multi-level marketing]] company that sold [[acai berry]] juice-based beverages until folding in 2014 subsequent to a $182 million loan default and allegations of [[pyramid scheme|pyramid scheming]], fraudulent advertising, and [[patent infringement]].<ref>{{cite web |title=MV Three Sixty Five Magazine |url=https://www.team-legacy.info/PDF/MV365_Magazine.pdf |accessdate=April 4, 2019 |pages=86}}</ref><ref name=\"YT\">{{cite news|title=Rodney and Adonica Howard-Browne MonaVie Black Diamond|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jdXhteTaPpE|accessdate=May 2, 2018|agency=YouTube|publisher=[[Monavie|Monavie Corporate]]|date=March 18, 2009}}</ref><ref name=imagenetixdocket>{{cite web| title = Imagenetix, Inc. vs. Monavie LLC et al. | publisher = [[United States District Court]] for the Southern District of California | date = May 2, 2018 | url = https://ia800205.us.archive.org/20/items/gov.uscourts.casd.269686/gov.uscourts.casd.269686.1.0.pdf| accessdate = 2008-09-20}}</ref> As of 2016, Howard-Browne also served as a \"North America Emerald Director\" for the multi-level marketing company Jeunesse.<ref name=\"Jeunesse\">{{cite web |title=Legacy Powered by Jeunesse |url=https://www.team-legacy.com/PDF/OurTeam-OurProducts.pdf |publisher=Jeunesse Global Holdings, LLC |accessdate=April 4, 2019 |page=41 |date=2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Allegation of plot to attack Donald Trump ===\nIn July 2017, Howard-Browne was one of 17 evangelical pastors who visited the [[White House]] to pray for and [[laying on of hands|lay hands]] on President [[Donald Trump]].<ref name=\"KCS\">{{cite news|last1=Gutierrez|first1=Lisa|title=\u2018Great spiritual awakening\u2019: Pastors lay hands on Donald Trump in the Oval Office|url=http://www.kansascity.com/news/nation-world/article160904779.html|accessdate=May 2, 2018|publisher=[[The Kansas City Star]]|date=July 12, 2017}}</ref> In a video several days later, Howard-Browne stated that \u201cthere is a planned attack on our president and that\u2019s all I can tell you about right now; I know what I\u2019m talking about, I\u2019ve spoken to high-ranking people in the government\".<ref>{{cite web\n | url = http://www.rightwingwatch.org/post/rodney-howard-browne-prayed-over-trump-in-order-to-avert-a-planned-attack-on-our-president/\n | title = Rodney Howard-Browne Prayed Over Trump In Order To Avert \u2018A Planned Attack On Our President\u2019 \n | last = Mantyla\n | first = Kyle\n | date = July 17, 2017\n | website = Right Wing Watch\n | publisher = People for the American Way\n | access-date = December 21, 2017\n | quote = There is a planned attack on our president,\" he said, \u201cand that\u2019s all I can tell you about right now; I know what I\u2019m talking about, I\u2019ve spoken to high-ranking people in the government and this is being planned by people that hate God, hate America, hate our president and we have to stop this, in Jesus name.\u201d}}</ref> Howard-Browne later said that the Secret Service met with him to discover which congressman told him about the plot but he refused to say, citing pastoral privilege.<ref>\n {{cite web\n  | url = http://www.rightwingwatch.org/post/its-not-my-problem-rodney-howard-browne-refused-to-provide-the-secret-service-with-details-of-a-plot-again-trump/\n  | title = Pastor Who Claimed His Prayers Averted Anti-Trump Attack Refuses To Provide Details To Secret Service Because It\u2019s \u2018Not My Problem\u2019\n  | last = Mantyla\n  | first = Kyle\n  | date = July 31, 2017\n  | website = Right Wing Watch\n  | publisher = Right Wing Watch\n  | access-date = 21 December 2017\n | quote = Somebody reported me to the Secret Service, so they came over\u201d he claimed. \u201cThree guys, we sat and talked; very nice people and they wanted to know who the congressman was. I said, \u2018I can\u2019t tell you that, it was pastoral privilege.\u2019 I said, \u2018I prayed for him\u2019 and he said, \u2018So, it was like a confession?\u2019 I said, \u2018Yeah, I can\u2019t tell you. I\u2019m not going to tell you, I can\u2019t tell you, it\u2019s impossible.'\u201d \u201cIf the Secret Service in Washington, D.C., don\u2019t know what\u2019s coming down, then why should somebody from Tampa?\u201d Howard-Browne added. \u201cThis is a senior member of Congress. If he actually knew anything, he would inform the Secret Service himself. It\u2019s not my problem.}}</ref> Howard-Browne praised God for giving America a 'Rambo'.<ref name=\"Right Wing Watch\">{{cite news |title=Rodney Howard-Browne Thanks God For Giving America \u2018A Rambo\u2019 In Trump|url=http://www.rightwingwatch.org/post/rodney-howard-browne-thanks-god-for-giving-america-a-rambo-in-trump/|date=18 May 2018| accessdate=4 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2016, Howard-Browne wrote a Facebook post titled \u201cDonald Trump Is the New World Order\u2019s Worst Nightmare,\u201d where he detailed his choice to back Trump in the election as a check against a global conspiracy to destroy America.<ref name=\"Weaver\">{{cite news |last1=Weaver |first1=Hilary |title=Donald Trump\u2019s Oval Office Prayer Circle, Explained |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/style/2017/07/donald-trump-oval-office-prayer-circle-explained |publisher=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]|accessdate=April 4, 2019 |date=July 12, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Hurricane Irma===\nIn September 2017, Howard-Browne received media attention after referring to [[Hurricane Irma]]\u2014a [[List of Category 4 Atlantic hurricanes|category 4]] storm that caused the death of 50 people in the U.S. and Caribbean and resulted in power outages affecting 5.5 million people in Florida\u2014as a \"nothingburger\". He further stated that \"prayer took the teeth out of the storm\".<ref name=\"Newsweek091217\">{{cite news |last1=Gaffey |first1=Conor |title=Hurricane Irma Was A Nothingburger, Says Pastor Who Prayed Over Trump At White House |url=https://www.newsweek.com/hurricane-irma-florida-trump-rodney-howard-browne-663594 |accessdate=April 4, 2019 |publisher=[[Newsweek]] |date=September 12, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Alleging human sacrifice===\nIn an October 2017 sermon at The River at Tampa Bay church, Howard-Browne alleged that \"They sacrifice children at the highest levels in Hollywood. They drink blood of young kids. This is a fact\", continuing, \"The human sacrifice and the cannibalism has been going on for years\" in Hollywood and Washington, D.C.<ref>\n{{cite web\n | url = https://www.charismanews.com/56-video/67850-rodney-howard-browne-hollywood-execs-are-full-of-the-devil-drink-the-blood-of-young-kids\n | title = Rodney Howard Browne: Hollywood Execs Are 'Full of the Devil,' 'Drink the Blood of Young Kids'\n | last = Justice\n | first = Jessilyn\n | date = October 20, 2017 \n | website = Charisma News\n | publisher = Charisma Media\n | access-date = December 21, 2017\n | quote = \"They sacrifice children at the highest levels in Hollywood. They drink blood of young kids. This is a fact. That's why the next thing to be exposed will be all the pedophilia that is going to come out of Hollywood and come out of Washington, D.C. The human sacrifice and the cannibalism has been going on for years\"}}</ref><ref>\n {{cite web\n  | url = https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/rodney-howard-browne-hollywood-devil-worship_us_59e96616e4b0f9d35bc9a27b\n  | title = Trump-Linked Pastor: Hollywood Is Full Of Satanists Who Drink Children\u2019s Blood\n  | last = Mazza\n  | first = Ed\n  | date = October 20, 2017\n  | website = Huffpost\n  | publisher = Oath Inc.\n  | access-date = December 21, 2017\n | quote = }}\n</ref><ref name=\"CT102017\">{{cite news |last1=Macintyre |first1=James |title=Pastor who prayed over Donald Trump says Hollywood is full of devil worshippers who drink children's blood |url=https://www.christiantoday.com/article/pastor-who-prayed-over-donald-trump-says-hollywood-is-full-of-devil-worshippers-who-drink-childrens-blood/116518.htm |accessdate=April 4, 2019 |publisher=[[Christian Today]] |date=October 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Arming of the River at Tampa Bay church===\nHoward-Browne drew attention for a social media post in November 2017, two days after the [[Sutherland Springs church shooting]], stating that his church was not a gun-free zone and that he and the church\u2019s pastors \u201care all heavily armed\u201d and would use \u201cdeadly force\u201d.<ref name=\"WaPo_112117\">{{cite news |last1=Eltagouri |first1=Marwa |title=This church has a warning for visitors: \u2018WE ARE HEAVILY ARMED \u2014 The Pastors\u2019 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/acts-of-faith/wp/2017/11/21/a-florida-church-has-a-warning-for-visitors-this-is-not-a-gun-free-zone-the-pastors/?noredirect=on |accessdate=April 4, 2019 |publisher=[[Washington Post]] |date=November 21, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"SJ\">{{cite news|last1=Denker|first1=Angela|title='We Are Heavily Armed. -The Pastors'|url=https://sojo.net/articles/we-are-heavily-armed-pastors|accessdate=May 2, 2018|publisher=[[Sojourners]]|date=April 18, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"CBN112017\">{{cite news|last1=Aaron|first1=Charlene|title=After Deadly Church Shooting, Rodney Howard-Browne's Church Warns 'We Are Heavily Armed'|url=http://www1.cbn.com/cbnnews/us/2017/november/after-deadly-church-shooting-rodney-howard-brownes-church-warns-we-are-are-heavily-armed|accessdate=May 2, 2018|publisher=[[Christian Broadcasting Network]]|date=November 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Conspiracy theories on InfoWars===\nIn March 2018, Howard-Browne made an appearance on [[Alex Jones]]' [[InfoWars]] program during which he claimed: that a string of [[Austin bombings|bombings in Austin, Texas]] were being used by \"anarchist terrorists\" in an attempt to bring \"everything under control\"; that churches and religious groups were being censored in the U.S.; and that \"globalist gremlins\" were attempting to thwart Donald Trump.<ref name=\"RWW\">{{cite news|last1=Holt|first1=Jared|title=Rodney Howard-Browne Says Only \u2018Divine Intervention\u2019 Can Save America|url=http://www.rightwingwatch.org/post/rodney-howard-browne-says-only-divine-intervention-can-save-america/|accessdate=May 2, 2018|publisher=[[Right Wing Watch]]|date=March 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Christchurch Mosque shootings===\nShortly after the [[Christchurch mosque shootings]] in March 2019, Howard-Browne tweeted his opinion that it was a '[[false flag]]' operation: \"There is no doubt that what happened in New Zealand as horrific as it is, is a false flag that will be blamed on conservatives when it\u2019s all said and done!  Only a total nutjob lunatic, insane demonized freak goes into a building and kills people, it\u2019s unacceptable on every level!\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rawstory.com/2019/03/megachurch-pastor-invited-trumps-white-house-declares-new-zealand-terror-attack-false-flag/|title=Megachurch pastor who was invited to Trump\u2019s White House declares New Zealand terror attack a \u2018false flag\u2019|first=Brad|last=Reed|website=www.rawstory.com}}</ref>\n\n===Iqaluit sermon===\nOn August 27, 2019, Howard-Browne delivered a sermon in the [[Canadian Arctic]] territory of [[Nunavut]] as part of a 300-city tour. He preached for over an hour at an [[Iqaluit]] church to a mostly [[Inuit]] audience of more than 100 people. The event featured a call for donations, including a video of Howard-Browne claiming \u201cGod loves a generous giver,\u201d which ''[[Nunatsiaq News]]'' criticized on the basis that poverty is widespread in the city and nearly half of Nunavut\u2019s population relies on social assistance amidst long-standing crises in food security and housing.<ref name=\"NunNews\"/> The news outlet also noted that he \u201clashed out\u201d at and \u201charangued\u201d audience members who tried to leave before the end of the sermon. Commenting after the event, [[Anglican bishop]] for the Arctic, [[David Parsons (bishop)|David Parsons]], described Howard-Browne as an [[extremist]].\n\n===Coronavirus pandemic===\n{{see also|Misinformation related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\nHoward-Browne kept his church open during the  [[2019-2020 coronavirus pandemic]] and on March 15 told his congregants to continue shaking hands because they were \u201crevivalists, not pansies\u201d. He also claimed in his sermon that the pandemic was a \u201cphantom plague\u201d engineered by the Rockefeller Foundation to shut down churches and force people to receive a vaccine that would cause mass deaths, all as part of a population control scheme.<ref name=\"NW_031620\">{{cite news |last1=Palmer |first1=Evan |title=Conservative pastor says his church 'will never close' because of coronavirus: 'we're raising up revivalists, not pansies' |url=https://www.newsweek.com/coronavirus-rodney-howard-browne-florida-pastor-pansies-1492460 |accessdate=March 16, 2020 |publisher=[[Newsweek]] |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Indep_031620\">{{cite news |last1=Naughtie |first1=Andrew |title=Coronavirus: US conservatives spark backlash after socialising against official health advice |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/coronavirus-republican-kevin-stitt-restaurant-social-distancing-tweet-restaurant-a9404346.html |accessdate=March 16, 2020 |publisher=[[The Independent]] |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rightwingwatch.org/post/rodney-howard-browne-coronavirus-pandemic-is-a-globalist-plot-to-kill-people-with-vaccines/|title=Rodney Howard-Browne: Coronavirus Pandemic Is a Globalist Plot to Kill People With Vaccines|first1=Kyle Mantyla &#124;|last1=March 16|first2=2020 10:24|last2=Am|website=Right Wing Watch|accessdate=Mar 31, 2020}}</ref> Several weeks prior, Howard-Browne claimed in a video that he would cure Florida of coronavirus.<ref name=\"OW_022620\">{{cite news |last1=Wolf |first1=Colin |title=Tampa pastor who claimed to cure Zika now says he will cure Florida of coronavirus |url=https://www.orlandoweekly.com/Blogs/archives/2020/02/26/tampa-pastor-who-claimed-to-cure-zika-now-says-he-will-cure-florida-of-coronavirus |accessdate=March 16, 2020 |publisher=[[Orlando Weekly]] |date=February 26, 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn March 29, 2020, Howard-Browne's congregation received a visit from the [[Hillsborough County Sheriff's Office]] about his violations of the county's safer-at-home order, which limited public gatherings to 10 people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/RightWingWatch/status/1244636146073812995|title=Right-wing pastor Rodney Howard-Browne has repeatedly stated that he will never cancel services at his The River church in Tampa. Now it looks like he received a visit from the local sheriff's office after holding services yesterday.pic.twitter.com/ABFYq4RtCg|first=|last=Right Wing Watch|date=Mar 30, 2020|accessdate=Mar 31, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"NBCN033020\"/> The next day, Hillsborough County Sheriff Chad Chronister announced that he had issued an arrest warrant to Howard-Browne for unlawful assembly and for violating rules regarding public health emergencies after Howard-Browne continued to hold large church services in defiance of the public order.<ref name=\"NYT033020\">{{cite news |last1=Mazzei |first1=Patricia |title=Florida Pastor Arrested After Defying Virus Orders |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/30/us/coronavirus-pastor-arrested-tampa-florida.html |accessdate=April 1, 2020 |publisher=[[New York Times]] |date=March 30, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"TBT033020\">{{cite news |last1=Marrero |first1=Tony |title=Pastor of Tampa church that held two large Sunday services arrested, jailed |url=https://www.tampabay.com/news/health/2020/03/30/tampa-church-holds-packed-service-draws-warning-from-sheriffs-office/ |accessdate=April 1, 2020 |publisher=[[Tampa Bay Times]] |date=March 30, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/HCSOSheriff/videos/230907918296583/|title=Hillsborough County Sheriff's Office on Facebook Watch|accessdate=Mar 31, 2020|via=www.facebook.com}}</ref><ref>Mantyla, Kyle (March 30, 2020). \"[https://www.rightwingwatch.org/post/arrest-warrant-issued-for-rodney-howard-browne-for-hosting-church-services-amid-the-coronavirus-outbreak/ Arrest Warrant Issued for Rodney Howard-Browne for Hosting Church Services Amid Coronavirus Pandemic]\". [[Right Wing Watch]].</ref> Chronister said he had no choice but to take action against Howard-Browne, stating \"His reckless disregard for human life put hundreds of people from his congregation at risk and thousands of residents who may interact with them this week.\"<ref name=\"NBCN033020\">{{cite news |last1=Li |first1=David K |title=Florida pastor arrested after holding church services despite coronavirus orders |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/florida-pastor-arrested-after-holding-church-services-despite-coronavirus-orders-n1172276 |accessdate=April 1, 2020 |publisher=[[NBC News]] |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn March 30, 2020, Howard-Browne was arrested and jailed for unlawful assembly and for violating health and safety rules, with each charge carrying a maximum penalty of 60 days in jail and a $500 fine.<ref name=\"TBT033020\"/><ref name=\"NYT033020\"/> He was released from jail after posting a $500 bond.<ref>Sommer, Will and Connor, Tracy (March 30, 2020). \"[https://www.thedailybeast.com/hillsborough-sheriff-to-arrest-rodney-howard-browne-megachurch-pastor-who-flouted-virus-rules|Rodney Howard-Browne, Megachurch Pastor Who Flouted Virus Rules, Arrested.]\" [[The Daily Beast]].</ref>\n\nOn April 1, Howard-Browne said that he would not open his church the following weekend over fear of his congregation\u2019s safety and to protect them from \u201cgovernment tyranny.\"<ref name=\"OW040320\">{{cite news |last1=Wolf |first1=Colin |title=Orlando lawyer for pastor who held services during coronavirus outbreak says church lost its insurance |url=https://m.orlandoweekly.com/Blogs/archives/2020/04/03/orlando-lawyer-for-pastor-who-held-services-during-coronavirus-outbreak-says-church-lost-its-insurance |accessdate=April 11, 2020 |publisher=[[Orlando Weekly]] |date=April 3, 2020}}</ref> However, his lawyer, [[Mathew Staver]] of the law firm [[Liberty Counsel]], said that Howard-Browne\u2019s arrest earlier in the week had led to the pastor\u2019s insurance policy being cancelled.<ref name=\"OW040320\"/><ref name=\"NBCN041020\">{{cite news |last1=Siemaszko |first1=Corky |title=Florida megachurch pastor caves after defying coronavirus rules |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/florida-megachurch-pastor-caves-after-defying-coronavirus-rules-n1181491 |accessdate=April 11, 2020 |publisher=[[NBC News]] |date=April 10, 2020}}</ref> Howard-Browne also claimed and that he had received death threats. The pastor held open the possibility that the church would be open for [[Easter]] services but then announced on April 9 that it would instead be closed.<ref name=\"NBCN041020\"/>\n\n== Publications ==\n*''The Killing of Uncle Sam: The Demise of the United States of America'' by Rodney Howard-Browne and [[Paul L. Williams (author)|Paul L. Williams]]\n*''How to Increase and Release the Anointing'' Rodney Howard-Browne-Word and Spirit Publishing (2018)\n*''Manifesting the Holy Ghost to You, in You, and Through You'' Rodney Howard-Browne-Word and Spirit Publishing (2018)\n*''How to Increase and Release the Anointing'' Rodney Howard-Browne-Word and Spirit Publishing (2018)\n*''School of the Spirit'' Rodney Howard-Browne-Word and Spirit Publishing (2018)\n*''The Touch of God: A Practical Handbook on the Anointing'' Rodney Howard-Browne-Word and Spirit Publishing (2018)\n*''Seeing Jesus as He Really Is'' Rodney Howard-Browne-Word and Spirit Publishing (2018)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.revival.com Revival Ministries International website]\n*[https://www.riverschoolofgovernment.com River School of Government]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Howard-Browne, Rodney}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century Christian mystics]]\n[[Category:Christian revivalists]]\n[[Category:Conspiracy theorists]]\n[[Category:Faith healers]]\n[[Category:People from the Eastern Cape]]\n[[Category:South African Charismatics]]\n[[Category:South African clergy]]\n[[Category:21st-century Christian mystics]]\n[[Category:20th-century Christian clergy]]\n[[Category:21st-century Christian clergy]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|South African preacher}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name          = Rodney Howard-Browne\n|image         = \n|image_size    = \n|caption       = \n|birth_name    = Rodney Morgan Howard Browne<ref name=\"TORONTOBLESSING\">{{Cite web|url=http://jbeard.users.rapidnet.com/bdm/Psychology/holylaugh.htm|title=Holy Laughter - Rodney Howard-Browne and the Toronto Blessing|website=jbeard.users.rapidnet.com|accessdate=Mar 31, 2020}}</ref>\n|birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1961|6|12}}<ref name=\"TORONTOBLESSING\"></ref>\n|birth_place   = [[Port Elizabeth]], South Africa\n|residence     = [[Tampa, Florida]], U.S.\n|nationality   = South African\n|spouse        = Adonica Howard-Browne (nee Weyers)\n|website       = [http://www.revival.com Revival Ministries International]\n|footnotes     = \n}}\n\n'''Rodney (Morgan) Howard-Browne''' (born June 12, 1961)<ref name=\"HCDC\">{{cite web |title=Hernando County Inmate Booking Information: Rodney Howard Browne |url=https://www.hernandosheriff.org/jail/Applications/JailSearch/JailSearchDetails.aspx?BookNo=HCSO20JBN002084 |website=Hernando County Detention Center |accessdate=April 11, 2020 |date=March 30, 2020}}</ref> is a South African-born American Christian [[Evangelism|evangelist]] and [[conspiracy theorist]].<ref name=\"Guard040420\">{{cite news |last1=Wilson |first1=Jason |title=The rightwing Christian preachers in deep denial over Covid-19's danger |url=https://www.theguardian.com/us-news/2020/apr/04/america-rightwing-christian-preachers-virus-hoax |accessdate=April 12, 2020 |publisher=[[The Guardian]] |date=April 4, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Forbes033120\">{{cite news |last1=Carlie Porterfield |first1=Carlie |title=Florida Megachurch Pastor Arrested For Defying Coronavirus Stay-At-Home Order And Holding Services |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/carlieporterfield/2020/03/31/florida-megachurch-pastor-arrested-for-defying-coronavirus-stay-at-home-order-and-holding-services/#7a5201e36ac6 |accessdate=April 12, 2020 |publisher=[[Forbes (magazine)|Forbes]] |date=March 31, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"NYT031720\">{{cite news |last1=Williamson |first1=Elizabeth |title=On the Political Right, Anger and Suspicion Over Virus Precautions |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/17/us/politics/coronavirus-republicans.html |accessdate=April 12, 2020 |publisher=[[New York Times]] |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"TBT033020\"/> He has resided in [[Tampa]], [[Florida]] since the mid-1990 and is pastor of The River church in Tampa Bay. The River is considered both [[Pentecostal]] and [[Charismatic]] with [[revival meetings]], led by Howard-Browne, known for those in the audience breaking into \"[[holy laughter]]\".<ref name=\"TBT\"/><ref name=\"M&G\"/><ref name=\"carnes\"/><ref name=ravitz/><ref name=\"VOA\"/>  Howard-Browne is the head of Revival Ministries International, a group he and his wife founded in 1997.\n\n==Biography==\nHoward-Browne and his three brothers (Mervyn, Bazil, and Gil) were raised in a [[Pentecostalism|Pentecostal]] family in the cities of [[Port Elizabeth]] and [[East London, Eastern Cape|East London]], South Africa. His father, Frank Mervyn Derric Howard-Browne (1924\u20132005),<ref name=\"TBT090205\">{{cite news |title=Frank Howard-Browne Obituary |url=https://www.legacy.com/obituaries/tampabaytimes/obituary.aspx?n=frank-howard-browne&pid=15005170 |accessdate=April 6, 2019 |publisher=[[Tampa Bay Times]] |date=September 2, 2005}}</ref> was a cleric.  Howard-Browne became a Christian at age five.<ref name=\"M&G\"/> In 1981, he met and married his wife Adonica (n\u00e9e Weyers).<ref name=ravitz>Ravitz, Jessica. [https://archive.sltrib.com/article.php?id=5294497&itype=NGPSID \"Up for Godly giddiness: Pastor spreads the joy of salvation 'anywhere the Lord opens a door.'\"] The Salt Lake Tribune, March 22, 2007</ref> In the 1980s, he volunteered to work for [[Youth for Christ]] before doing a teaching stint with Rhema Bible School in [[Johannesburg]].\n\nIn December 1989, the family emigrated from South Africa to the United States,<ref>[https://www.pbs.org/wnet/religionandethics/week251/profile.html \"Profile: Evangelist Rodney Howard-Browne.\"] Religion and Ethics NewsWeekly, PBS, August 20, 1999</ref><ref name=\"M&G\">{{cite news |url=https://mg.co.za/article/2012-03-16-gods-bartender-in-good-spirits|last1=Philp |first1=Rowan Philp |title=God's bartender in good spirits |accessdate=April 4, 2019 |publisher=[[Mail & Guardian]] |date=March 16, 2012}}</ref> settling in [[Louisville, Kentucky]], and in 1991, he began holding revival meetings.<ref name=\"TBT090205\"/><ref name=\"Time062401\"/><ref name=\"RMI1\">{{cite web |title=History of Campmeetings |url=https://www.revival.com/index.html |website=Revival Ministries International |accessdate=April 6, 2019 |quote=Through the summer of 1991, we held revival meetings in Louisville, Kentucky, and all over the surrounding\u2026}}</ref> The Rodney Howard-Browne Evangelistic Association was incorporated in November 1993<ref name=\"FDS\">{{cite web |title=Rodney Howard Brown Evangelistic Association, Inc.: Annual Report 1994 |url=http://search.sunbiz.org/Inquiry/CorporationSearch/ConvertTiffToPDF?storagePath=COR%5C0107%5C0105%5CAR000589.tif&documentNumber=F93000005142 |publisher=Florida Department of State, Division of Corporations |accessdate=January 4, 2020}}</ref> and the family moved to the [[Tampa Bay, Florida]] area in 1994. Rodney's eldest brother Gil<ref name=\"TBT090205\"/> went on to operate Times of Refreshing Ministries, an online evangelical ministry.<ref name=\"TORM\">{{cite web |title=Times of Refreshing Ministries:The Internet Ministry of Evangelists Gil & Loraine Howard-Browne \u2013 About Us |url=http://revivaltimes.com/about.html |accessdate=April 6, 2019}}</ref>. Likewise, his youngest brother Bazil established an eponymous evangelical ministry on 1 January 1994 with the professed aim of people achieving financial freedom through the special anointing of God <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bhbem.wordpress.com/2009/05/26/what-you-need-to-know-about-bazil-howard-browne/|title=What you need to know about Bazil Howard-Browne|date=May 26, 2009|accessdate=Mar 31, 2020}}</ref>. Prior to this he had worked alongside his brother Rodney for a year.\n\nIn 1996, Howard-Browne founded a church he named \"The River\" at Tampa Bay Church in [[Tampa, Florida]], serving as its pastor ever since.<ref name=\"TBT011005\">{{cite news |last1=Graham |first1=Kevin |title=Church's Hummer prize too worldly? |url=http://www.sptimes.com/2005/01/10/Hillsborough/Church_s_Hummer_prize.shtml |accessdate=April 5, 2019 |publisher=[[Tampa Bay Times]] |date=January 10, 2005 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180326000430/http://www.sptimes.com/2005/01/10/Hillsborough/Church_s_Hummer_prize.shtml |archivedate=March 26, 2018}}</ref> Howard-Browne and his wife also founded Revival Ministries International in 1997, as well as River Bible Institute and River School of Worship.<ref>Howard-Browne, Rodney [https://www.revival.com/about \"About us\"] Revival.com</ref>\n\nHoward-Browne\u2019s services are characterized by [[faith healing|laying on of hands]] with worshipers giggling in apparent [[spiritual drunkenness]], [[speaking in tongues]], emitting animal noises, breaking into uncontrollable [[holy laughter]], shaking, dancing in the aisles, or falling to the ground.<ref name=\"TBT\"/><ref name=\"M&G\"/><ref name=\"carnes\"/><ref name=ravitz/><ref name=\"VOA\">{{cite news |last1=Socolovsky |first1=Jerome |title=African-born Pastor Brings \u2018Holy Laughter\u2019 Revival to Washington |url=https://www.voanews.com/a/african-born-pastor-brings-holy-laughter-revival-to-washington/1954365.html|accessdate=April 5, 2019 |publisher=[[Voice of America]] |date=July 9, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"NunNews\">{{cite news |last1=Rohner |first1=Thomas |title=Conspiracy-theorizing megachurch preacher visits Nunavut|url=https://nunatsiaq.com/stories/article/conspiracy-theorizing-megachurch-preacher-visits-nunavut/ |accessdate=January 4, 2020 |publisher=[[Nunatsiaq News]] |date=September 5, 2019 |quote=Howard-Browne also spoke in tongues, which he claimed was once understood in the obscure native dialect of a Papua New Guinea pastor}}</ref> He refers to himself as \"God's bartender\" and the \"holy ghost bartender\".<ref name=\"carnes\">Carnes, Tony. [http://www.christianitytoday.com/ct/1999/august9/9t913a.html \"Howard-Browne Takes New York.\"] Christianity Today, August 9, 1999</ref><ref name=\"TBT\">{{cite news|url=http://tampabayonline.net/reports/minister/homealt.htm|title=The Holy Ghost Bartender|last=Bearden|first=Michelle|date=1999-06-28|newspaper=[[The Tampa Tribune]]|accessdate=2019-02-23|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120707031815/http://tampabayonline.net/reports/minister/homealt.htm|archivedate=2012-07-07|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nHoward-Browne is credited with introducing holy laughter to [[Carpenter's Home Church]] in [[Lakeland, Florida]] during a series of revival services with Karl Strader in 1993. The holy laughter revivals later spread to nearby churches in Melbourne, Titusville, Stuart and Vero Beach, Florida.<ref name=\"OS090196\">{{cite news |last1=Pinsky |first1=Mark I |title=When Holy Laughter Starts, Some Find It Hard To Stop |url=https://www.orlandosentinel.com/news/os-xpm-1996-09-01-9608310934-story.html |accessdate=April 6, 2019 |publisher=[[Orlando Sentinel]] |date=September 1, 1996}}</ref><ref name=\"Ledger051808\">{{cite news |last1=McMullen |first1=Cary |title=Florida Outpouring: Internet Draws Thousands to Lakeland Revival |url= https://www.theledger.com/article/LK/20080518/News/608117817/LL/ |accessdate=April 6, 2019 |publisher=[[The Ledger]] |date=May 18, 2008}}</ref> Howard-Browne is credited with bringing holy laughter to the charismatic Toronto Airport Vineyard Church (soon after expelled by its parent [[Association of Vineyard Churches|Vineyard Church]]) at a 1994 revival in [[Toronto, Canada]] with evangelist Randy Clark, known as the \u201c[[Toronto Blessing]],\" and then a year later, to [[Assemblies of God]] (AOG) Brownsville Church in [[Pensacola, Florida]] with evangelist [[Steve Hill (evangelist)|Steve Hill]].  The event became known in Christian circles as the [[Brownsville Revival]].<ref name=\"OS090196\"/><ref name=\"Ledger051808\"/><ref name=\"Time062401\">{{cite news |last1=Ostling |first1=Richard N |title=Laughing for the Lord |url=http://content.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,164903,00.html |accessdate=April 6, 2019 |publisher=[[Time Magazine]] |date=June 24, 2001}}</ref> Howard-Browne also ministered under pastor Mike Rose at the Juneau Christian Center (formerly known as the Bethel Assembly of God) in [[Juneau, Alaska]], an AOG church that [[Sarah Palin]] later attended after becoming governor of Alaska.<ref name=\"HuffPo101208\">{{cite news |last1=Wilson |first1=Bruce |title=Palin and the Holy Laughter Anointing |url=https://www.huffpost.com/entry/palin-and-the-holy-laught_b_125582 |accessdate=April 6, 2019 |publisher=[[Huffington Post]] |date=October 12, 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"NPR090508\">{{cite news |last1=Bradley Hagerty |first1=Barbara |title=Examining Palin's Pentecostal Background |url=https://www.npr.org/templates/story/story.php?storyId=94332540 |accessdate=April 6, 2019 |publisher=[[NPR]] |date=September 5, 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"Hapers083008\">{{cite news |last1=Silverstein |first1=Ken |title=Palin and Her Pastors: \"Those that die without Christ have a horrible, horrible surprise\" |url=https://harpers.org/blog/2008/08/palin-and-her-pastors-those-that-die-without-christ-have-a-horrible-horrible-surprise/ |accessdate=April 6, 2019 |publisher=[[Harper's Magazine]] |date=August 30, 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"Newsweek102708\">{{cite web |last1=Miller |first1=Lisa |title=What Are Sarah Palin\u2019s Religious Beliefs? |url=https://www.newsweek.com/what-are-sarah-palins-religious-beliefs-91785 |website=[[Newsweek]] |accessdate=April 6, 2019 |date=October 27, 2008}}</ref>\n\nHoward-Browne first came to national prominence in the US in 1999 when his Revival Ministries organization rented [[Madison Square Garden]] in New York City for six weeks. The event, called Good News New York, was described as \u201can effort to achieve a Billy Graham-style faith uprising\u201d, but was \u201cderided in local media as a giant flop\u201d. It was estimated to cost up to $10 million but only 3,000 people were counted in attendance at the 19,000-seat arena.<ref name=\"M&G\"/><ref name=\"carnes\"/><ref name=\"TBT\"/> Investigative journalists in his home town of Tampa reported at the time that since arriving from South Africa almost penniless in December 1989, his sudden wealth included a boat, a [[Harley Davidson]] motorcycle, a home in one of Tampa\u2019s exclusive gated communities and access to a private jet; however, they were unable to find evidence of financial wrongdoing.<ref name=\"M&G\"/><ref name=\"TBT\"/>\n\nHoward-Browne\u2019s daughter Kelly died due to cystic fibrosis on Christmas Day, 25 December 2002, at the age of 18. He then vowed that \u201csince the devil has taken their daughter with this dreaded disease, he would pay with one million souls over the next ten years\u201d.<ref name=\"Kambulow\"/><ref name=\"TBT122802\">{{cite news |title=Kelly Howard-Browne Obituary |url=https://www.legacy.com/obituaries/tampabaytimes/obituary.aspx?n=kelly-howard-browne&pid=680575 |accessdate=April 6, 2019 |publisher=[[Tampa Bay Times]] |date=December 28, 2002}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, it was reported that Howard-Browne\u2019s River Church had hosted political meetings for the Florida chapter of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] during the preceding two years, including a rally for then presidential candidate [[Newt Gingrich]], at which Howard-Browne called for a national \"rising\" of Christian Americans \"that will not sit idly by and allow the killing of unborn babies and allow Islam to take over this country\". At the same event, he described [[Mormonism]] as a \"cult\" that, in the 19th century, \"had death squads that would go around killing everybody that was not a Mormon\". He later recanted, saying Mormons were \"honourable people\".<ref name=\"M&G\"/>\n\nHoward-Browne published ''The Killing of Uncle Sam: The Demise of the United States of America'', which was scheduled to be released in May 2018, and announced that proceeds from sales of the book would go to the River School of Government, a degree granting program, operated by Howard-Browne and his wife under the auspices of Revival Ministries, that funds training for people seeking to run for political office.<ref name=\"DFP\">{{cite news |last1=McGregor |first1=Grady |title=Controversial pastor visits Dickinson: Rival pastor from Montana dragged from church after protesting |url=https://www.thedickinsonpress.com/news/4360976-controversial-pastor-visits-dickinson-rival-pastor-montana-dragged-church-after |accessdate=January 4, 2020 |publisher=[[Dickinson Press]] |date=November 17, 2017}}</ref>  \n\nHoward-Browne's evangelical movement has been rejected as cult-like by many mainstream Christian organisations, and it has been described as \"a combination of brimstone and fire about God\u2019s power, sprinkled with hipster references and a conviction that church\u2014like Disneyland\u2014should be 'the happiest place on earth'.\"<ref name=\"M&G\"/> The Christian Research Institute labelled his operation a \u201ccult\u201d and called the him \"a good stage hypnotist\" who has made millions from vulnerable believers.<ref name=\"M&G\"/> According to ''[[The Tampa Tribune]]'', critics have described him as \"a manipulator leading followers into a cult; a circus ring leader making a good living.\"<ref name=\"TBT\"/>\n\n==Statements and controversies==\n===Diploma mill doctorate===\nHoward-Browne claimed to have earned a \"doctorate of ministry degree\" in 1992  from \"The School of Bible Theology\", a [[non-accredited]] Pentecostal correspondence school in San Jacinto, California that has been described as a \"[[diploma mill]]\".<ref name=TBT/><ref name=\"AI1\">{{cite news|last1=Kowalski|first1=David|title=\"Name it and Frame it\" \u2014 Phony Doctorates in the Church|url=http://www.apologeticsindex.org/2794-name-it-and-frame-it-phony-doctorates-in-the-church|accessdate=May 3, 2018|publisher=Apologetics Index|date=2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dSur1KLjWIUC&source=gbs_navlinks_s|last1=Stokes |first1=Jerry |title=Joseph Smith and Word of Faith Movement |page=21 |accessdate=April 4, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Kambulow\">{{cite book |last1=Kambulow |first1=Walter |title=The Best of the Kambulows |date=June 1, 2003 |page=879 |url=https://books.google.com/books/about/THE_BEST_OF_THE_KAMBULOW.html?id=YS3cAgAAQBAJ |accessdate=April 4, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Multi-level marketing: Monavie and Jeunesse===\nHoward-Browne and his wife Adonica were top-ranking (\u201cBlack Diamond executive level\u201d) distributors for [[Monavie]], a [[multi-level marketing]] company that sold [[acai berry]] juice-based beverages until folding in 2014 subsequent to a $182 million loan default and allegations of [[pyramid scheme|pyramid scheming]], fraudulent advertising, and [[patent infringement]].<ref>{{cite web |title=MV Three Sixty Five Magazine |url=https://www.team-legacy.info/PDF/MV365_Magazine.pdf |accessdate=April 4, 2019 |pages=86}}</ref><ref name=\"YT\">{{cite news|title=Rodney and Adonica Howard-Browne MonaVie Black Diamond|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=jdXhteTaPpE|accessdate=May 2, 2018|agency=YouTube|publisher=[[Monavie|Monavie Corporate]]|date=March 18, 2009}}</ref><ref name=imagenetixdocket>{{cite web| title = Imagenetix, Inc. vs. Monavie LLC et al. | publisher = [[United States District Court]] for the Southern District of California | date = May 2, 2018 | url = https://ia800205.us.archive.org/20/items/gov.uscourts.casd.269686/gov.uscourts.casd.269686.1.0.pdf| accessdate = 2008-09-20}}</ref> As of 2016, Howard-Browne also served as a \"North America Emerald Director\" for the multi-level marketing company Jeunesse.<ref name=\"Jeunesse\">{{cite web |title=Legacy Powered by Jeunesse |url=https://www.team-legacy.com/PDF/OurTeam-OurProducts.pdf |publisher=Jeunesse Global Holdings, LLC |accessdate=April 4, 2019 |page=41 |date=2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Allegation of plot to attack Donald Trump ===\nIn July 2017, Howard-Browne was one of 17 evangelical pastors who visited the [[White House]] to pray for and [[laying on of hands|lay hands]] on President [[Donald Trump]].<ref name=\"KCS\">{{cite news|last1=Gutierrez|first1=Lisa|title=\u2018Great spiritual awakening\u2019: Pastors lay hands on Donald Trump in the Oval Office|url=http://www.kansascity.com/news/nation-world/article160904779.html|accessdate=May 2, 2018|publisher=[[The Kansas City Star]]|date=July 12, 2017}}</ref> In a video several days later, Howard-Browne stated that \u201cthere is a planned attack on our president and that\u2019s all I can tell you about right now; I know what I\u2019m talking about, I\u2019ve spoken to high-ranking people in the government\".<ref>{{cite web\n | url = http://www.rightwingwatch.org/post/rodney-howard-browne-prayed-over-trump-in-order-to-avert-a-planned-attack-on-our-president/\n | title = Rodney Howard-Browne Prayed Over Trump In Order To Avert \u2018A Planned Attack On Our President\u2019 \n | last = Mantyla\n | first = Kyle\n | date = July 17, 2017\n | website = Right Wing Watch\n | publisher = People for the American Way\n | access-date = December 21, 2017\n | quote = There is a planned attack on our president,\" he said, \u201cand that\u2019s all I can tell you about right now; I know what I\u2019m talking about, I\u2019ve spoken to high-ranking people in the government and this is being planned by people that hate God, hate America, hate our president and we have to stop this, in Jesus name.\u201d}}</ref> Howard-Browne later said that the Secret Service met with him to discover which congressman told him about the plot but he refused to say, citing pastoral privilege.<ref>\n {{cite web\n  | url = http://www.rightwingwatch.org/post/its-not-my-problem-rodney-howard-browne-refused-to-provide-the-secret-service-with-details-of-a-plot-again-trump/\n  | title = Pastor Who Claimed His Prayers Averted Anti-Trump Attack Refuses To Provide Details To Secret Service Because It\u2019s \u2018Not My Problem\u2019\n  | last = Mantyla\n  | first = Kyle\n  | date = July 31, 2017\n  | website = Right Wing Watch\n  | publisher = Right Wing Watch\n  | access-date = 21 December 2017\n | quote = Somebody reported me to the Secret Service, so they came over\u201d he claimed. \u201cThree guys, we sat and talked; very nice people and they wanted to know who the congressman was. I said, \u2018I can\u2019t tell you that, it was pastoral privilege.\u2019 I said, \u2018I prayed for him\u2019 and he said, \u2018So, it was like a confession?\u2019 I said, \u2018Yeah, I can\u2019t tell you. I\u2019m not going to tell you, I can\u2019t tell you, it\u2019s impossible.'\u201d \u201cIf the Secret Service in Washington, D.C., don\u2019t know what\u2019s coming down, then why should somebody from Tampa?\u201d Howard-Browne added. \u201cThis is a senior member of Congress. If he actually knew anything, he would inform the Secret Service himself. It\u2019s not my problem.}}</ref> Howard-Browne praised God for giving America a 'Rambo'.<ref name=\"Right Wing Watch\">{{cite news |title=Rodney Howard-Browne Thanks God For Giving America \u2018A Rambo\u2019 In Trump|url=http://www.rightwingwatch.org/post/rodney-howard-browne-thanks-god-for-giving-america-a-rambo-in-trump/|date=18 May 2018| accessdate=4 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2016, Howard-Browne wrote a Facebook post titled \u201cDonald Trump Is the New World Order\u2019s Worst Nightmare,\u201d where he detailed his choice to back Trump in the election as a check against a global conspiracy to destroy America.<ref name=\"Weaver\">{{cite news |last1=Weaver |first1=Hilary |title=Donald Trump\u2019s Oval Office Prayer Circle, Explained |url=https://www.vanityfair.com/style/2017/07/donald-trump-oval-office-prayer-circle-explained |publisher=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]|accessdate=April 4, 2019 |date=July 12, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Hurricane Irma===\nIn September 2017, Howard-Browne received media attention after referring to [[Hurricane Irma]]\u2014a [[List of Category 4 Atlantic hurricanes|category 4]] storm that caused the death of 50 people in the U.S. and Caribbean and resulted in power outages affecting 5.5 million people in Florida\u2014as a \"nothingburger\". He further stated that \"prayer took the teeth out of the storm\".<ref name=\"Newsweek091217\">{{cite news |last1=Gaffey |first1=Conor |title=Hurricane Irma Was A Nothingburger, Says Pastor Who Prayed Over Trump At White House |url=https://www.newsweek.com/hurricane-irma-florida-trump-rodney-howard-browne-663594 |accessdate=April 4, 2019 |publisher=[[Newsweek]] |date=September 12, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Alleging human sacrifice===\nIn an October 2017 sermon at The River at Tampa Bay church, Howard-Browne alleged that \"They sacrifice children at the highest levels in Hollywood. They drink blood of young kids. This is a fact\", continuing, \"The human sacrifice and the cannibalism has been going on for years\" in Hollywood and Washington, D.C.<ref>\n{{cite web\n | url = https://www.charismanews.com/56-video/67850-rodney-howard-browne-hollywood-execs-are-full-of-the-devil-drink-the-blood-of-young-kids\n | title = Rodney Howard Browne: Hollywood Execs Are 'Full of the Devil,' 'Drink the Blood of Young Kids'\n | last = Justice\n | first = Jessilyn\n | date = October 20, 2017 \n | website = Charisma News\n | publisher = Charisma Media\n | access-date = December 21, 2017\n | quote = \"They sacrifice children at the highest levels in Hollywood. They drink blood of young kids. This is a fact. That's why the next thing to be exposed will be all the pedophilia that is going to come out of Hollywood and come out of Washington, D.C. The human sacrifice and the cannibalism has been going on for years\"}}</ref><ref>\n {{cite web\n  | url = https://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/rodney-howard-browne-hollywood-devil-worship_us_59e96616e4b0f9d35bc9a27b\n  | title = Trump-Linked Pastor: Hollywood Is Full Of Satanists Who Drink Children\u2019s Blood\n  | last = Mazza\n  | first = Ed\n  | date = October 20, 2017\n  | website = Huffpost\n  | publisher = Oath Inc.\n  | access-date = December 21, 2017\n | quote = }}\n</ref><ref name=\"CT102017\">{{cite news |last1=Macintyre |first1=James |title=Pastor who prayed over Donald Trump says Hollywood is full of devil worshippers who drink children's blood |url=https://www.christiantoday.com/article/pastor-who-prayed-over-donald-trump-says-hollywood-is-full-of-devil-worshippers-who-drink-childrens-blood/116518.htm |accessdate=April 4, 2019 |publisher=[[Christian Today]] |date=October 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Arming of the River at Tampa Bay church===\nHoward-Browne drew attention for a social media post in November 2017, two days after the [[Sutherland Springs church shooting]], stating that his church was not a gun-free zone and that he and the church\u2019s pastors \u201care all heavily armed\u201d and would use \u201cdeadly force\u201d.<ref name=\"WaPo_112117\">{{cite news |last1=Eltagouri |first1=Marwa |title=This church has a warning for visitors: \u2018WE ARE HEAVILY ARMED \u2014 The Pastors\u2019 |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/acts-of-faith/wp/2017/11/21/a-florida-church-has-a-warning-for-visitors-this-is-not-a-gun-free-zone-the-pastors/?noredirect=on |accessdate=April 4, 2019 |publisher=[[Washington Post]] |date=November 21, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"SJ\">{{cite news|last1=Denker|first1=Angela|title='We Are Heavily Armed. -The Pastors'|url=https://sojo.net/articles/we-are-heavily-armed-pastors|accessdate=May 2, 2018|publisher=[[Sojourners]]|date=April 18, 2018}}</ref><ref name=\"CBN112017\">{{cite news|last1=Aaron|first1=Charlene|title=After Deadly Church Shooting, Rodney Howard-Browne's Church Warns 'We Are Heavily Armed'|url=http://www1.cbn.com/cbnnews/us/2017/november/after-deadly-church-shooting-rodney-howard-brownes-church-warns-we-are-are-heavily-armed|accessdate=May 2, 2018|publisher=[[Christian Broadcasting Network]]|date=November 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Conspiracy theories on InfoWars===\nIn March 2018, Howard-Browne made an appearance on [[Alex Jones]]' [[InfoWars]] program during which he claimed: that a string of [[Austin bombings|bombings in Austin, Texas]] were being used by \"anarchist terrorists\" in an attempt to bring \"everything under control\"; that churches and religious groups were being censored in the U.S.; and that \"globalist gremlins\" were attempting to thwart Donald Trump.<ref name=\"RWW\">{{cite news|last1=Holt|first1=Jared|title=Rodney Howard-Browne Says Only \u2018Divine Intervention\u2019 Can Save America|url=http://www.rightwingwatch.org/post/rodney-howard-browne-says-only-divine-intervention-can-save-america/|accessdate=May 2, 2018|publisher=[[Right Wing Watch]]|date=March 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Christchurch Mosque shootings===\nShortly after the [[Christchurch mosque shootings]] in March 2019, Howard-Browne tweeted his opinion that it was a '[[false flag]]' operation: \"There is no doubt that what happened in New Zealand as horrific as it is, is a false flag that will be blamed on conservatives when it\u2019s all said and done!  Only a total nutjob lunatic, insane demonized freak goes into a building and kills people, it\u2019s unacceptable on every level!\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rawstory.com/2019/03/megachurch-pastor-invited-trumps-white-house-declares-new-zealand-terror-attack-false-flag/|title=Megachurch pastor who was invited to Trump\u2019s White House declares New Zealand terror attack a \u2018false flag\u2019|first=Brad|last=Reed|website=www.rawstory.com}}</ref>\n\n===Iqaluit sermon===\nOn August 27, 2019, Howard-Browne delivered a sermon in the [[Canadian Arctic]] territory of [[Nunavut]] as part of a 300-city tour. He preached for over an hour at an [[Iqaluit]] church to a mostly [[Inuit]] audience of more than 100 people. The event featured a call for donations, including a video of Howard-Browne claiming \u201cGod loves a generous giver,\u201d which ''[[Nunatsiaq News]]'' criticized on the basis that poverty is widespread in the city and nearly half of Nunavut\u2019s population relies on social assistance amidst long-standing crises in food security and housing.<ref name=\"NunNews\"/> The news outlet also noted that he \u201clashed out\u201d at and \u201charangued\u201d audience members who tried to leave before the end of the sermon. Commenting after the event, [[Anglican bishop]] for the Arctic, [[David Parsons (bishop)|David Parsons]], described Howard-Browne as an [[extremist]].\n\n===Coronavirus pandemic===\n{{see also|Misinformation related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\nHoward-Browne kept his church open during the  [[2019-2020 coronavirus pandemic]] and on March 15 told his congregants to continue shaking hands because they were \u201crevivalists, not pansies\u201d. He also claimed in his sermon that the pandemic was a \u201cphantom plague\u201d engineered by the Rockefeller Foundation to shut down churches and force people to receive a vaccine that would cause mass deaths, all as part of a population control scheme.<ref name=\"NW_031620\">{{cite news |last1=Palmer |first1=Evan |title=Conservative pastor says his church 'will never close' because of coronavirus: 'we're raising up revivalists, not pansies' |url=https://www.newsweek.com/coronavirus-rodney-howard-browne-florida-pastor-pansies-1492460 |accessdate=March 16, 2020 |publisher=[[Newsweek]] |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Indep_031620\">{{cite news |last1=Naughtie |first1=Andrew |title=Coronavirus: US conservatives spark backlash after socialising against official health advice |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/americas/coronavirus-republican-kevin-stitt-restaurant-social-distancing-tweet-restaurant-a9404346.html |accessdate=March 16, 2020 |publisher=[[The Independent]] |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rightwingwatch.org/post/rodney-howard-browne-coronavirus-pandemic-is-a-globalist-plot-to-kill-people-with-vaccines/|title=Rodney Howard-Browne: Coronavirus Pandemic Is a Globalist Plot to Kill People With Vaccines|first1=Kyle Mantyla &#124;|last1=March 16|first2=2020 10:24|last2=Am|website=Right Wing Watch|accessdate=Mar 31, 2020}}</ref> Several weeks prior, Howard-Browne claimed in a video that he would cure Florida of coronavirus.<ref name=\"OW_022620\">{{cite news |last1=Wolf |first1=Colin |title=Tampa pastor who claimed to cure Zika now says he will cure Florida of coronavirus |url=https://www.orlandoweekly.com/Blogs/archives/2020/02/26/tampa-pastor-who-claimed-to-cure-zika-now-says-he-will-cure-florida-of-coronavirus |accessdate=March 16, 2020 |publisher=[[Orlando Weekly]] |date=February 26, 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn March 29, 2020, Howard-Browne's congregation received a visit from the [[Hillsborough County Sheriff's Office]] about his violations of the county's safer-at-home order, which limited public gatherings to 10 people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/RightWingWatch/status/1244636146073812995|title=Right-wing pastor Rodney Howard-Browne has repeatedly stated that he will never cancel services at his The River church in Tampa. Now it looks like he received a visit from the local sheriff's office after holding services yesterday.pic.twitter.com/ABFYq4RtCg|first=|last=Right Wing Watch|date=Mar 30, 2020|accessdate=Mar 31, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"NBCN033020\"/> The next day, Hillsborough County Sheriff Chad Chronister announced that he had issued an arrest warrant to Howard-Browne for unlawful assembly and for violating rules regarding public health emergencies after Howard-Browne continued to hold large church services in defiance of the public order.<ref name=\"NYT033020\">{{cite news |last1=Mazzei |first1=Patricia |title=Florida Pastor Arrested After Defying Virus Orders |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/30/us/coronavirus-pastor-arrested-tampa-florida.html |accessdate=April 1, 2020 |publisher=[[New York Times]] |date=March 30, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"TBT033020\">{{cite news |last1=Marrero |first1=Tony |title=Pastor of Tampa church that held two large Sunday services arrested, jailed |url=https://www.tampabay.com/news/health/2020/03/30/tampa-church-holds-packed-service-draws-warning-from-sheriffs-office/ |accessdate=April 1, 2020 |publisher=[[Tampa Bay Times]] |date=March 30, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/HCSOSheriff/videos/230907918296583/|title=Hillsborough County Sheriff's Office on Facebook Watch|accessdate=Mar 31, 2020|via=www.facebook.com}}</ref><ref>Mantyla, Kyle (March 30, 2020). \"[https://www.rightwingwatch.org/post/arrest-warrant-issued-for-rodney-howard-browne-for-hosting-church-services-amid-the-coronavirus-outbreak/ Arrest Warrant Issued for Rodney Howard-Browne for Hosting Church Services Amid Coronavirus Pandemic]\". [[Right Wing Watch]].</ref> Chronister said he had no choice but to take action against Howard-Browne, stating \"His reckless disregard for human life put hundreds of people from his congregation at risk and thousands of residents who may interact with them this week.\"<ref name=\"NBCN033020\">{{cite news |last1=Li |first1=David K |title=Florida pastor arrested after holding church services despite coronavirus orders |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/florida-pastor-arrested-after-holding-church-services-despite-coronavirus-orders-n1172276 |accessdate=April 1, 2020 |publisher=[[NBC News]] |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref> \n\nOn March 30, 2020, Howard-Browne was arrested and jailed for unlawful assembly and for violating health and safety rules, with each charge carrying a maximum penalty of 60 days in jail and a $500 fine.<ref name=\"TBT033020\"/><ref name=\"NYT033020\"/> He was released from jail after posting a $500 bond.<ref>Sommer, Will and Connor, Tracy (March 30, 2020). \"[https://www.thedailybeast.com/hillsborough-sheriff-to-arrest-rodney-howard-browne-megachurch-pastor-who-flouted-virus-rules|Rodney Howard-Browne, Megachurch Pastor Who Flouted Virus Rules, Arrested.]\" [[The Daily Beast]].</ref>\n\nOn April 1, Howard-Browne said that he would not open his church the following weekend over fear of his congregation\u2019s safety and to protect them from \u201cgovernment tyranny.\"<ref name=\"OW040320\">{{cite news |last1=Wolf |first1=Colin |title=Orlando lawyer for pastor who held services during coronavirus outbreak says church lost its insurance |url=https://m.orlandoweekly.com/Blogs/archives/2020/04/03/orlando-lawyer-for-pastor-who-held-services-during-coronavirus-outbreak-says-church-lost-its-insurance |accessdate=April 11, 2020 |publisher=[[Orlando Weekly]] |date=April 3, 2020}}</ref> However, his lawyer, [[Mathew Staver]] of the law firm [[Liberty Counsel]], said that Howard-Browne\u2019s arrest earlier in the week had led to the pastor\u2019s insurance policy being cancelled.<ref name=\"OW040320\"/><ref name=\"NBCN041020\">{{cite news |last1=Siemaszko |first1=Corky |title=Florida megachurch pastor caves after defying coronavirus rules |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/florida-megachurch-pastor-caves-after-defying-coronavirus-rules-n1181491 |accessdate=April 11, 2020 |publisher=[[NBC News]] |date=April 10, 2020}}</ref> Howard-Browne also claimed and that he had received death threats. The pastor held open the possibility that the church would be open for [[Easter]] services but then announced on April 9 that it would instead be closed.<ref name=\"NBCN041020\"/>\n\n== Publications ==\n*''The Killing of Uncle Sam: The Demise of the United States of America'' by Rodney Howard-Browne and [[Paul L. Williams (author)|Paul L. Williams]]\n*''How to Increase and Release the Anointing'' Rodney Howard-Browne-Word and Spirit Publishing (2018)\n*''Manifesting the Holy Ghost to You, in You, and Through You'' Rodney Howard-Browne-Word and Spirit Publishing (2018)\n*''How to Increase and Release the Anointing'' Rodney Howard-Browne-Word and Spirit Publishing (2018)\n*''School of the Spirit'' Rodney Howard-Browne-Word and Spirit Publishing (2018)\n*''The Touch of God: A Practical Handbook on the Anointing'' Rodney Howard-Browne-Word and Spirit Publishing (2018)\n*''Seeing Jesus as He Really Is'' Rodney Howard-Browne-Word and Spirit Publishing (2018)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.revival.com Revival Ministries International website]\n*[https://www.riverschoolofgovernment.com River School of Government]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Howard-Browne, Rodney}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1961 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century Christian mystics]]\n[[Category:Christian revivalists]]\n[[Category:Conspiracy theorists]]\n[[Category:Faith healers]]\n[[Category:People from the Eastern Cape]]\n[[Category:South African Charismatics]]\n[[Category:South African clergy]]\n[[Category:21st-century Christian mystics]]\n[[Category:20th-century Christian clergy]]\n[[Category:21st-century Christian clergy]]\n", "name_user": "Rhode Island Red", "label": "safe", "comment": "parameter fix", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rodney_Howard-Browne"}
{"title_page": "Oriza Hirata", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name = Oriza Hirata<br />\u5e73\u7530\u30aa\u30ea\u30b6\n| image = Oriza Hirata speaking at Tokyo Kaikan, September 2013.JPG\n| imagesize = 240px\n| caption = in [[Tokyo]] <br />(September, 2013)\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1962|11|08}}\n| birth_place = [[Tokyo]], [[Japan]]\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| death_cause =\n| known_for = ''T\u014dky\u014d Notes'', ''Citizens of Seoul''\n| nationality = [[Japanese people|Japanese]]\n| occupation = Playwright, director, academic\n| years_active = 1989-present\n| religion  = \n| spouse = \n| website = {{URL|http://www.seinendan.org/eng/oriza/}}\n}}\n\n{{nihongo|'''Oriza Hirata'''|\u5e73\u7530\u30aa\u30ea\u30b6|Hirata Oriza|born on 8 November 1962, in [[Tokyo]]}} is a Japanese playwright, director, and academic. For the majority of his life, he has been best known for his work in theater and creating what he has coined, \u201ccontemporary colloquial theater,\u201d or as theater critics call it, \u201cquiet drama.\u201d<ref name=Rimer>Rimer, J. Thomas, Mitsuya M\u014dri, and M. Cody Poulton. The Columbia Anthology of Modern Japanese Drama. New York: Columbia UP, 2014. Print.</ref>\n\n==Career==\nOriza Hirata graduated from [[International Christian University]] as a part of their Humanities division.<ref name=Shinsai>{{cite journal|last1=Hirata|first1=Oriza|title=Sayonara II|journal=Shinsai Only 3/11/12|date=11 March 2012|page=40}}</ref> In 1983, he formed the Seinendan Theater Company, which he established in order to practice contemporary colloquial theater. In 1984, Seinendan settled into using the Komaba Agora Theater as their main base of operations. Hirata remains as the theater's primary artistic director and has continued to play a major role in the theater's management.<ref name=Komaba>{{cite web|title=Komaba Agora Theater|url=http://www.seinendan.org/eng/agora/|website=Seinendan|publisher=Agora Kikaku|accessdate=7 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nHirata's first play, {{nihongo|''Citizens of Seoul''|\u30bd\u30a6\u30eb\u5e02\u6c11|''Seoul shimin''}},<ref name=\"Play list\">{{cite web|last1=Hirata|first1=Oriza|title=Play List|url=http://www.seinendan.org/eng/play/|website=Seinendan|publisher=Agora Kikaku|accessdate=7 June 2015}}</ref> first premiered in 1989, and has remained one of his most famous plays. 6 Years later, in 1994, he debuted {{nihongo|''T\u014dky\u014d Notes''|\u6771\u4eac\u30ce\u30fc\u30c8|''T\u014dky\u014d n\u014dto''}},<ref name=\"Play list\" /> which is still considered his magnum opus.<ref name=Rimer /> As a playwright, Hirata has continued to write and direct plays both at Komaba Agora theater, as well as theaters in Europe, the Americas, and other parts of Asia. He is also known for doing international collaborations both in Japan and all around the world, where he has worked with a multitude of playwrights and artists to introduce his own work to new audiences, as well as introduce foreign work to Japan.<ref name=International>{{cite web|title=International|website=Seinendan|publisher=Agora Kikaku}}</ref>\n\nHirata worked at Obirin University for six years as a professor in their theater department before moving onto [[Osaka University]], where he works in their communication-design and robotics departments.<ref name=\"Hirata education\">{{cite web|title=Education|url=http://www.seinendan.org/eng/oriza/education.php|website=Seinendan|publisher=Agora Kikaku|accessdate=7 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Contemporary colloquial theater==\n\nContemporary colloquial theater is a theatrical style Oriza Hirata founded as an answer to the \u201cboisterous and festive nature of 1980s Japanese theater.\u201d<ref name=Rimer /> This style emphasizes colloquial Japanese language use that is designed to sound distinctly typical of the linguistic tendencies and patterns of everyday Japanese speaking. As a result, his plays oftentimes feature multiple characters talking at once, sentence fragments, inaudible speech, and an understated, \"normal\" speaking tone. This style informs his plays stylistically, both in language and plot, in the sense that Hirata emphasizes [[realism (theatre)|realism]] throughout.<ref name=Rimer/> However, Hirata has preferred his own stylistic title of \"contemporary colloquial theater\" because he thinks that relatable terms like [[Shingeki]] or [[realism (theatre)|realism]] \"sounded too much like the Western drama that [they] emulated.\"<ref name=\"Poulton mjt\">{{cite book|last1=Poulton|first1=M. Cody|title=Modern Japanese Theatre and Performance|date=2006|publisher=Lexington Books|location=Lanham, MD|isbn=978-0-7391-1152-9|pages=26\u201330}}</ref> \nHirata's style is partially due to his identification the impact of Western style was having on Japanese arts. As a reaction, he has sought to create an artistic style more representative of typical Japanese language and culture. As a playwright, he founded the Seinendan theater company in 1983 as a way to push his acting style into the greater Japanese and international theatre scenes.<ref name=Rimer/>\nHirata has worked closely with international actors when translating his work to preserve the Japanese identity of the speech, which has particularly resonated with French audiences.<ref name=Hirata>Hirata, Oriza. \"Artist Interview: Speaking with Oriza Hirata, a New Opinion Leader in the World of Contemporary Theater.\" Interview by Akihiko Senda. Performing Arts Network Japan. The Japan Foundation, 23 Mar. 2007. Web. 28 Apr. 2015.</ref> This style also tends to emphasize a small, intimate set of characters\u2014usually represented by the actors playing the role of a family\u2014to serve as a \u201cmicrocosm of Japanese society as a whole.\u201d <ref name=Rimer/> Japanese theater scholar, M. Cody Poulton, describes Hirata's style as an emphasis of the Greek idea of ''ethos'', \"the prevalent tone of sentiment of a people or community; the genius of an institution or system.\"<ref name=\"Poulton mjt\" />\n\n==Interdisciplinary work==\n\nAfter working at Obirin University as a theater professor, Oriza Hirata moved to work for [[Osaka University]], where he collaborated in the scientific fields of communication-design and robotics.<ref>\"Oriza Hirata.\" ORIZA HIRATA: SEINENDAN. Seinendan, n.d. Web. 28 Apr. 2015.</ref>\n\nHirata has participated in designing university classes that emphasize the communication environment for different fields in order for them to perform more successfully.\n{{Quote|text=There are design elements and organizational elements that can encourage better communication in the doctor\u2019s office, such as the positions of the doctor\u2019s and the patient\u2019s chairs, the color of the walls, the lighting, and these elements can create an environment that encourages the patient to ask the doctor questions and bring out answers that can reduce medical/diagnostic error.|sign=Hirata Oriza|source=<ref name=Hirata/>}}\n\nFor robotics, Hirata used his theater experience to attempt to make robots that act similarly to humans. While his work has been used to generally fulfill this role, he has also brought his work in robotics back to the theater, where he has incorporated robots in plays to explore themes of humanity. His play, ''I, Worker'' uses two robots as main characters to explore this very idea. He has collaborated with robotics expert [[Hiroshi Ishiguro]] for his theatrical experiments using robots.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Posner|first1=Dassia N.|last2=Orenstein|first2=Claudia|last3=Bell|first3=John|title=The Routledge Companion to Puppetry and Material Performance|date=2014|publisher=Routledge|location=New York|isbn=978-0-415-70540-0|page=282}}</ref>\n\n==International work and acclaim==\n\nShortly after beginning his career as a playwright, Oriza Hirata has had a prolific international career\u2014both touring his work around the world, as well as staging foreign playwrights work at his own theater in Japan.\n\nBeginning in the early 2000s, Hirata's work started to garner international attention. With the help of Japan's Saison Foundation, a grant-making foundation that supports Japanese Theater, and [[Manhattan]]'s [[Nonprofit organization]] [[Japan Society (Manhattan)|Japan Society]], Hirata's most famous work, ''T\u014dky\u014d Notes'' was debuted in the [[United States]] in October 2000 in [[New York City]]. [[Japan Society (Manhattan)|Japan Society]]'s theater series, Japanese Theatre NOW, has helped bring a number of contemporary Japanese dramas to the [[United States]], Hirata's being notable since ''T\u014dky\u014d Notes'' was one of the first.<ref name=Thornbury>{{cite book|last1=Thronbury|first1=Barbara|title=America's Japan and Japan's Performing Arts: Cultural Mobility and Exchange in New York, 1952\u20132011|date=2013|publisher=The University of Michigan Press|location=Ann Arbor, MI|isbn=978-0-472-11885-4|pages=17\u201319}}</ref>\n\nSince then, Hirata's work and company have traveled much of the world, including [[France]], [[Belgium]], [[Switzerland]], [[Ireland]], [[Germany]], the [[United Kingdom]], [[Korea]], [[China]], [[Australia]], and [[Brazil]]. Hirata says that he believes he has \"done the best work in France,\" where \"the people in France have been very enthusiastic about [his] work.\" Both in [[France]] and [[Belgium]], Hirata has collaborated with international actors and directors to bring his theatrical work to an international audience, as well as creating new commissioned work as both a playwright and director.<ref name=International /><ref name=Hirata />\n\nHirata has also collaborated on many international works inside of [[Japan]], using his theater to stage plays by playwrights from [[France]], [[Switzerland]], [[Italy]], [[Spain]], the [[United States]], [[Korea]], and [[China]]. Hirata's admiration for the French theater scene can be seen with these collaborations as well, as he has tended to stage more French plays than any other country he has collaborated with.<ref name=International />\n\nA year after the [[Fukushima Daiichi nuclear disaster]], Hirata submitted a 10-minute play, along with 18 other American and Japanese artist, to be performed and documented in an event called Shinsai: Theaters For Japan.<ref name=\"Shinsai web\">{{cite web|title=SHINSAI: Theaters for Japan|url=https://www.tcg.org/shinsai/archive.cfm|website=Theatre Communications Group|publisher=Theatre Communications Group|accessdate=3 June 2015}}</ref> The event happened that the Great Hall at Cooper Union in [[New York City]]. Hirata's play, entitled \"Sayonara II\", tells the story of a partially-broken robot who is asked to read poems to the people who died after the disaster.<ref name=Shinsai />\n\n==Accolades==\n\n*39th [[Kishida Prize for Drama]] for his play ''T\u014dky\u014d Notes '' (1995).<ref name=Shinsai />\n*5th Yomiuru Theater Outstanding Director Award for producing Masataka Matsuda's play ''The Cape of the Moon'' (1998).<ref name=Shinsai />\n*9th Yomiuri Theater Award for Outstanding Production on his play ''Attacking Ueno Zoo for the Fourth Time'' (2002).<ref name=Shinsai />\n*Association Internationale des Critiques des Th\u00e9\u00e2tre Critique Award for his book ''Arts as the Basis of a Nation'' (2002).<ref name=Shinsai />\n*Winner of the Grand Prix of the 2nd Asahi Performing Arts Awards for his play ''Across the River in May'' (2003).<ref name=Shinsai />\n*Montblanc de la Culture Arts Patronage Award (2006).<ref name=Shinsai />\n\n==List of works==\n\n===Major works===\n*1989: {{nihongo|''Citizens of Seoul''|\u30bd\u30a6\u30eb\u5e02\u6c11|''Seoul shimin''}}:<ref name=\"Play list\" /> One of Hirata's earliest and most critically acclaimed works, ''Citizens of Seoul'' tackles Japan's superiority complex over Korea during their colonization.\n*1994: {{nihongo|''T\u014dky\u014d Notes''|\u6771\u4eac\u30ce\u30fc\u30c8|''T\u014dky\u014d n\u014dto''}}:<ref name=\"Play list\" /> Hirata's most famous and praised work around the world, ''T\u014dky\u014d Notes'' takes place in a museum where a number of people's personal lives are examined in order to gain a fuller picture of the political, social, and cultural context of a near-future Japan.\n*2002: {{nihongo|''The Yalta Conference''|\u30e4\u30eb\u30bf\u4f1a\u8ac7|''Yaruta kaidan''}}:<ref name=\"Play list\" /> Summarizing the world's history post-WWII, this is one of Hiraza's most grand dramas in terms of scope. [[Winston Churchill]], [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]], and [[Joseph Stalin]] are the only 3 characters in the play.\n\n===Recent works===\n*2009: {{nihongo|''Par-dessus bord -Tori no tobu takasa''|\u9ce5\u306e\u98db\u3076\u9ad8\u3055|''Tori no tubu takasa''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*2009: {{nihongo|''The Tongue-Cut Sparrow''|\u820c\u5207\u308a\u96c0|''Shitakiri Suzume''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*2009: {{nihongo|''Christmas in Tehran''|\u30af\u30ea\u30b9\u30de\u30b9 \u30a4\u30f3 \u30c6\u30d8\u30e9\u30f3|''Kurisumasu in Teheran''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*2008: {{nihongo|''I, Worker''|\u50cd\u304f\u79c1|''Hataraku Watashi''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*2008: {{nihongo|''A Long Night in the Tropics''|\u7720\u308c\u306a\u3044\u591c\u306a\u3093\u3066\u306a\u3044|''Nemurenai Yorunante nai''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*2008: {{nihongo|''A Cold Wind Blows through Cherry Blossoms''|\u98a8\u306e\u3064\u3081\u305f\u304d\u6afb\u304b\u306a|''Kaze no Tsumetaki Sakura kana''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*2008: {{nihongo|''In the Heart of a Forest''|\u68ee\u306e\u5965|''Mori no Oku''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*2007: {{nihongo|''Citizens of Seoul 1929: Graffiti''|\u30bd\u30a6\u30eb\u5e02\u6c11 \u662d\u548c\u671b\u90f7\u7de8|''Seoul Shimin Sh\u014dwa B\u014dky\u014d Hen''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*2007: {{nihongo|''Songs of Farewell''|\u5225\u308c\u306e\u5504|''Wakare no Uta''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n\n===Other notable works===\n*2005: {{nihongo|''Sand and Soldiers''|\u7802\u3068\u5175\u968a|''Sunato Heitai''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*2005: {{nihongo|''Conference before the Throne''|\u5fa1\u524d\u4f1a\u8b70 |''Gozen Kaigi''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*2003: {{nihongo|''No More Winds Blow''|\u3082\u3046\u98a8\u3082\u5439\u304b\u306a\u3044|''M\u014d Kazemo Fukanai''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*2003: {{nihongo|''The Journal of POWs''|\u5357\u5cf6\u4fd8\u865c\u8a18|''Nant\u014d Furyoki''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*2002: {{nihongo|''Across the River in May''|\u305d\u306e\u6cb3\u3092\u3053\u3048\u3066\u3001\u4e94\u6708|''Sono Kawa o Koete, Gogatsu''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*2001: {{nihongo|''Attacking the Ueno Zoo for the Fourth Time''|\u4e0a\u91ce\u52d5\u7269\u5712\u518d\u3005\u3005\u8972\u6483|''Ueno D\u014dbutsuen sai-sai-sai Sh\u016bgeki''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*2000: {{nihongo|''Suddenly Married''|\u96a3\u306b\u3044\u3066\u3082\u4e00\u4eba|''Tonari ni Itemo Hitori''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*2000: {{nihongo|''Citizens of Seoul 1919''|\u30bd\u30a6\u30eb\u5e02\u6c111919 |''Seoul Shimin 1919''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*1999: {{nihongo|''People of the Far Away Days''|\u9060\u3044\u65e5\u3005\u306e\u4eba|''Tooi Hibi no Hito''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*1999: {{nihongo|''The Night Longer than the Sea''|\u6d77\u3088\u308a\u3082\u9577\u3044\u591c |''Umi yorimo Nagai Yoru''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*1999: {{nihongo|''The Treasury of Loyal Retainers''|\u5fe0\u81e3\u8535 |''Ch\u016bshingura''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*1999: {{nihongo|''A Couple's Story''|\u592b\u5a66\u5584\u54c9|''Meoto Zenai''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*1998: {{nihongo|''Komachi's Tale - New Version''|\u65b0\u7248\u30fb\u5c0f\u753a\u98a8\u4f1d|''Shinpan Komachif\u016bden''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*1997: {{nihongo|''Revolutionists''|\u9769\u547d\u65e5\u8a18|''Kakumei Nikki''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*1997: {{nihongo|''Cause the Moon is So Bright Tonight''|\u6708\u304c\u3068\u3063\u3066\u3082\u84bc\u3044\u304b\u3089|''Tsuki ga Tottemo Aoikara''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*1997: {{nihongo|''The Little Match Girls''|\u30de\u30c3\u30c1\u58f2\u308a\u306e\u5c11\u5973\u305f\u3061|''Matchi Uri no Sh\u014djotachi''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*1997: {{nihongo|''The Balkan Zoo''|\u30d0\u30eb\u30ab\u30f3\u52d5\u7269\u5712|''Balkan D\u014dbutsuen''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*1996: {{nihongo|''The Dancer''|\u8e0a\u308a\u5b50|''Odoriko''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*1996: {{nihongo|''Kings of the Road''|\u5192\u967a\u738b|''B\u014dken \u014c''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*1996: {{nihongo|''A Hard Life to Accept''|\u3053\u306e\u751f\u306f\u53d7\u3051\u5165\u308c\u304c\u305f\u3057|''Kono Sei wa Ukeiregathashi''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*1995: {{nihongo|''A Burning House, or Shambles?''|\u706b\u5b85\u304b\u4fee\u7f85\u304b|''Kataku ka Shura ka''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*1994: {{nihongo|''Transfer Student''|\u8ee2\u6821\u751f|''Tenk\u014dsei''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*1994: {{nihongo|''Some Forgotten Dream''|\u601d\u3044\u51fa\u305b\u306a\u3044\u5922\u306e\u3044\u304f\u3064\u304b|''Omoidasenai Yume no Ikutsuka''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*1992: {{nihongo|''Northernmost Monkeys''|\u5317\u9650\u306e\u733f|''Hokugen no Saru''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*1992: {{nihongo|''Run in Your Sleep''|\u8d70\u308a\u306a\u304c\u3089\u7720\u308c|''Hashirinagara Nemure''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*1992: {{nihongo|''Isn't Life More than Goodbyes?''|\u3055\u3088\u306a\u3089\u3060\u3051\u304c\u4eba\u751f\u304b |''Sayonara dakega Jinsei ka''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*1992: {{nihongo|''My Days of Mah-jong''|\u9ebb\u96c0\u653e\u6d6a\u8a18|''M\u0101jyan H\u014dr\u014dki''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*1991: {{nihongo|''From S Plateau''|\uff33\u9ad8\u539f\u304b\u3089|''S K\u014dgen Kara''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*1991: {{nihongo|''Travel on Train''|\u963f\u623f\u5217\u8eca|''Ah\u014d Ressha''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*1991: {{nihongo|''Confession of a Feeble Mind''|\u6697\u611a\u5c0f\u50b3|''Angu Shoden''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*1990: {{nihongo|''Southward''|\u5357\u3078|''Minami e''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*1990: {{nihongo|''The Scientifically Minded''|\u30ab\u30ac\u30af\u3059\u308b\u30b3\u30b3\u30ed|''Kagakusuru Kokoro''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.seinendan.org/eng/oriza/ Seinendan]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hirata, Oriza}}\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Japanese directors]]\n[[Category:Japanese academics]]\n[[Category:Japanese dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:20th-century Japanese dramatists and playwrights]] \n[[Category:21st-century Japanese dramatists and playwrights]] \n[[Category:International Christian University alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name = Oriza Hirata<br />\u5e73\u7530\u30aa\u30ea\u30b6\n| image = Oriza Hirata speaking at Tokyo Kaikan, September 2013.JPG\n| imagesize = 240px\n| caption = in [[Tokyo]] <br />(September, 2013)\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1962|11|08}}\n| birth_place = [[Tokyo]], [[Japan]]\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| death_cause =\n| known_for = ''T\u014dky\u014d Notes'', ''Citizens of Seoul''\n| nationality = [[Japanese people|Japanese]]\n| occupation = Playwright, director, academic\n| years_active = 1989-present\n| religion  = \n| spouse = \n| website = {{URL|http://www.seinendan.org/eng/oriza/}}\n}}\n\n{{nihongo|'''Oriza Hirata'''|\u5e73\u7530\u30aa\u30ea\u30b6|Hirata Oriza|born on 8 November 1962, in [[Tokyo]]}} is a Japanese playwright, director, and academic. For the majority of his life, he has been best known for his work in theater and creating what he has coined, \u201ccontemporary colloquial theater,\u201d or as theater critics call it, \u201cquiet drama.\u201d<ref name=Rimer>Rimer, J. Thomas, Mitsuya M\u014dri, and M. Cody Poulton. The Columbia Anthology of Modern Japanese Drama. New York: Columbia UP, 2014. Print.</ref>\n\n==Career==\nOriza Hirata graduated from [[International Christian University]] as a part of their Humanities division.<ref name=Shinsai>{{cite journal|last1=Hirata|first1=Oriza|title=Sayonara II|journal=Shinsai Only 3/11/12|date=11 March 2012|page=40}}</ref> In 1983, he formed the Seinendan Theater Company, which he established in order to practice contemporary colloquial theater. In 1984, Seinendan settled into using the Komaba Agora Theater as their main base of operations. Hirata remains as the theater's primary artistic director and has continued to play a major role in the theater's management.<ref name=Komaba>{{cite web|title=Komaba Agora Theater|url=http://www.seinendan.org/eng/agora/|website=Seinendan|publisher=Agora Kikaku|accessdate=7 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nHirata's first play, {{nihongo|''Citizens of Seoul''|\u30bd\u30a6\u30eb\u5e02\u6c11|''Seoul shimin''}},<ref name=\"Play list\">{{cite web|last1=Hirata|first1=Oriza|title=Play List|url=http://www.seinendan.org/eng/play/|website=Seinendan|publisher=Agora Kikaku|accessdate=7 June 2015}}</ref> first premiered in 1989, and has remained one of his most famous plays. 6 Years later, in 1994, he debuted {{nihongo|''T\u014dky\u014d Notes''|\u6771\u4eac\u30ce\u30fc\u30c8|''T\u014dky\u014d n\u014dto''}},<ref name=\"Play list\" /> which is still considered his magnum opus.<ref name=Rimer /> As a playwright, Hirata has continued to write and direct plays both at Komaba Agora theater, as well as theaters in Europe, the Americas, and other parts of Asia. He is also known for doing international collaborations both in Japan and all around the world, where he has worked with a multitude of playwrights and artists to introduce his own work to new audiences, as well as introduce foreign work to Japan.<ref name=International>{{cite web|title=International|website=Seinendan|publisher=Agora Kikaku}}</ref>\n\nHirata worked at Obirin University for six years as a professor in their theater department before moving onto [[Osaka University]], where he works in their communication-design and robotics departments.<ref name=\"Hirata education\">{{cite web|title=Education|url=http://www.seinendan.org/eng/oriza/education.php|website=Seinendan|publisher=Agora Kikaku|accessdate=7 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Contemporary colloquial theater==\n\nContemporary colloquial theater is a theatrical style Oriza Hirata founded as an answer to the \u201cboisterous and festive nature of 1980s Japanese theater.\u201d<ref name=Rimer /> This style emphasizes colloquial Japanese language use that is designed to sound distinctly typical of the linguistic tendencies and patterns of everyday Japanese speaking. As a result, his plays oftentimes feature multiple characters talking at once, sentence fragments, inaudible speech, and an understated, \"normal\" speaking tone. This style informs his plays stylistically, both in language and plot, in the sense that Hirata emphasizes [[realism (theatre)|realism]] throughout.<ref name=Rimer/> However, Hirata has preferred his own stylistic title of \"contemporary colloquial theater\" because he thinks that relatable terms like [[Shingeki]] or [[realism (theatre)|realism]] \"sounded too much like the Western drama that [they] emulated.\"<ref name=\"Poulton mjt\">{{cite book|last1=Poulton|first1=M. Cody|title=Modern Japanese Theatre and Performance|date=2006|publisher=Lexington Books|location=Lanham, MD|isbn=978-0-7391-1152-9|pages=26\u201330}}</ref> \nHirata's style is partially due to his identification the impact of Western style was having on Japanese arts. As a reaction, he has sought to create an artistic style more representative of typical Japanese language and culture. As a playwright, he founded the Seinendan theater company in 1983 as a way to push his acting style into the greater Japanese and international theatre scenes.<ref name=Rimer/>\nHirata has worked closely with international actors when translating his work to preserve the Japanese identity of the speech, which has particularly resonated with French audiences.<ref name=Hirata>Hirata, Oriza. \"Artist Interview: Speaking with Oriza Hirata, a New Opinion Leader in the World of Contemporary Theater.\" Interview by Akihiko Senda. Performing Arts Network Japan. The Japan Foundation, 23 Mar. 2007. Web. 28 Apr. 2015.</ref> This style also tends to emphasize a small, intimate set of characters\u2014usually represented by the actors playing the role of a family\u2014to serve as a \u201cmicrocosm of Japanese society as a whole.\u201d <ref name=Rimer/> Japanese theater scholar, M. Cody Poulton, describes Hirata's style as an emphasis of the Greek idea of ''ethos'', \"the prevalent tone of sentiment of a people or community; the genius of an institution or system.\"<ref name=\"Poulton mjt\" />\n\n==Interdisciplinary work==\n\nAfter working at Obirin University as a theater professor, Oriza Hirata moved to work for [[Osaka University]], where he collaborated in the scientific fields of communication-design and robotics.<ref>\"Oriza Hirata.\" ORIZA HIRATA: SEINENDAN. Seinendan, n.d. Web. 28 Apr. 2015.</ref>\n\nHirata has participated in designing university classes that emphasize the communication environment for different fields in order for them to perform more successfully.\n{{Quote|text=There are design elements and organizational elements that can encourage better communication in the doctor\u2019s office, such as the positions of the doctor\u2019s and the patient\u2019s chairs, the color of the walls, the lighting, and these elements can create an environment that encourages the patient to ask the doctor questions and bring out answers that can reduce medical/diagnostic error.|sign=Hirata Oriza|source=<ref name=Hirata/>}}\n\nFor robotics, Hirata used his theater experience to attempt to make robots that act similarly to humans. While his work has been used to generally fulfill this role, he has also brought his work in robotics back to the theater, where he has incorporated robots in plays to explore themes of humanity. His play, ''I, Worker'' uses two robots as main characters to explore this very idea. He has collaborated with robotics expert [[Hiroshi Ishiguro]] for his theatrical experiments using robots.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Posner|first1=Dassia N.|last2=Orenstein|first2=Claudia|last3=Bell|first3=John|title=The Routledge Companion to Puppetry and Material Performance|date=2014|publisher=Routledge|location=New York|isbn=978-0-415-70540-0|page=282}}</ref>\n\n==International work and acclaim==\n\nShortly after beginning his career as a playwright, Oriza Hirata has had a prolific international career\u2014both touring his work around the world, as well as staging foreign playwrights work at his own theater in Japan.\n\nBeginning in the early 2000s, Hirata's work started to garner international attention. With the help of Japan's Saison Foundation, a grant-making foundation that supports Japanese Theater, and [[Manhattan]]'s [[Nonprofit organization]] [[Japan Society (Manhattan)|Japan Society]], Hirata's most famous work, ''T\u014dky\u014d Notes'' was debuted in the [[United States]] in October 2000 in [[New York City]]. [[Japan Society (Manhattan)|Japan Society]]'s theater series, Japanese Theatre NOW, has helped bring a number of contemporary Japanese dramas to the [[United States]], Hirata's being notable since ''T\u014dky\u014d Notes'' was one of the first.<ref name=Thornbury>{{cite book|last1=Thronbury|first1=Barbara|title=America's Japan and Japan's Performing Arts: Cultural Mobility and Exchange in New York, 1952-2011|date=2013|publisher=The University of Michigan Press|location=Ann Arbor, MI|isbn=978-0-472-11885-4|pages=17\u201319}}</ref>\n\nSince then, Hirata's work and company have traveled much of the world, including [[France]], [[Belgium]], [[Switzerland]], [[Ireland]], [[Germany]], the [[United Kingdom]], [[Korea]], [[China]], [[Australia]], and [[Brazil]]. Hirata says that he believes he has \"done the best work in France,\" where \"the people in France have been very enthusiastic about [his] work.\" Both in [[France]] and [[Belgium]], Hirata has collaborated with international actors and directors to bring his theatrical work to an international audience, as well as creating new commissioned work as both a playwright and director.<ref name=International /><ref name=Hirata />\n\nHirata has also collaborated on many international works inside of [[Japan]], using his theater to stage plays by playwrights from [[France]], [[Switzerland]], [[Italy]], [[Spain]], the [[United States]], [[Korea]], and [[China]]. Hirata's admiration for the French theater scene can be seen with these collaborations as well, as he has tended to stage more French plays than any other country he has collaborated with.<ref name=International />\n\nA year after the [[Fukushima Daiichi nuclear disaster]], Hirata submitted a 10-minute play, along with 18 other American and Japanese artist, to be performed and documented in an event called Shinsai: Theaters For Japan.<ref name=\"Shinsai web\">{{cite web|title=SHINSAI: Theaters for Japan|url=https://www.tcg.org/shinsai/archive.cfm|website=Theatre Communications Group|publisher=Theatre Communications Group|accessdate=3 June 2015}}</ref> The event happened that the Great Hall at Cooper Union in [[New York City]]. Hirata's play, entitled \"Sayonara II\", tells the story of a partially-broken robot who is asked to read poems to the people who died after the disaster.<ref name=Shinsai />\n\n==Accolades==\n\n*39th [[Kishida Prize for Drama]] for his play ''T\u014dky\u014d Notes '' (1995).<ref name=Shinsai />\n*5th Yomiuru Theater Outstanding Director Award for producing Masataka Matsuda's play ''The Cape of the Moon'' (1998).<ref name=Shinsai />\n*9th Yomiuri Theater Award for Outstanding Production on his play ''Attacking Ueno Zoo for the Fourth Time'' (2002).<ref name=Shinsai />\n*Association Internationale des Critiques des Th\u00e9\u00e2tre Critique Award for his book ''Arts as the Basis of a Nation'' (2002).<ref name=Shinsai />\n*Winner of the Grand Prix of the 2nd Asahi Performing Arts Awards for his play ''Across the River in May'' (2003).<ref name=Shinsai />\n*Montblanc de la Culture Arts Patronage Award (2006).<ref name=Shinsai />\n\n==List of Works==\n\n===Major Works===\n*1989: {{nihongo|''Citizens of Seoul''|\u30bd\u30a6\u30eb\u5e02\u6c11|''Seoul shimin''}}:<ref name=\"Play list\" /> One of Hirata's earliest and most critically acclaimed works, ''Citizens of Seoul'' tackles Japan's superiority complex over Korea during their colonization.\n*1994: {{nihongo|''T\u014dky\u014d Notes''|\u6771\u4eac\u30ce\u30fc\u30c8|''T\u014dky\u014d n\u014dto''}}:<ref name=\"Play list\" /> Hirata's most famous and praised work around the world, ''T\u014dky\u014d Notes'' takes place in a museum where a number of people's personal lives are examined in order to gain a fuller picture of the political, social, and cultural context of a near-future Japan.\n*2002: {{nihongo|''The Yalta Conference''|\u30e4\u30eb\u30bf\u4f1a\u8ac7|''Yaruta kaidan''}}:<ref name=\"Play list\" /> Summarizing the world's history post-WWII, this is one of Hiraza's most grand dramas in terms of scope. [[Winston Churchill]], [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]], and [[Joseph Stalin]] are the only 3 characters in the play.\n\n===Recent Works===\n*2009: {{nihongo|''Par-dessus bord -Tori no tobu takasa''|\u9ce5\u306e\u98db\u3076\u9ad8\u3055|''Tori no tubu takasa''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*2009: {{nihongo|''The Tongue-Cut Sparrow''|\u820c\u5207\u308a\u96c0|''Shitakiri Suzume''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*2009: {{nihongo|''Christmas in Tehran''|\u30af\u30ea\u30b9\u30de\u30b9 \u30a4\u30f3 \u30c6\u30d8\u30e9\u30f3|''Kurisumasu in Teheran''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*2008: {{nihongo|''I, Worker''|\u50cd\u304f\u79c1|''Hataraku Watashi''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*2008: {{nihongo|''A Long Night in the Tropics''|\u7720\u308c\u306a\u3044\u591c\u306a\u3093\u3066\u306a\u3044|''Nemurenai Yorunante nai''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*2008: {{nihongo|''A Cold Wind Blows through Cherry Blossoms''|\u98a8\u306e\u3064\u3081\u305f\u304d\u6afb\u304b\u306a|''Kaze no Tsumetaki Sakura kana''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*2008: {{nihongo|''In the Heart of a Forest''|\u68ee\u306e\u5965|''Mori no Oku''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*2007: {{nihongo|''Citizens of Seoul 1929: Graffiti''|\u30bd\u30a6\u30eb\u5e02\u6c11 \u662d\u548c\u671b\u90f7\u7de8|''Seoul Shimin Sh\u014dwa B\u014dky\u014d Hen''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*2007: {{nihongo|''Songs of Farewell''|\u5225\u308c\u306e\u5504|''Wakare no Uta''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n\n===Other Notable Works===\n*2005: {{nihongo|''Sand and Soldiers''|\u7802\u3068\u5175\u968a|''Sunato Heitai''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*2005: {{nihongo|''Conference before the Throne''|\u5fa1\u524d\u4f1a\u8b70 |''Gozen Kaigi''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*2003: {{nihongo|''No More Winds Blow''|\u3082\u3046\u98a8\u3082\u5439\u304b\u306a\u3044|''M\u014d Kazemo Fukanai''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*2003: {{nihongo|''The Journal of POWs''|\u5357\u5cf6\u4fd8\u865c\u8a18|''Nant\u014d Furyoki''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*2002: {{nihongo|''Across the River in May''|\u305d\u306e\u6cb3\u3092\u3053\u3048\u3066\u3001\u4e94\u6708|''Sono Kawa o Koete, Gogatsu''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*2001: {{nihongo|''Attacking the Ueno Zoo for the Fourth Time''|\u4e0a\u91ce\u52d5\u7269\u5712\u518d\u3005\u3005\u8972\u6483|''Ueno D\u014dbutsuen sai-sai-sai Sh\u016bgeki''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*2000: {{nihongo|''Suddenly Married''|\u96a3\u306b\u3044\u3066\u3082\u4e00\u4eba|''Tonari ni Itemo Hitori''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*2000: {{nihongo|''Citizens of Seoul 1919''|\u30bd\u30a6\u30eb\u5e02\u6c111919 |''Seoul Shimin 1919''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*1999: {{nihongo|''People of the Far Away Days''|\u9060\u3044\u65e5\u3005\u306e\u4eba|''Tooi Hibi no Hito''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*1999: {{nihongo|''The Night Longer than the Sea''|\u6d77\u3088\u308a\u3082\u9577\u3044\u591c |''Umi yorimo Nagai Yoru''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*1999: {{nihongo|''The Treasury of Loyal Retainers''|\u5fe0\u81e3\u8535 |''Ch\u016bshingura''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*1999: {{nihongo|''A Couple's Story''|\u592b\u5a66\u5584\u54c9|''Meoto Zenai''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*1998: {{nihongo|''Komachi's Tale - New Version''|\u65b0\u7248\u30fb\u5c0f\u753a\u98a8\u4f1d|''Shinpan Komachif\u016bden''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*1997: {{nihongo|''Revolutionists''|\u9769\u547d\u65e5\u8a18|''Kakumei Nikki''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*1997: {{nihongo|''Cause the Moon is So Bright Tonight''|\u6708\u304c\u3068\u3063\u3066\u3082\u84bc\u3044\u304b\u3089|''Tsuki ga Tottemo Aoikara''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*1997: {{nihongo|''The Little Match Girls''|\u30de\u30c3\u30c1\u58f2\u308a\u306e\u5c11\u5973\u305f\u3061|''Matchi Uri no Sh\u014djotachi''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*1997: {{nihongo|''The Balkan Zoo''|\u30d0\u30eb\u30ab\u30f3\u52d5\u7269\u5712|''Balkan D\u014dbutsuen''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*1996: {{nihongo|''The Dancer''|\u8e0a\u308a\u5b50|''Odoriko''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*1996: {{nihongo|''Kings of the Road''|\u5192\u967a\u738b|''B\u014dken \u014c''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*1996: {{nihongo|''A Hard Life to Accept''|\u3053\u306e\u751f\u306f\u53d7\u3051\u5165\u308c\u304c\u305f\u3057|''Kono Sei wa Ukeiregathashi''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*1995: {{nihongo|''A Burning House, or Shambles?''|\u706b\u5b85\u304b\u4fee\u7f85\u304b|''Kataku ka Shura ka''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*1994: {{nihongo|''Transfer Student''|\u8ee2\u6821\u751f|''Tenk\u014dsei''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*1994: {{nihongo|''Some Forgotten Dream''|\u601d\u3044\u51fa\u305b\u306a\u3044\u5922\u306e\u3044\u304f\u3064\u304b|''Omoidasenai Yume no Ikutsuka''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*1992: {{nihongo|''Northernmost Monkeys''|\u5317\u9650\u306e\u733f|''Hokugen no Saru''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*1992: {{nihongo|''Run in Your Sleep''|\u8d70\u308a\u306a\u304c\u3089\u7720\u308c|''Hashirinagara Nemure''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*1992: {{nihongo|''Isn't Life More than Goodbyes?''|\u3055\u3088\u306a\u3089\u3060\u3051\u304c\u4eba\u751f\u304b |''Sayonara dakega Jinsei ka''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*1992: {{nihongo|''My Days of Mah-jong''|\u9ebb\u96c0\u653e\u6d6a\u8a18|''M\u0101jyan H\u014dr\u014dki''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*1991: {{nihongo|''From S Plateau''|\uff33\u9ad8\u539f\u304b\u3089|''S K\u014dgen Kara''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*1991: {{nihongo|''Travel on Train''|\u963f\u623f\u5217\u8eca|''Ah\u014d Ressha''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*1991: {{nihongo|''Confession of a Feeble Mind''|\u6697\u611a\u5c0f\u50b3|''Angu Shoden''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*1990: {{nihongo|''Southward''|\u5357\u3078|''Minami e''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n*1990: {{nihongo|''The Scientifically Minded''|\u30ab\u30ac\u30af\u3059\u308b\u30b3\u30b3\u30ed|''Kagakusuru Kokoro''}}<ref name=\"Play list\" />\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.seinendan.org/eng/oriza/ Seinendan]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hirata, Oriza}}\n[[Category:1962 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Japanese directors]]\n[[Category:Japanese academics]]\n[[Category:Japanese dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:20th-century Japanese dramatists and playwrights]] \n[[Category:21st-century Japanese dramatists and playwrights]] \n[[Category:International Christian University alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Chris the speller", "label": "safe", "comment": "cap, punct", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oriza_Hirata"}
{"title_page": "Gareth Owen (sound designer)", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Gareth Owen\n| image         =Gareth Owen - Sound Designer - Biog Photo - Full Size.jpg\n| birth_name     = Gareth John Owen\n| birth_date     = {{Birth date and age|1979|8|20|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = Sheffield, England\n| nationality    = British\n| education    = University of Plymouth\n| occupation    = Theatrical Sound Designer\n| years_active   = 1998\u2013present\n| children      = 2\n| website         = {{official URL}}\n| imagesize     =\n}}\n\n'''Gareth Owen''' is an eight-time [[Tony_Award|Tony]] & [[Laurence_Olivier_Award|Olivier]] Award-winning/nominated [[sound design]]er specialising in [[musical theatre]] in London's [[West_End_theatre|West End]], on [[Broadway_Theatre|Broadway]] and internationally.\n\n==Early life==\n\nGareth John Owen was born in [[Sheffield]], [[United Kingdom]], a son of two teachers, both of whom specialised in special needs. At the age of nine the family, now including a younger sister, moved to the [[Cayman Islands]] where Owen attended Cayman Islands Middle School, while nurturing a life long love of the ocean. Upon returning to the UK the family, missing the warm weather and sea air, moved to [[St_Ives,_Cornwall|St. Ives]] in [[Cornwall]] at the south-western tip of the country. Here Owen attended both [[Mounts_Bay_Academy|Mounts Bay School]] and [[Truro_and_Penwith_College|Penwith Sixth Form College]] before heading to [[University_of_Plymouth|Plymouth University]] in [[Plymouth]], UK, to study for a Bachelor's Degree in Underwater [[Science]]. At various points, Owen has worked as a grocery packer, [[marina]] fuel attendant, [[milkman]], [[Q-Zar|Quasar]] attendant, commercial boatman, pool lifeguard, [[Muay_Thai|thai-boxing]] instructor, and [[Surf_lifesaving|beach lifeguard]]. He also worked extensively in nightclubs as a [[Lighting_designer|lighting jockey]], [[Bouncer_(doorman)|doorman]], [[Disc_jockey|DJ]], [[Promoter_(entertainment)|promoter]] and [[Production_manager_(music)|production manager]].\n\n==Career==\n\nOwen was nominated for his first [[Tony Award]] in 2010 for his [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] production of [[Trevor Nunn]]'s musical, ''[[A Little Night Music]]'' starring [[Catherine Zeta-Jones]] and [[Angela Lansbury]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibdb.com/awardperson.asp?id=485023 |title=IBDB Person Awards |work=Internet Broadway Database |access-date=4 October 2010 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121023134441/http://www.ibdb.com/awardperson.asp?id=485023 |archive-date=23 October 2012 |df= }}</ref>\n\nHe was then nominated for an [[Olivier Award]] for his [[West End theatre|West End]] production of [[Terry Johnson (dramatist)|Terry Johnson]]'s musical, [[End of the Rainbow]] starring multi-award-winning [[Tracie Bennett]] as [[Judy Garland]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.olivierawards.com/nominations/view/item114060/Best-Sound-Design/ |title=Olivier Award for Sound Design |work=The Olivier Awards |access-date=14 March 2011 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://archive.is/20110714235819/http://www.olivierawards.com/nominations/view/item114060/Best-Sound-Design/ |archive-date=14 July 2011 |df= }}</ref> The show later transferred to Broadway where he went on to pick up a further Tony nomination for Best Sound Design.\n\nIn recent years Owen collected a 2nd Oliver nomination for ''[[Top Hat (musical)|Top Hat]]'', and, after five nominations, finally won the Oliver for Best Sound Design in 2014 with the London production of ''[[Merrily We Roll Along (musical)|Merrily We Roll Along]]''.\n\nIn 2015 Owen won the Olivier for Sound Design for the second consecutive year, this time for [[Memphis (musical)|Memphis]] at the Shaftesbury Theatre, starring [[Beverley Knight]]. Composed by [[David Bryan]] from [[Bon Jovi]], and directed by [[Christopher Ashley]], this marked his sixth win/nomination in a row. He also received the prestigious Pro Sound Award for his work on the same production.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prosoundawards.com//|title=Pro Sound Award for Best Theatre Sound|work=The Pro Sound Awards|accessdate=23 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Owen won several awards for the Broadway musical [[Come from Away|''Come From Away'']] including the [[Outer Critics Circle Award]] and the [[Craig Noel|Craig Noel Award]], as well as a [[Helen Hayes Award]] nomination.\n\nGareth has worked on over two hundred and seventy-five commercial sound designs throughout the world including: ''[[42nd Street (musical)|42nd Street,]] [[Starlight Express]], [[Bat Out of Hell]], [[Wind in the Willows (musical)|Wind in the Willows,]]'' ''[[The Hunchback of Notre Dame (musical)|Disney's Hunchback of Notre Dame]]'', ''[[Spring Awakening (musical)|Spring Awakening]]'', ''[[Young Frankenstein (musical)|Young Frankenstein]]'',''[[The Bodyguard (musical)|The Bodyguard]]'', ''[[Let It Be (musical)|Let it Be]]'', ''[[The Little Mermaid (musical)|Disney's Little Mermaid]]'', ''[[Sister Act (musical)|Sister Act]]'', ''[[Hairspray (musical)|Hairspray]]'', ''[[Beauty and the Beast (musical)|Disney's Beauty & The Beast]]'', ''[[Singin' in the Rain (musical)|Singin' in the Rain]]'', ''[[Aspects of Love]]'', ''[[Footloose (musical)#Original London production|Footloose]]'', ''[[Flashdance]]'', ''[[Carousel (musical)|Carousel]]'', ''[[Fiddler on the Roof]]'', ''[[Fame the Musical|Fame]]'', ''[[Saturday Night Fever (musical)|Saturday Night Fever]]'' and ''[[La Cage aux Folles (musical)|La Cage Aux Folles]]''.\n\n==Other endeavours==\n\nIn 2009, Owen joined a steering [[committee]] that would eventually go on to form the Association of Sound Designers<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.associationofsounddesigners.com/|title=Who We Are|work=The Association of Sound Designers|accessdate=11 January 2019}}</ref> - an organisation that eventually went on to represent the majority of sound engineers working in British theatre. He served as a full committee member for the maximum possible term of five years, from 2012 to 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.associationofsounddesigners.com/asdhistory/|title=The History of the ASD|work=The Association of Sound Designers|accessdate=11 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Selected Awards==\n{{Awards table|2}}\n|-\n|2020\n|''[[Come From Away]]''\n|[[Green_Room_Awards|Green Room Award]] for Best Sound Design\n|{{Won}}\n|\n|-\n|2020\n|''[[Come From Away]]''\n|[[WhatsOnStage_Awards|WhatsOnStage Award]] for Best Sound Design\n|{{Won}}\n|\n|-\n|2020\n|''[[& Juliet]]''\n|[[WhatsOnStage_Awards|WhatsOnStage Award]] for Best Sound Design\n|{{Nominated}}\n|\n|-\n|2019\n|''[[Come From Away]]''\n|[[Laurence Olivier Award|Olivier Award]] for [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Sound Design|Best Sound Design]]\n|{{Won}}\n|\n|-\n|2019\n|''[[Summer:_The_Donna_Summer_Musical|The Donna Summer Musical]]''\n| [[NAACP_Theatre_Awards|NAACP Theatre Award]] for Best Sound Larger Theatre\n|{{Nominated}}\n|\n|-\n|2018\n|''[[Starlight_Express|Starlight Express]] (Bochum)'' \n| Pro Sound Award for Best Immersive Design \n|{{Won}}\n|\n|-\n|2018\n|''Carmen La Cubana''\n|[[BroadwayWorld]] Germany Award for Best Sound Design\n|{{Won}}\n|\n|-\n|2018\n|''[[Come From Away]]''\n|[[BroadwayWorld]] Toronto Award for Best Original Sound Design\n|{{Won}}\n|\n|-\n|2018\n|''[[Bat Out of Hell The Musical]]''\n|[[Laurence Olivier Award|Olivier Award]] for [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Sound Design|Best Sound Design]]\n|{{Nominated}}\n|\n|-\n|2018\n|''[[Come From Away]]''\n|[[BroadwayWorld]] Award for Best Sound Design\n|{{Won}}\n|\n|-\n|2018\n|''[[Summer: The Donna Summer Musical|Summer]]''\n|[[Craig_Noel|Craig Noel]] Award for Best Sound Design\n|{{Nominated}}\n|\n|-\n|2017\n|''[[Bat Out of Hell The Musical]]''\n|AV Technology Award for Best Sound Design\n|{{Won}}\n|\n|-\n|2017\n|''[[Come From Away]]''\n|[[Outer Critics Circle Award]] for Best Sound Design\n|{{Won}}\n|\n|-\n|2017\n|''[[Bat Out of Hell The Musical]]''\n|[[BroadwayWorld]] Award for Best Sound Design\n|{{Won}}\n|\n|-\n|2017\n|''[[Come From Away]]''\n|[[Dora_Mavor_Moore_Award|Dora Award]] for Best Sound Design\n|{{Won}}\n|\n|-\n|2017\n|''Individual Recognition''\n|Pro Sound Award for Sound Engineer of the Year<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.futureevents.uk/prosound_awards/winners2017/|title=Pro Sound Award Winners 2017|work=The Pro Sound Awards|accessdate=22 October 2017}}</ref>\n|{{Won}}\n|\n|-\n|2017\n|''[[Come From Away]]''\n|[[Helen_Hayes_Award|Helen Hayes Award]] for Best Sound Design\n|{{Won}}\n|\n|-\n|2016\n|''[[A Bronx Tale (musical)|A Bronx Tale]]''\n|[[BroadwayWorld]] Award for Best Sound Design\n|{{Won}}\n|\n|-\n|2015\n|''[[Memphis (musical)|Memphis the Musical]]''\n|[[Laurence Olivier Award|Olivier Award]] for [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Sound Design|Best Sound Design]]\n|{{Won}}\n|\n|-\n|2015\n| ''[[Memphis (musical)|Memphis the Musical]]''\n| Pro Sound Award for Best Theatre Sound<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prosoundawards.com//|title=Pro Sound Award for Best Theatre Sound|work=The Pro Sound Awards|accessdate=23 October 2015}}</ref>\n| {{Won}}\n|\n|-\n|2015\n|''[[The Hunchback of Notre Dame (musical)|Hunchback of Notre Dame]]''\n| [[BroadwayWorld]] Award for Best Sound Design\n|{{Nominated}}\n|\n|-\n|2014\n|''[[Merrily We Roll Along (musical)|Merrily We Roll Along]]''\n|[[Laurence Olivier Award|Olivier Award]] for [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Sound Design|Best Sound Design]]\n| {{Won}}\n|\n|-\n|2013\n| ''[[Top Hat (musical)|Top Hat]]''\n|[[Laurence Olivier Award|Olivier Award]] for [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Sound Design|Best Sound Design]]\n| {{Nominated}}\n|\n|-\n|2014\n| ''[[I Can't Sing!]]''\n| Pro Sound Award for Best Theatre Sound\n| {{Won}}\n|\n|-\n|2012\n| ''[[End of the Rainbow]]''\n| [[Tony Award]] for Best Sound Design of a Musical\n| {{Nominated}}\n|\n|-\n|2011\n| ''[[End of the Rainbow]]''\n|[[Laurence Olivier Award|Olivier Award]] for [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Sound Design|Best Sound Design]]\n| {{Nominated}}\n|\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[A Little Night Music]]''\n| [[Tony Award]] for Best Sound Design of a Musical\n| {{Nominated}}\n| \n{{end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.garethowensound.com Official site]\n* {{IBDB name}}\n*[http://www.theasd.uk Association of Sound Designers]\n*[https://www.facebook.com/Garethowensound/ Professional Facebook page]\n*[https://www.facebook.com/Garethjowen/ Personal Facebook page]\n*[https://www.twitter.com/Garethowensound/ Twitter account]\n*[https://www.instagram.com/Garethowensound/ Instagram]\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Owen, Gareth}}\n[[Category:Sound designers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Gareth Owen\n| image         =Gareth Owen - Sound Designer - Biog Photo - Full Size.jpg\n| birth_name     = Gareth John Owen\n| birth_date     = {{Birth date and age|1979|8|20|df=y}}\n| birth_place    = Sheffield, England\n| nationality    = British\n| education    = University of Plymouth\n| occupation    = Theatrical Sound Designer\n| years_active   = 1998\u2013present\n| children      = 2\n| website         = {{official URL}}\n| imagesize     =\n}}\n\n'''Gareth Owen''' is an eight-time [[Tony_Award|Tony]] & [[Laurence_Olivier_Award|Olivier]] Award-winning/nominated [[sound design]]er specialising in [[musical theatre]] in London's [[West_End_theatre|West End]], on [[Broadway_Theatre|Broadway]] and internationally.\n\n==Early life==\n\nGareth John Owen was born in [[Sheffield]], [[United Kingdom]], a son of two teachers, both of whom specialised in special needs. At the age of nine the family, now including a younger sister, moved to the [[Cayman Islands]] where Owen attended Cayman Islands Middle School, while nurturing a life long love of the ocean. Upon returning to the UK the family, missing the warm weather and sea air, moved to [[St_Ives,_Cornwall|St. Ives]] in [[Cornwall]] at the south-western tip of the country. Here Owen attended both [[Mounts_Bay_Academy|Mounts Bay School]] and [[Truro_and_Penwith_College|Penwith Sixth Form College]] before heading to [[University_of_Plymouth|Plymouth University]] in [[Plymouth]], UK, to study for a Bachelor's Degree in Underwater [[Science]]. At various points, Owen has worked as a grocery packer, [[marina]] fuel attendant, [[milkman]], [[Q-Zar|Quasar]] attendant, commercial boatman, pool lifeguard, [[Muay_Thai|thai-boxing]] instructor, and [[Surf_lifesaving|beach lifeguard]]. He also worked extensively in nightclubs as a [[Lighting_designer|lighting jockey]], [[Bouncer_(doorman)|doorman]], [[Disc_jockey|DJ]], [[Promoter_(entertainment)|promoter]] and [[Production_manager_(music)|production manager]].\n\n==Career==\n\nOwen was nominated for his first [[Tony Award]] in 2010 for his [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] production of [[Trevor Nunn]]'s musical, ''[[A Little Night Music]]'' starring [[Catherine Zeta-Jones]] and [[Angela Lansbury]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibdb.com/awardperson.asp?id=485023 |title=IBDB Person Awards |work=Internet Broadway Database |access-date=4 October 2010 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121023134441/http://www.ibdb.com/awardperson.asp?id=485023 |archive-date=23 October 2012 |df= }}</ref>\n\nHe was then nominated for an [[Olivier Award]] for his [[West End theatre|West End]] production of [[Terry Johnson (dramatist)|Terry Johnson]]'s musical, [[End of the Rainbow]] starring multi-award-winning [[Tracie Bennett]] as [[Judy Garland]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.olivierawards.com/nominations/view/item114060/Best-Sound-Design/ |title=Olivier Award for Sound Design |work=The Olivier Awards |access-date=14 March 2011 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://archive.is/20110714235819/http://www.olivierawards.com/nominations/view/item114060/Best-Sound-Design/ |archive-date=14 July 2011 |df= }}</ref> The show later transferred to Broadway where he went on to pick up a further Tony nomination for Best Sound Design.\n\nIn recent years Owen collected a 2nd Oliver nomination for ''[[Top Hat (musical)|Top Hat]]'', and, after five nominations, finally won the Oliver for Best Sound Design in 2014 with the London production of ''[[Merrily We Roll Along (musical)|Merrily We Roll Along]]''.\n\nIn 2015 Owen won the Olivier for Sound Design for the second consecutive year, this time for [[Memphis (musical)|Memphis]] at the Shaftesbury Theatre, starring [[Beverley Knight]]. Composed by [[David Bryan]] from [[Bon Jovi]], and directed by [[Christopher Ashley]], this marked his sixth win/nomination in a row. He also received the prestigious Pro Sound Award for his work on the same production.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.prosoundawards.com//|title=Pro Sound Award for Best Theatre Sound|work=The Pro Sound Awards|accessdate=23 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Owen won several awards for the Broadway musical [[Come from Away|''Come From Away'']] including the [[Outer Critics Circle Award]] and the [[Craig Noel|Craig Noel Award]], as well as a [[Helen Hayes Award]] nomination.\n\nGareth has worked on over two hundred and seventy-five commercial sound designs throughout the world including: ''[[42nd Street (musical)|42nd Street,]] [[Starlight Express]], [[Bat Out of Hell]], [[Wind in the Willows (musical)|Wind in the Willows,]]'' ''[[The Hunchback of Notre Dame (musical)|Disney's Hunchback of Notre Dame]]'', ''[[Spring Awakening (musical)|Spring Awakening]]'', ''[[Young Frankenstein (musical)|Young Frankenstein]]'',''[[The Bodyguard (musical)|The Bodyguard]]'', ''[[Let It Be (musical)|Let it Be]]'', ''[[The Little Mermaid (musical)|Disney's Little Mermaid]]'', ''[[Sister Act (musical)|Sister Act]]'', ''[[Hairspray (musical)|Hairspray]]'', ''[[Beauty and the Beast (musical)|Disney's Beauty & The Beast]]'', ''[[Singin' in the Rain (musical)|Singin' in the Rain]]'', ''[[Aspects of Love]]'', ''[[Footloose (musical)#Original London production|Footloose]]'', ''[[Flashdance]]'', ''[[Carousel (musical)|Carousel]]'', ''[[Fiddler on the Roof]]'', ''[[Fame the Musical|Fame]]'', ''[[Saturday Night Fever (musical)|Saturday Night Fever]]'' and ''[[La Cage aux Folles (musical)|La Cage Aux Folles]]''.\n\n==Other endeavours==\n\nIn 2009, Owen joined a steering committee that would eventually go on to form the Association of Sound Designers<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.associationofsounddesigners.com/|title=Who We Are|work=The Association of Sound Designers|accessdate=11 January 2019}}</ref> - an organisation that eventually went on to represent the majority of sound engineers working in British theatre. He served as a full committee member for the maximum possible term of five years, from 2012 to 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.associationofsounddesigners.com/asdhistory/|title=The History of the ASD|work=The Association of Sound Designers|accessdate=11 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Selected Awards==\n{{Awards table|2}}\n|-\n|2020\n|''[[Come From Away]]''\n|[[Green_Room_Awards|Green Room Award]] for Best Sound Design\n|{{Won}}\n|\n|-\n|2020\n|''[[Come From Away]]''\n|[[WhatsOnStage_Awards|WhatsOnStage Award]] for Best Sound Design\n|{{Won}}\n|\n|-\n|2020\n|''[[& Juliet]]''\n|[[WhatsOnStage_Awards|WhatsOnStage Award]] for Best Sound Design\n|{{Nominated}}\n|\n|-\n|2019\n|''[[Come From Away]]''\n|[[Laurence Olivier Award|Olivier Award]] for [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Sound Design|Best Sound Design]]\n|{{Won}}\n|\n|-\n|2019\n|''[[Summer:_The_Donna_Summer_Musical|The Donna Summer Musical]]''\n| [[NAACP_Theatre_Awards|NAACP Theatre Award]] for Best Sound Larger Theatre\n|{{Nominated}}\n|\n|-\n|2018\n|''[[Starlight_Express|Starlight Express]] (Bochum)'' \n| Pro Sound Award for Best Immersive Design \n|{{Won}}\n|\n|-\n|2018\n|''Carmen La Cubana''\n|[[BroadwayWorld]] Germany Award for Best Sound Design\n|{{Won}}\n|\n|-\n|2018\n|''[[Come From Away]]''\n|[[BroadwayWorld]] Toronto Award for Best Original Sound Design\n|{{Won}}\n|\n|-\