ical)|Merrily We Roll Along]]''\n|[[Laurence Olivier Award|Olivier Award]] for [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Sound Design|Best Sound Design]]\n| {{Won}}\n|\n|-\n|2013\n| ''[[Top Hat (musical)|Top Hat]]''\n|[[Laurence Olivier Award|Olivier Award]] for [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Sound Design|Best Sound Design]]\n| {{Nominated}}\n|\n|-\n|2014\n| ''[[I Can't Sing!]]''\n| Pro Sound Award for Best Theatre Sound\n| {{Won}}\n|\n|-\n|2012\n| ''[[End of the Rainbow]]''\n| [[Tony Award]] for Best Sound Design of a Musical\n| {{Nominated}}\n|\n|-\n|2011\n| ''[[End of the Rainbow]]''\n|[[Laurence Olivier Award|Olivier Award]] for [[Laurence Olivier Award for Best Sound Design|Best Sound Design]]\n| {{Nominated}}\n|\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[A Little Night Music]]''\n| [[Tony Award]] for Best Sound Design of a Musical\n| {{Nominated}}\n| \n{{end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[http://www.garethowensound.com Official site]\n* {{IBDB name}}\n*[http://www.theasd.uk Association of Sound Designers]\n*[https://www.facebook.com/Garethowensound/ Professional Facebook page]\n*[https://www.facebook.com/Garethjowen/ Personal Facebook page]\n*[https://www.twitter.com/Garethowensound/ Twitter account]\n*[https://www.instagram.com/Garethowensound/ Instagram]\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Owen, Gareth}}\n[[Category:Sound designers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n", "name_user": "Foolscap2000a", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eOther endeavours", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gareth_Owen_(sound_designer)"}
{"title_page": "Mike Yenni", "text_new": "[[File:Michael S. Yenni.jpg|alt=|right|frameless|271x271px]]\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                = Michael S. Yenni\n| nationality         = American\n| office1             = President of [[Jefferson Parish, Louisiana|Jefferson Parish]]\n| term_start1         = January 6, 2016\n| term_end1           = January 7, 2020\n| predecessor1        = John F. Young\n| successor1          = Cynthia Lee Sheng\n| office2             = 21st Mayor of [[Kenner, Louisiana|Kenner]]\n| term_start2         = July 1, 2010\n| term_end2           = January 6, 2016\n| predecessor2        = Edmond J. \"Ed\" Muniz\n| successor2          = Michael G. \"Mike\" Sigur\n| birth_place         = Metairie, LA\n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| alma_mater          = [[Southeastern Louisiana University]]\n| party               = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n| branch              = United States Navy Reserve\n| rank                = [[File:Lieutenant-united-states-symbol.png|35px|frameless|left]]\nLieutenant: 2014-present <br> [[File:Lieutenant-jr-united-states-symbol.png|35px|frameless|left]] Lieutenant (Junior Grade): 2012-2014 <br> \n[[File:Ensign-united-states-symbol.png|35px|frameless|left]] Ensign: 2010-2012\n| allegiance          = United States of America\n| years of military service = 2010 to the present\n| awards              = Navy and Marine Corp Commendation Medal, Meritorious Unit Commendation, Global War of Terrorism, Pistol Marksmanship Medal, National Defense Service Medal\n| spouse              = Michelle Swanner Yenni\n| children            = 3\n}}\n'''Michael S. Yenni''' is an American politician and the former President of [[Jefferson Parish, Louisiana|Jefferson Parish]], [[Louisiana]] from 2016 to 2020. He was Mayor of [[Kenner, Louisiana|Kenner]], Louisiana from 2010 to 2016. In 2016, the embattled politician admitted to sending sexually suggestive texts to a teenage boy<ref>https://wgno.com/news/local/mike-yenni-to-address-sexting-allegations-in-10-p-m-news-commercial/</ref>. After surviving a recall petition, Yenni declined to run for a second term.\n\n==Early life==\nMichael S. Yenni was born Michael Maunoir.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nola.com/elections/index.ssf/2015/10/jefferson_parish_president_win.html|title=Mike Yenni wins Jefferson Parish presidency over Elton Lagasse|work=NOLA.com|access-date=2017-11-01}}</ref> He received a bachelor's degree from Southeastern Louisiana University. Yenni served as the Director of the Department of Citizens' Affairs in Jefferson Parish from January 2005 to June 2006. On July 1, 2006 he became the 7th Chief Administrative Officer for the City of Kenner for then Mayor Ed Muniz's entire term in office. Yenni's grandfather Joe Yenni was the Mayor of Kenner from 1970\u20131980 and President of Jefferson Parish from 1980 until his death in March 1987. His uncle Mike Yenni was elected in September 1987 succeeding his late father as President of Jefferson Parish until his death in October 1995.\n\n==Political career==\nYenni was elected the 21st Mayor of Kenner in 2010. He was sworn into office on July 1, 2010. Mayor Yenni was  reelected in 2014, with 75% of the vote against 2 other challengers to a second term. In 2015, he was a Republican candidate for President of Jefferson Parish in the October 2015 election, in which he defeated Parish Councilman at Large Elton Lagasse and 3 other candidates in the primary election. Michael Yenni was sworn as the 15th President on January 6, 2016. His administration made advancements towards the parish's success in areas of economic growth and infrastructure enhancements.\n\nHis political career was marred in scandal in October, 2016, when Yenni admitted to sending improper texts to a young adult in video released to the public <ref>https://www.nola.com/news/politics/article_dc0212b4-b012-53fc-9678-9aa7aa556405.html</ref>. The video went viral and led to a failed voter led recall petition and most elected Parish officials to call for Yenni's immediate resignation. The video was released as a response to a claim made in an youth news site The Tab<ref>https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Tab</ref> in which a male Brown University student and New Orleans native accused Yenni of sexting him after the accuser graduated from high school. ref>https://www.nola.com/news/politics/article_287d7742-5c6d-58d3-8884-f77d6ed4d891.html</ref>.\n\nThe scandal also led Yenni to be banned from all Jefferson Parish School Board properties and events<ref>https://www.nola.com/news/education/article_9009af31-5b79-5c7a-ab08-a7043bab0cc2.html</ref>\n\nOn August 8, 2019, Yenni announced that he would not seek reelection for a second term as Jefferson Parish President. He stated his decision was based on protecting his family and friends from \"that kind of campaign\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nola.com/news/politics/article_c7861d42-b9ee-11e9-8a51-4fe6c2ec00f9.html|title=Embattled Mike Yenni won't seek re-election, can't put family through 'that kind' of campaign.|last=Staff|first=Faimon Roberts, nola.com|access-date=2019-08-08}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nYenni is a graduate of Jesuit High School and received his bachelor\u2019s degree in Political Science from Southeastern Louisiana University. He has a long family history in government dating back to his grandfather, Joseph Yenni, who served as Mayor of Kenner and President of Jefferson Parish, and his uncle Michael Yenni who also served as Parish President. Yenni is a member of the United States Naval Reserve where he holds the rank of Lieutenant in the Public Affairs Community. He resides in Kenner and is married to Michelle Yenni. Together they have three daughters, Reagan, Madison and McKinley.\n\n==Electoral history==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:0.5em ; font-size:95%\"\n|+<big>Parish President election, 2015: Results<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.fox8live.com/story/30343028/mike-yenni-elected-jefferson-parish-president|title=Mike Yenni elected Jefferson Parish president|last=Staff|first=FOX8Live.com|access-date=2017-11-01}}</ref></big>\n!'''Year'''\n!'''Republican'''\n!'''Votes'''\n!'''%'''\n!'''Republican'''\n!'''Votes'''\n!'''%'''\n!'''Republican'''\n!'''Votes'''\n!'''%'''\n!'''Republican'''\n!'''Votes'''\n!'''%'''\n!'''Other'''\n!'''Votes'''\n!'''%'''\n|-\n|Parish President election, 2015 \n| {{Party shading/Republican}} |'''Mike Yenni'''\n| {{Party shading/Republican}} align=\"right\" |'''45,823'''\n| {{Party shading/Republican}} |'''52%'''\n| {{Party shading/Republican}} |Elton Lagasse \n| {{Party shading/Republican}} align=\"right\" |32,593\n| {{Party shading/Republican}} |37%\n|Robin Daldegan Christiana\n|2,979\n|3%\n|Vincent Joseph De Salvo, Jr.\n|2,491\n|3%\n|\"Al\" Morella\n|3,838\n|4%\n|-\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+<big>Mayor City of Kenner, 2014: Results</big>\n!Year\n!Republican\n!Votes\n!%\n!Republican\n!Votes\n!%\n!Other\n!Votes\n!%\n|-\n|Mayor City of Kenner election, 2014\n|'''Mike Yenni'''\n|'''6,285'''\n|'''75%'''\n|Walter A. \"Walt\" Bennetti\n|1,442\n|17%\n|\"Al\" Morella\n|617\n|7%\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+<big>Mayor City of Kenner, 2010: Results</big>\n!Year\n!Republican\n!Votes\n!Pct\n!Republican\n!Votes\n!Pct\n|-\n|Mayor City of Kenner election, 2010\n|'''Mike Yenni'''\n|'''6,745'''\n|'''57%'''\n|\"Phil\" Capitano\n|5,181\n|43%\n|}\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n;Official campaign website\n* [http://www.electmikeyenni.com/biography/ Elect Mike Yenni]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yenni, Michael S.}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Louisiana Republicans]]\n[[Category:Mayors of places in Louisiana]]\n[[Category:Presidents of Jefferson Parish, Louisiana]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Michael S. Yenni.jpg|alt=|right|frameless|271x271px]]\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                = Michael S. Yenni\n| nationality         = American\n| office1             = President of [[Jefferson Parish, Louisiana|Jefferson Parish]]\n| term_start1         = January 6, 2016\n| term_end1           = January 7, 2020\n| predecessor1        = John F. Young\n| successor1          = Cynthia Lee Sheng\n| office2             = 21st Mayor of [[Kenner, Louisiana|Kenner]]\n| term_start2         = July 1, 2010\n| term_end2           = January 6, 2016\n| predecessor2        = Edmond J. \"Ed\" Muniz\n| successor2          = Michael G. \"Mike\" Sigur\n| birth_place         = Metairie, LA\n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| alma_mater          = [[Southeastern Louisiana University]]\n| party               = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n| branch              = United States Navy Reserve\n| rank                = [[File:Lieutenant-united-states-symbol.png|35px|frameless|left]]\nLieutenant: 2014-present <br> [[File:Lieutenant-jr-united-states-symbol.png|35px|frameless|left]] Lieutenant (Junior Grade): 2012-2014 <br> \n[[File:Ensign-united-states-symbol.png|35px|frameless|left]] Ensign: 2010-2012\n| allegiance          = United States of America\n| years of military service = 2010 to the present\n| awards              = Navy and Marine Corp Commendation Medal, Meritorious Unit Commendation, Global War of Terrorism, Pistol Marksmanship Medal, National Defense Service Medal\n| spouse              = Michelle Swanner Yenni\n| children            = 3\n}}\n'''Michael S. Yenni''' is an American politician and the former President of [[Jefferson Parish, Louisiana|Jefferson Parish]] from 2016 to 2020, [[Louisiana]]. He was Mayor of [[Kenner, Louisiana|Kenner]], Louisiana from 2010 to 2016. In 2016, the embattled politician admitted to sending sexually suggestive texts to a teenage boy<ref>https://wgno.com/news/local/mike-yenni-to-address-sexting-allegations-in-10-p-m-news-commercial/</ref>. After surviving a recall petition, Yenni declined to run for a second term.\n\n==Early life==\nMichael S. Yenni was born Michael Maunoir.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nola.com/elections/index.ssf/2015/10/jefferson_parish_president_win.html|title=Mike Yenni wins Jefferson Parish presidency over Elton Lagasse|work=NOLA.com|access-date=2017-11-01}}</ref> He received a bachelor's degree from Southeastern Louisiana University. Yenni served as the Director of the Department of Citizens' Affairs in Jefferson Parish from January 2005 to June 2006. On July 1, 2006 he became the 7th Chief Administrative Officer for the City of Kenner for then Mayor Ed Muniz's entire term in office. Yenni's grandfather Joe Yenni was the Mayor of Kenner from 1970\u20131980 and President of Jefferson Parish from 1980 until his death in March 1987. His uncle Mike Yenni was elected in September 1987 succeeding his late father as President of Jefferson Parish until his death in October 1995.\n\n==Political career==\nYenni was elected the 21st Mayor of Kenner in 2010. He was sworn into office on July 1, 2010. Mayor Yenni was  reelected in 2014, with 75% of the vote against 2 other challengers to a second term. In 2015, he was a Republican candidate for President of Jefferson Parish in the October 2015 election, in which he defeated Parish Councilman at Large Elton Lagasse and 3 other candidates in the primary election. Michael Yenni was sworn as the 15th President on January 6, 2016. His administration made advancements towards the parish's success in areas of economic growth and infrastructure enhancements.\n\nHis political career was marred in scandal in October, 2016, when Yenni admitted to sending improper texts to a young adult in video released to the public <ref>https://www.nola.com/news/politics/article_dc0212b4-b012-53fc-9678-9aa7aa556405.html</ref>. The video went viral and led to a failed voter led recall petition and most elected Parish officials to call for Yenni's immediate resignation. The video was released as a response to a claim made in an youth news site The Tab<ref>https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Tab</ref> in which a male Brown University student and New Orleans native accused Yenni of sexting him after the accuser graduated from high school. ref>https://www.nola.com/news/politics/article_287d7742-5c6d-58d3-8884-f77d6ed4d891.html</ref>.\n\nThe scandal also led Yenni to be banned from all Jefferson Parish School Board properties and events<ref>https://www.nola.com/news/education/article_9009af31-5b79-5c7a-ab08-a7043bab0cc2.html</ref>\n\nOn August 8, 2019, Yenni announced that he would not seek reelection for a second term as Jefferson Parish President. He stated his decision was based on protecting his family and friends from \"that kind of campaign\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nola.com/news/politics/article_c7861d42-b9ee-11e9-8a51-4fe6c2ec00f9.html|title=Embattled Mike Yenni won't seek re-election, can't put family through 'that kind' of campaign.|last=Staff|first=Faimon Roberts, nola.com|access-date=2019-08-08}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nYenni is a graduate of Jesuit High School and received his bachelor\u2019s degree in Political Science from Southeastern Louisiana University. He has a long family history in government dating back to his grandfather, Joseph Yenni, who served as Mayor of Kenner and President of Jefferson Parish, and his uncle Michael Yenni who also served as Parish President. Yenni is a member of the United States Naval Reserve where he holds the rank of Lieutenant in the Public Affairs Community. He resides in Kenner and is married to Michelle Yenni. Together they have three daughters, Reagan, Madison and McKinley.\n\n==Electoral history==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:0.5em ; font-size:95%\"\n|+<big>Parish President election, 2015: Results<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.fox8live.com/story/30343028/mike-yenni-elected-jefferson-parish-president|title=Mike Yenni elected Jefferson Parish president|last=Staff|first=FOX8Live.com|access-date=2017-11-01}}</ref></big>\n!'''Year'''\n!'''Republican'''\n!'''Votes'''\n!'''%'''\n!'''Republican'''\n!'''Votes'''\n!'''%'''\n!'''Republican'''\n!'''Votes'''\n!'''%'''\n!'''Republican'''\n!'''Votes'''\n!'''%'''\n!'''Other'''\n!'''Votes'''\n!'''%'''\n|-\n|Parish President election, 2015 \n| {{Party shading/Republican}} |'''Mike Yenni'''\n| {{Party shading/Republican}} align=\"right\" |'''45,823'''\n| {{Party shading/Republican}} |'''52%'''\n| {{Party shading/Republican}} |Elton Lagasse \n| {{Party shading/Republican}} align=\"right\" |32,593\n| {{Party shading/Republican}} |37%\n|Robin Daldegan Christiana\n|2,979\n|3%\n|Vincent Joseph De Salvo, Jr.\n|2,491\n|3%\n|\"Al\" Morella\n|3,838\n|4%\n|-\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+<big>Mayor City of Kenner, 2014: Results</big>\n!Year\n!Republican\n!Votes\n!%\n!Republican\n!Votes\n!%\n!Other\n!Votes\n!%\n|-\n|Mayor City of Kenner election, 2014\n|'''Mike Yenni'''\n|'''6,285'''\n|'''75%'''\n|Walter A. \"Walt\" Bennetti\n|1,442\n|17%\n|\"Al\" Morella\n|617\n|7%\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+<big>Mayor City of Kenner, 2010: Results</big>\n!Year\n!Republican\n!Votes\n!Pct\n!Republican\n!Votes\n!Pct\n|-\n|Mayor City of Kenner election, 2010\n|'''Mike Yenni'''\n|'''6,745'''\n|'''57%'''\n|\"Phil\" Capitano\n|5,181\n|43%\n|}\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n;Official campaign website\n* [http://www.electmikeyenni.com/biography/ Elect Mike Yenni]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yenni, Michael S.}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Louisiana Republicans]]\n[[Category:Mayors of places in Louisiana]]\n[[Category:Presidents of Jefferson Parish, Louisiana]]\n", "name_user": "JohnDough100", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mike_Yenni"}
{"title_page": "Motets by Johann Sebastian Bach, discography", "text_new": "This article includes a list of commercial recordings of the [[Motet (Bach)|motets]] of [[Johann Sebastian Bach]]. Bach motets have often been recorded as a set (typically comprising the six motets catalogued as BWV{{nbsp}}225-230).{{efn|\"BWV\" is [[Bach-Werke-Verzeichnis]], a thematic catalogue of Bach's works.}}  However, other motets are attributed to Bach and there is some doubt about the authorship of [[Lobet den Herrn, alle Heiden, BWV 230|''Lobet den Herrn, alle Heiden'', BWV 230]], one of the {{abbr|BWV|Bach-Werke-Verzeichnis (catalogue of Bach's works)}} \"six\".\n\nA single CD can contain the set of six motets plus other works. For example, [[Maasaki Suzuki]]'s 2009 recording on [[BIS Records|BIS]] includes [[O Jesu Christ, meins Lebens Licht, BWV 118|''O Jesu Christ, meins Lebens Licht'', BWV 118]] (which at one time was categorised as a cantata) and [[Ich lasse dich nicht, BWV Anh. 159|''Ich lasse dich nicht'', BWV Anh. 159]] (the authorship of which has been disputed).<ref name=\"BIS\">{{Cite web |url=https://bis.se/conductors/suzuki-masaaki/bach-motets |title=Bach Motets |website=bis.se (BIS Records) |access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref> The motets chosen for a particular recording can reflect the way the balance of opinion changes regarding the status of a particular work. This appears to be the case with the two sets by [[John Eliot Gardiner]] conducting the [[Monteverdi Choir]]. They recorded Bach's motets without {{nowrap|BWV Anh. 159}} in 1980, but included it in their 2011 live recording.<ref name=\"muzie\">[https://www.muziekweb.nl/en/Link/DBX11558 ''Bach: Motets''] and [https://www.muziekweb.nl/en/Link/DBX10438 ''Bach Motets''] at {{url|www.muziekweb.nl}}.</ref>\n\n== Types of choirs ==\nChoirs with [[one voice per part]] (OVPP) are used in some [[historically informed performance]]s of Bach. However, OVPP recordings of the motets are relatively rare. Exceptions include the [[Hilliard Ensemble]]'s second set,<ref name=\"Guardian\">{{Cite news |last=Clements |first=Andrew |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2007/may/18/classicalmusicandopera.shopping2 |title=Bach: Motets |date=18 May 2007 |work=The Guardian}}</ref> and [[Konrad Jungh\u00e4nel]] with the group Cantus C\u00f6lln.<ref name=\"Bach Cantatas6\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.bach-cantatas.com/Vocal/BWV225-231-Rec6.htm |title= Motets / Recordings \u2013 Part 6 |website=Bach Cantatas Website}}</ref>\n\nAt least some of the motets would have been first performed by singers from Leipzig's [[Thomanerchor]], which comprises boys and young men. This choir has recorded the motets (initially under [[G\u00fcnther Ramin]] in the 1950s),<ref name=\"Bach Cantatas2\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.bach-cantatas.com/Vocal/BWV225-231-Rec2.htm  |title= Motets / Recordings \u2013 Part 2 |website=Bach Cantatas Website}}</ref> as have other choirs with boys' voices such as the [[Choir of New College, Oxford]].<ref name=\"BachCantatas7\"/>\n\n== Instrumental accompaniment ==\nMusic directors need to make choices about the instrumental accompaniment, if any, to be used. One approach is to have instruments doubling the vocal lines, something which is described as playing ''[[colla parte]]''. The opposite approach is to be ''[[a cappella]]'', that is, without an accompaniment. It is also possible to have a compromise with some support for the singers from instruments such as an [[Organ (music)|organ]].\n\nSurviving sources do not make it clear what Bach's approach was to the accompaniment of most of these pieces. In the case of [[Der Geist hilft unser Schwachheit auf, BWV 226|''Der Geist hilft unser Schwachheit auf'', BWV 226]] orchestral parts are extant, indicating that choir I was doubled by strings and choir II by reeds (two [[oboe]]s, [[Taille (instrument)|taille]] and [[bassoon]]). There is also a [[basso continuo]] (separate [[violone]] and organ parts are provided) which underlies both choirs.<ref name=\"bachchoir\">{{Cite web |url=https://bach.org/education/motet-bwv-226/ |title=Motet BWV 226 |website=Bach Choir of Bethlehem |access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\nAn accompaniment is also specified for ''Lobet den Herrn''.<ref name=\"Leavis\">{{cite web | url= https://www.jstor.org/stable/731829| title=Bach's Setting of Psalm CXVII (BWV.230) | publisher=OUP | work=[[Music & Letters]]. Vol. 52, No. 1 | date=January 1971 | author=Leavis, Ralph}}  Accessed via JSTOR (subscription required)</ref>\n\nA tradition of performing the motets ''a capella'' is long-established,<ref name=\"MT\">Emery, W. (1974). Bach in Practice. [[The Musical Times]], 115(1578), 661-661. doi:10.2307/960490. Accessed via JSTOR (subscription required)</ref> and is reflected in the recordings. The Hilliard Ensemble's OVPP version is mainly ''a capella''. They omit the instrumental parts of ''Der Geist hilft unser Schwachheit auf'', but sing ''Lobet den Herrn'' to organ accompaniment.<ref name=\"Guardian\"/>\n\n== History ==\nThe first of the motets to be recorded was [[Jesu, meine Freude, BWV 227|''Jesu meine Freude'']] in 1927. This version was sung in English.<ref name=\"Bach Cantatas1\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.bach-cantatas.com/Vocal/BWV225-231-Rec1.htm|title= Motets / Recordings \u2013 Part 1 |website=Bach Cantatas Website}}</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\nIn 2010, Suzuki and his ensemble were given a French award ([[Diapason d'Or|Diapason d\u2019Or de l\u2019Ann\u00e9e]]) and a German award ([[Preis der deutschen Schallplattenkritik]]) for their recording of Bach motets on BIS.\n \nJohn Eliot Gardiner, who has won more [[Gramophone Classical Music Awards|Gramophone Awards]] than any other living artist, received one for his second recording of the motets with the Monteverdi Choir on SDG. It was one of the [[Gramophone_Classical_Music_Awards#2013|2013 awards]], the category being \"Baroque Vocal\".\n\nGrete Pedersen with the Norwegian choir [[Det Norske Solistkor]] won a Diapason d'Or in 2018 for their recording of the motets on BIS.\n\n== Discography ==\nThe intention has been to feature versions which are still available. The year given is that of recording. In the case of pre-1980s recordings, the date of reissue on CD can be significantly later than the original recording.\n{{Cantata discography header |work= Bach Motets |show_more=yes |more = Additional info}}\n{{Cantata discography row\n| id = Ramin\n| title = 6 Motetten<ref name=\"Bach Cantatas2\"/>\n| conductor = {{sortname|G\u00fcnther|Ramin}}\n| choir = [[Thomanerchor]]\n| instrumentalists =\n| soloists = {{plainlist|\n}}\n| label = [[Archiv]] (reissue)\n| year = 1950s\n| more =\n}}\n{{Cantata discography row\n| id = Christophers\n| title = The Six Motets<ref name=\"BachCantatas5\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.bach-cantatas.com/Vocal/BWV225-231-Rec5.htm|title= Motets / Recordings \u2013 Part 5 |website=Bach Cantatas Website}}</ref>\n| conductor = {{sortname|Harry|Christophers}}\n| choir = [[The Sixteen]]\n| instrumentalists =\n| soloists = {{plainlist|\n}}\n| label = [[Hyperion Records|Hyperion]]\n| year = 1989\n| more =\n}}\n{{Cantata discography row\n| id = \n| title = Bach Motetten\n| conductor = \n| choir = [[Hilliard Ensemble]]\n| instrumentalists =\n| soloists = {{plainlist|\n}}\n| label = [[ECM Records|ECM]]\n| year = 2003\n| more = second Hilliard recording\n}}\n{{Cantata discography row\n| id = Higginbottom\n| title = Bach Motets<ref name=\"BachCantatas7\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.bach-cantatas.com/Vocal/BWV225-231-Rec7.htm|title= Motets / Recordings \u2013 Part 7 |website=Bach Cantatas Website}}</ref>\n| conductor = [[Edward Higginbottom]]\n| choir = [[Choir of New College, Oxford]]\n| instrumentalists = organ\n| soloists = {{plainlist|\n}}\n| label = Novum<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.newcollegechoir.com/news/?pid=7&nid=1&storyid=12 |title=Recordings |website=Choir of New College, Oxford}}</ref>\n| year = 2008\n| more = organ accompaniment\n}}\n{{Cantata discography row\n| id = Suzuki\n| title = Bach Motets<ref name=\"BIS\"></ref>\n| conductor = {{sortname|Masaaki|Suzuki}}\n| choir = [[Bach Collegium Japan]]\n| instrumentalists =\n| soloists = {{plainlist|\n}}\n| label = [[BIS Records|BIS]]\n| year = 2009\n| more =\n}}\n{{Cantata discography row\n| id = Gardiner2\n| title =Bach Motets<ref name=\"muzie\"></ref>\n| conductor = {{sortname|John Eliot|Gardiner}}\n| choir = [[Monteverdi Choir]]\n| instrumentalists =\n| soloists = {{plainlist|\n}}\n| label = [[Soli Deo Gloria (record label)|SDG]]\n| year = 2011\n| more = second Gardiner recording\n}}\n{{Cantata discography row\n| id = Pedersen\n| title =\n| conductor = {{sortname|Grete|Pedersen}}\n| choir = [[Det Norske Solistkor|Norwegian Soloists' Choir]]\n| instrumentalists = Ensemble Allegria\n| soloists = {{plainlist|\n}}\n| label = BIS\n| year = 2017\n| more = \n}}\n{{End}}\n{{expand list|date=April 2020}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Discographies of compositions by J. S. Bach]]\n", "text_old": "This article includes a list of commercial recordings of the [[Motet (Bach)|motets]] of [[Johann Sebastian Bach]]. Bach motets have often been recorded as a set (typically comprising the six motets catalogued as BWV{{nbsp}}225-230).{{efn|\"BWV\" is [[Bach-Werke-Verzeichnis]], a thematic catalogue of Bach's works.}}  However, other motets are attributed to Bach and there is some doubt about the authorship of [[Lobet den Herrn, alle Heiden, BWV 230|''Lobet den Herrn, alle Heiden'', BWV 230]], one of the {{abbr|BWV|Bach-Werke-Verzeichnis (catalogue of Bach's works)}} \"six\".\n\nA single CD can contain the set of six motets plus other works. For example, [[Maasaki Suzuki]]'s 2009 recording on [[BIS Records|BIS]] includes [[O Jesu Christ, meins Lebens Licht, BWV 118|''O Jesu Christ, meins Lebens Licht'', BWV 118]] (which at one time was categorised as a cantata) and [[Ich lasse dich nicht, BWV Anh. 159|''Ich lasse dich nicht'', BWV Anh. 159]] (the authorship of which has been disputed).<ref name=\"BIS\">{{Cite web |url=https://bis.se/conductors/suzuki-masaaki/bach-motets |title=Bach Motets |website=bis.se (BIS Records) |access-date=6 April 2020}}</ref> The motets chosen for a particular recording can reflect the way the balance of opinion changes regarding the status of a particular work. This appears to be the case with the two sets by [[John Eliot Gardiner]] conducting the [[Monteverdi Choir]]. They recorded Bach's motets without {{nowrap|BWV Anh. 159}} in 1980, but included it in their 2011 live recording.<ref name=\"muzie\">[https://www.muziekweb.nl/en/Link/DBX11558 ''Bach: Motets''] and [https://www.muziekweb.nl/en/Link/DBX10438 ''Bach Motets''] at {{url|www.muziekweb.nl}}.</ref>\n\n== Types of choirs ==\nChoirs with [[one voice per part]] (OVPP) are used in some [[historically informed performance]]s of Bach. However, OVPP recordings of the motets are relatively rare. Exceptions include the [[Hilliard Ensemble]]'s second set,<ref name=\"Guardian\">{{Cite news |last=Clements |first=Andrew |url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2007/may/18/classicalmusicandopera.shopping2 |title=Bach: Motets |date=18 May 2007 |work=The Guardian}}</ref> and [[Konrad Jungh\u00e4nel]] with the group Cantus C\u00f6lln.<ref name=\"Bach Cantatas6\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.bach-cantatas.com/Vocal/BWV225-231-Rec6.htm |title= Motets / Recordings \u2013 Part 6 |website=Bach Cantatas Website}}</ref>\n\nAt least some of the motets would have been first performed by singers from Leipzig's [[Thomanerchor]], which comprises boys and young men. This choir has recorded the motets (initially under [[G\u00fcnther Ramin]] in the 1950s),<ref name=\"Bach Cantatas2\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.bach-cantatas.com/Vocal/BWV225-231-Rec2.htm  |title= Motets / Recordings \u2013 Part 2 |website=Bach Cantatas Website}}</ref> as have other choirs with boys' voices such as the [[Choir of New College, Oxford]].<ref name=\"BachCantatas7\"/>\n\n== Instrumental accompaniment ==\nMusic directors need to make choices about the instrumental accompaniment, if any, to be used. One approach is to have instruments doubling the vocal lines, something which is described as playing ''[[colla parte]]''. The opposite approach is to be ''[[a cappella]]'', that is, without an accompaniment. It is also possible to have a compromise with some support for the singers from instruments such as an [[Organ (music)|organ]].\n\nSurviving sources do not make it clear what Bach's approach was to the accompaniment of most of these pieces. In the case of [[Der Geist hilft unser Schwachheit auf, BWV 226|''Der Geist hilft unser Schwachheit auf'', BWV 226]] orchestral parts are extant, indicating that choir I was doubled by strings and choir II by reeds (two [[oboe]]s, [[Taille (instrument)|taille]] and [[bassoon]]). There is also a [[basso continuo]] (separate [[violone]] and organ parts are provided) which underlies both choirs.<ref name=\"bachchoir\">{{Cite web |url=https://bach.org/education/motet-bwv-226/ |title=Motet BWV 226 |website=Bach Choir of Bethlehem |access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\nAn accompaniment is also specified for ''Lobet den Herrn''.<ref name=\"Leavis\">{{cite web | url= https://www.jstor.org/stable/731829| title=Bach's Setting of Psalm CXVII (BWV.230) | publisher=OUP | work=[[Music & Letters]]. Vol. 52, No. 1 | date=January 1971 | author=Leavis, Ralph}}  Accessed via JSTOR (subscription required)</ref>\n\nA tradition of performing the motets ''a capella'' is long-established, and is reflected in the recordings.<ref name=\"MT\">Emery, W. (1974). Bach in Practice. [[The Musical Times]], 115(1578), 661-661. doi:10.2307/960490. Accessed via JSTOR (subscription required)</ref> The Hilliard Ensemble's OVPP version is mainly ''a capella''. They omit the instrumental parts of ''Der Geist hilft unser Schwachheit auf'', but sing ''Lobet den Herrn'' to organ accompaniment.<ref name=\"Guardian\"/>\n\n== History ==\nThe first of the motets to be recorded was [[Jesu, meine Freude, BWV 227|''Jesu meine Freude'']] in 1927. This version was sung in English.<ref name=\"Bach Cantatas1\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.bach-cantatas.com/Vocal/BWV225-231-Rec1.htm|title= Motets / Recordings \u2013 Part 1 |website=Bach Cantatas Website}}</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\nIn 2010, Suzuki and his ensemble were given a French award ([[Diapason d'Or|Diapason d\u2019Or de l\u2019Ann\u00e9e]]) and a German award ([[Preis der deutschen Schallplattenkritik]]) for their recording of Bach motets on BIS.\n \nJohn Eliot Gardiner, who has won more [[Gramophone Classical Music Awards|Gramophone Awards]] than any other living artist, received one for his second recording of the motets with the Monteverdi Choir on SDG. It was one of the [[Gramophone_Classical_Music_Awards#2013|2013 awards]], the category being \"Baroque Vocal\".\n\nGrete Pedersen with the Norwegian choir [[Det Norske Solistkor]] won a Diapason d'Or in 2018 for their recording of the motets on BIS.\n\n== Discography ==\nThe intention has been to feature versions which are still available. The year given is that of recording. In the case of pre-1980s recordings, the date of reissue on CD can be significantly later than the original recording.\n{{Cantata discography header |work= Bach Motets |show_more=yes |more = Additional info}}\n{{Cantata discography row\n| id = Ramin\n| title = 6 Motetten<ref name=\"Bach Cantatas2\"/>\n| conductor = {{sortname|G\u00fcnther|Ramin}}\n| choir = [[Thomanerchor]]\n| instrumentalists =\n| soloists = {{plainlist|\n}}\n| label = [[Archiv]] (reissue)\n| year = 1950s\n| more =\n}}\n{{Cantata discography row\n| id = Christophers\n| title = The Six Motets<ref name=\"BachCantatas5\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.bach-cantatas.com/Vocal/BWV225-231-Rec5.htm|title= Motets / Recordings \u2013 Part 5 |website=Bach Cantatas Website}}</ref>\n| conductor = {{sortname|Harry|Christophers}}\n| choir = [[The Sixteen]]\n| instrumentalists =\n| soloists = {{plainlist|\n}}\n| label = [[Hyperion Records|Hyperion]]\n| year = 1989\n| more =\n}}\n{{Cantata discography row\n| id = \n| title = Bach Motetten\n| conductor = \n| choir = [[Hilliard Ensemble]]\n| instrumentalists =\n| soloists = {{plainlist|\n}}\n| label = [[ECM Records|ECM]]\n| year = 2003\n| more = second Hilliard recording\n}}\n{{Cantata discography row\n| id = Higginbottom\n| title = Bach Motets<ref name=\"BachCantatas7\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.bach-cantatas.com/Vocal/BWV225-231-Rec7.htm|title= Motets / Recordings \u2013 Part 7 |website=Bach Cantatas Website}}</ref>\n| conductor = [[Edward Higginbottom]]\n| choir = [[Choir of New College, Oxford]]\n| instrumentalists = organ\n| soloists = {{plainlist|\n}}\n| label = Novum<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.newcollegechoir.com/news/?pid=7&nid=1&storyid=12 |title=Recordings |website=Choir of New College, Oxford}}</ref>\n| year = 2008\n| more = organ accompaniment\n}}\n{{Cantata discography row\n| id = Suzuki\n| title = Bach Motets<ref name=\"BIS\"></ref>\n| conductor = {{sortname|Masaaki|Suzuki}}\n| choir = [[Bach Collegium Japan]]\n| instrumentalists =\n| soloists = {{plainlist|\n}}\n| label = [[BIS Records|BIS]]\n| year = 2009\n| more =\n}}\n{{Cantata discography row\n| id = Gardiner2\n| title =Bach Motets<ref name=\"muzie\"></ref>\n| conductor = {{sortname|John Eliot|Gardiner}}\n| choir = [[Monteverdi Choir]]\n| instrumentalists =\n| soloists = {{plainlist|\n}}\n| label = [[Soli Deo Gloria (record label)|SDG]]\n| year = 2011\n| more = second Gardiner recording\n}}\n{{Cantata discography row\n| id = Pedersen\n| title =\n| conductor = {{sortname|Grete|Pedersen}}\n| choir = [[Det Norske Solistkor|Norwegian Soloists' Choir]]\n| instrumentalists = Ensemble Allegria\n| soloists = {{plainlist|\n}}\n| label = BIS\n| year = 2017\n| more = \n}}\n{{End}}\n{{expand list|date=April 2020}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Discographies of compositions by J. S. Bach]]\n", "name_user": "Thoughtfortheday", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eInstrumental accompaniment:move ref", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Motets_by_Johann_Sebastian_Bach,_discography"}
